WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.633 --> 00:00:04.999
DVD commentary

2
00:00:04.633 --> 00:00:06.999
Welcome. This is Chris Weitz.
director of New Moon.

3
00:00:07.069 --> 00:00:12.974
I have with me. by magic.
from London. Peter Lambert.

4
00:00:13.042 --> 00:00:17.342
my accomplice in crime.
the editor of New Moon.

5
00:00:17.413 --> 00:00:18.471
PETER LAMBERT: Hello.

6
00:00:19.348 --> 00:00:21.441
WEITZ: That was the Summit logo. delightful.

7
00:00:22.384 --> 00:00:25.683
Now. part of the reason that...
Okay. here's a moon.

8
00:00:25.754 --> 00:00:26.846
(LAMBERT LAUGHING)

9
00:00:26.922 --> 00:00:32.451
Now. the reason that we started this way
was because I felt that in the theaters.

10
00:00:32.528 --> 00:00:38.125
there would be nothing but screaming
for about the first 30 seconds of the movie.

11
00:00:38.967 --> 00:00:43.336
And so. interesting point. actually.

12
00:00:43.405 --> 00:00:45.771
this is the proper way that a moon phases.

13
00:00:45.841 --> 00:00:47.809
from right to left.
in the northern hemisphere.

14
00:00:47.876 --> 00:00:52.006
and I know this because
I was at a science and film conference

15
00:00:52.081 --> 00:00:56.415
in which someone complained that
they'd gotten it wrong in every film ever.

16
00:00:57.653 --> 00:01:02.386
Ironically. though. it reads like
a palindrome. Noom Wen. not New Moon.

17
00:01:02.458 --> 00:01:05.689
LAMBERT: This actually took the DP
an entire month to film.

18
00:01:06.028 --> 00:01:09.361
He had to stand very still with the camera
pointing at the sky all that time.

19
00:01:09.431 --> 00:01:10.557
(WEITZ LAUGHING)

20
00:01:10.632 --> 00:01:12.532
It's not actually true.

21
00:01:12.601 --> 00:01:16.401
WEITZ: Okay. so then in pops the sun.
Here comes Bella.

22
00:01:16.472 --> 00:01:20.909
and this is like in the book
where she is seeing the clock at 12:00.

23
00:01:20.976 --> 00:01:22.841
It's her worst nightmare.

24
00:01:25.247 --> 00:01:28.614
Yes. and then we use
that red flag as what we call a wipe

25
00:01:28.684 --> 00:01:31.118
to transition us into the meadow.

26
00:01:31.186 --> 00:01:32.244
Now here we are in the meadow.

27
00:01:32.321 --> 00:01:35.381
and those things on the right
are called god rays by the CGI people.

28
00:01:35.457 --> 00:01:38.893
-LAMBERT: They're beautiful.
-They're beautiful. but they're not real.

29
00:01:39.495 --> 00:01:43.192
More god rays.
We see Gran in the distance out of focus.

30
00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:49.599
LAMBERT: I remember we talked about how
there was Team Jacob and Team Edward.

31
00:01:49.671 --> 00:01:53.539
I always wanted to mount a campaign
for Team Gran. based on this scene.

32
00:01:53.609 --> 00:01:56.077
for the more mature
gentlemen Twilight fans.

33
00:01:56.145 --> 00:01:59.080
They could go to conventions
and support Team Gran.

34
00:01:59.148 --> 00:02:01.946
WEITZ: It was a demographic
we were trying to hit desperately.

35
00:02:02.017 --> 00:02:03.746
I'm not sure that we've managed to do that.

36
00:02:03.819 --> 00:02:05.616
LAMBERT: (LAUGHING) Hit them hard
at the start of the movie.

37
00:02:05.687 --> 00:02:08.417
WEITZ: Okay.
first diamond shot of the movie.

38
00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:11.687
Pretty good. I think.
as far as our diamond shots go.

39
00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:14.320
Some are better. I think.
when we get to Italy.

40
00:02:14.396 --> 00:02:19.459
but. obviously. this was a very big deal
to kind of re-imagine the diamond shots

41
00:02:19.535 --> 00:02:24.404
and get the effect
both of subsurface scattering.

42
00:02:24.473 --> 00:02:26.407
which is the light under the skin.

43
00:02:26.475 --> 00:02:30.969
and also to have these rays of light
coming out.

44
00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:33.539
LAMBERT: You guys looked at lots
of references. didn't you?

45
00:02:33.615 --> 00:02:35.708
I remember there were loads of diamonds
and things like that.

46
00:02:35.784 --> 00:02:38.719
WEITZ: We did. and it turns out diamonds
don't actually scatter light outwards.

47
00:02:38.787 --> 00:02:41.688
but people think they do.
So that's what we did.

48
00:02:41.757 --> 00:02:44.783
And in fact. when we first shot this.

49
00:02:45.961 --> 00:02:49.988
Rob had these kind of black dots
all over his face to mark positions.

50
00:02:50.065 --> 00:02:51.794
and he looked like a plague victim.

51
00:02:51.867 --> 00:02:52.891
(LAMBERT LAUGHING)

52
00:02:52.968 --> 00:02:57.701
If you can imagine Rob ever. ever looking
not incredibly super handsome.

53
00:02:57.773 --> 00:02:59.673
that might be the time.

54
00:02:59.741 --> 00:03:02.904
LAMBERT: The shot coming out of the mirror.
that was like a...

55
00:03:02.978 --> 00:03:04.639
We made a mistake with
that visual effect originally.

56
00:03:04.713 --> 00:03:07.147
We forgot that Edward's not meant
to sparkle in it to start with.

57
00:03:07.216 --> 00:03:09.684
I seem to remember.
And then we got a note from Stephenie

58
00:03:09.751 --> 00:03:12.117
saying he shouldn't be sparkling
in the reflection.

59
00:03:12.187 --> 00:03:13.279
WEITZ: Wow. this film is going quickly.

60
00:03:13.355 --> 00:03:16.085
Okay. notice in the book here on the left

61
00:03:16.158 --> 00:03:19.958
that you see Montepulciano.
or rather Volterra.

62
00:03:20.028 --> 00:03:23.896
in the illustration
of the Romeo and Juliet book.

63
00:03:24.666 --> 00:03:26.861
LAMBERT: That took me about 2 months
before I noticed that.

64
00:03:26.935 --> 00:03:28.027
(WEITZ LAUGHING)

65
00:03:29.238 --> 00:03:31.968
WEITZ: Bella doesn't seem very grateful
about her presents. I don't know why.

66
00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:33.974
I think Kristen was in a bad mood that day.

67
00:03:34.042 --> 00:03:35.976
By the way. the reason
that the kids aren't here today

68
00:03:36.044 --> 00:03:39.377
is because at the after party
for the premiere.

69
00:03:40.115 --> 00:03:42.583
they ordered some burgers. right.
They took quite a while to come.

70
00:03:42.651 --> 00:03:48.886
and they left them sitting there.
and I think I ate Kristen's hamburger.

71
00:03:48.957 --> 00:03:50.925
and when she came back. it was all gone.

72
00:03:50.993 --> 00:03:53.553
So there's a bit of
an actor revolt against me.

73
00:03:53.629 --> 00:03:56.223
which is why I had to call in Peter.

74
00:03:57.666 --> 00:04:01.102
The old gray hair joke. He slays them.

75
00:04:01.203 --> 00:04:02.397
(LAMBERT LAUGHING)

76
00:04:02.471 --> 00:04:04.029
Happy birthday.

77
00:04:04.539 --> 00:04:06.473
-WEITZ: Lovely Billy Burke.
-He's great.

78
00:04:06.541 --> 00:04:09.874
WEITZ: Very funny and not as old
as his mustache would imply.

79
00:04:09.945 --> 00:04:11.378
Actually quite a sexy young guy.

80
00:04:11.446 --> 00:04:12.470
if I do say so.

81
00:04:12.547 --> 00:04:13.809
LAMBERT: It's amazing
how a'tache can age a man.

82
00:04:13.882 --> 00:04:15.179
WEITZ: Yeah. it is. It is.

83
00:04:15.250 --> 00:04:18.981
I think when I want to look more
sophisticated. I'm gonna wear one.

84
00:04:19.721 --> 00:04:23.122
LAMBERT: This top shot
of the truck is the sort of...

85
00:04:23.191 --> 00:04:24.658
It was not the top shot
of the truck anymore.

86
00:04:24.726 --> 00:04:27.126
I just realized from
the dialogue I'm hearing.

87
00:04:27.195 --> 00:04:29.959
But it's the one little bit
that reminds me of Twilight.

88
00:04:30.032 --> 00:04:32.193
It's like the start of Twilight. that shot.

89
00:04:32.334 --> 00:04:35.428
-Oh. yeah.
-Wherefore art thou. Bella?

90
00:04:35.504 --> 00:04:36.596
(ALL LAUGH)

91
00:04:36.672 --> 00:04:40.335
Let me take a picture of you guys.
My mom wants me to put together. like.

92
00:04:40.409 --> 00:04:41.637
a scrapbook full of memories.

93
00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:42.734
ERIC: Oh.
MIKE: Cool. Yeah.

94
00:04:42.811 --> 00:04:44.039
I take them. I'm not in them.

95
00:04:44.112 --> 00:04:45.511
-No. no. no. come here.
-BELLA: Well. you are today.

96
00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:47.104
You'll photoshop this
if my nose looks big. right?

97
00:04:47.182 --> 00:04:48.809
ERIC: Don't worry. I'm in the picture.
No one will...

98
00:04:48.884 --> 00:04:53.844
WEITZ: Volvo. one of our sponsors.
offered us a new car for Edward.

99
00:04:54.156 --> 00:05:00.026
and I thought. well. if I leave the car
the same color as before. you know.

100
00:05:00.095 --> 00:05:01.824
people are gonna think
that I'm treating them like idiots.

101
00:05:01.897 --> 00:05:04.525
like they can't tell the difference
between one model of car and another.

102
00:05:04.599 --> 00:05:05.691
So I thought. well. we'll make it black.

103
00:05:05.767 --> 00:05:08.167
We won't make it too glossy black.
It'll be kind of coal black.

104
00:05:08.236 --> 00:05:11.137
and that'll show depression and sorrow.

105
00:05:23.018 --> 00:05:27.352
And. yes. and here comes dream boat.

106
00:05:27.622 --> 00:05:30.090
Bella. your birth is definitely
something to celebrate.

107
00:05:30.158 --> 00:05:31.489
Yeah. but my aging's not.

108
00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:34.495
WEITZ: And for the longest time.
Peter thought he said.

109
00:05:34.563 --> 00:05:36.827
"Your breath is something to celebrate. "
not "your birth. "

110
00:05:36.898 --> 00:05:38.126
LAMBERT: I thought it was just creepy.

111
00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:42.102
WEITZ: Yeah. well. she does have
very good breath. I'm sure. Bella.

112
00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:43.364
but it was her birth.

113
00:05:43.438 --> 00:05:46.839
LAMBERT: Yeah. I kind of like that

114
00:05:46.908 --> 00:05:49.433
sort of slow motion shot
of him walking towards Kristen.

115
00:05:49.511 --> 00:05:53.709
When we saw it with an audience
at the premiere for the first time.

116
00:05:53.782 --> 00:05:55.613
everyone cheered when Rob came on.

117
00:05:55.684 --> 00:05:58.209
and then almost like
a perfect response to them cheering.

118
00:05:58.286 --> 00:06:00.311
he does that little
sort of self-effacing smile

119
00:06:00.389 --> 00:06:03.017
and looks down like
he's actually responding to the audience.

120
00:06:03.091 --> 00:06:04.456
It was good timing.

121
00:06:04.526 --> 00:06:06.153
WEITZ: I have to say.
I have to take credit for it.

122
00:06:06.228 --> 00:06:07.991
I always knew that was gonna happen.

123
00:06:08.063 --> 00:06:12.022
and I knew that his smile
would almost seem to be in response

124
00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:14.591
-to an audience actually reacting to him.
-LAMBERT: You're pretty clever.

125
00:06:14.669 --> 00:06:18.105
WEITZ: Okay. now this is another example
of my genius. In that 2-shot.

126
00:06:18.173 --> 00:06:22.667
when Jacob comes into the 2-shot.
he completely blocks out Edward.

127
00:06:22.744 --> 00:06:25.304
showing the possibility
that he may be a threat to him.

128
00:06:25.380 --> 00:06:27.473
LAMBERT: Is that
what they call foreshadowing

129
00:06:27.549 --> 00:06:29.244
-in the directing business?
-WEITZ: Yes. it is. actually.

130
00:06:29.317 --> 00:06:34.220
Yeah. in the directing biz.
we call it "being really obvious. "

131
00:06:34.289 --> 00:06:35.779
(BOTH LAUGHING)

132
00:06:35.857 --> 00:06:39.725
No. we were shooting this
over the course of an entire day and...

133
00:06:39.795 --> 00:06:41.126
LAMBERT: This was a monster to shoot.

134
00:06:41.196 --> 00:06:43.756
WEITZ: Yeah. in Vancouver.

135
00:06:43.832 --> 00:06:46.596
And the light conditions were changing.

136
00:06:46.668 --> 00:06:51.071
so what you do is in the DI.
which is the digital intermediate

137
00:06:51.139 --> 00:06:54.939
where you can manipulate colors
and light variations.

138
00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:58.138
we made it as even as possible.
so that it didn't seem like a sunny day

139
00:06:58.213 --> 00:07:00.579
and that Edward should be glowing and all.

140
00:07:00.649 --> 00:07:02.913
And... Oh. poor Edward.

141
00:07:02.984 --> 00:07:06.476
Edward. yeah. in some way. senses

142
00:07:06.555 --> 00:07:11.515
that Jacob might be a better match
for Bella.

143
00:07:11.927 --> 00:07:15.294
and so. to me. he's a bit sad here.

144
00:07:15.630 --> 00:07:19.361
And here. me being obvious again.
when Jacob talks about bad dreams

145
00:07:19.434 --> 00:07:26.237
and lifts the dream catcher.
it's practically obscuring Edward.

146
00:07:27.008 --> 00:07:30.102
And I've often thought how this is
very much like the Brady Bunch episode

147
00:07:30.178 --> 00:07:31.736
where the tiki is introduced.

148
00:07:31.813 --> 00:07:34.441
You could actually say that
this movie is about what happens

149
00:07:34.516 --> 00:07:38.213
when Jacob gives Bella
an evil dream catcher

150
00:07:38.286 --> 00:07:40.846
and everything starts to go wrong
in her life.

151
00:07:40.922 --> 00:07:43.254
LAMBERT: We should have changed
the music for that to a kind of...

152
00:07:43.325 --> 00:07:45.623
(LAMBERT MIMICKING DRAMATIC MUSIC)

153
00:07:45.694 --> 00:07:46.922
... when he brought it out.

154
00:07:46.995 --> 00:07:48.360
(WEITZ LAUGHING)

155
00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:55.069
WEITZ: Hello. Alice. Here she comes.
People cheer.

156
00:07:55.136 --> 00:07:58.867
-LAMBERT: She's just been in the art class.
-Yes. lovely smock. Alice.

157
00:08:00.075 --> 00:08:03.806
And there's old Jackson
hanging back there.

158
00:08:03.879 --> 00:08:05.608
Now. there is some controversy

159
00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:11.482
over whether Jasper's mood control powers

160
00:08:11.553 --> 00:08:15.580
could actually work on Bella. given that
she's so resistant to vampire powers.

161
00:08:15.657 --> 00:08:21.425
but it turns out that Jasper's powers work
on her adrenal glands. not on her brain.

162
00:08:21.496 --> 00:08:23.487
Therefore. it can calm her down.

163
00:08:23.565 --> 00:08:26.261
which is why she found herself
willing to agree to go

164
00:08:26.334 --> 00:08:30.202
to this gathering at the Cullens'.
so that's why. really.

165
00:08:31.373 --> 00:08:34.638
You can't trust vampires. Trust me.

166
00:08:35.076 --> 00:08:37.772
WEITZ: And this was an ad-lib by Rob.
which he subsequently hated.

167
00:08:37.846 --> 00:08:39.973
but I think it's quite nice.

168
00:08:40.749 --> 00:08:43.183
...hath had no power yet upon thy beauty.

169
00:08:44.352 --> 00:08:46.217
Thou art not conquered.

170
00:08:47.689 --> 00:08:51.591
Beauty's ensign yet is crimson
in thy lips and in thy cheeks.

171
00:08:52.427 --> 00:08:55.294
And death's pale flag is not advanced there.

172
00:08:55.363 --> 00:08:57.331
BELLA: I hate being celebrated.

173
00:08:58.033 --> 00:09:00.968
EDWARD: There are worse tragedies.
I mean. look at Romeo.

174
00:09:01.036 --> 00:09:04.005
Killed his true love out of sheer stupidity.

175
00:09:05.907 --> 00:09:06.999
BELLA: Yeah.

176
00:09:07.509 --> 00:09:09.670
Though I do envy him one thing.

177
00:09:11.546 --> 00:09:13.605
BELLA: Juliet is. like. perfect.

178
00:09:13.682 --> 00:09:16.947
If you like
that obviously beautiful sort of thing.

179
00:09:17.052 --> 00:09:18.417
(EDWARD LAUGHS)

180
00:09:20.221 --> 00:09:23.156
Not the girl. the suicide.

181
00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:30.830
WEITZ: Now. here's this kind of rather odd
discussion about suicide where

182
00:09:31.399 --> 00:09:35.335
Edward is surprisingly upbeat
about the notion.

183
00:09:36.471 --> 00:09:40.430
And I thought it was an interesting way
for them to play it.

184
00:09:42.243 --> 00:09:46.771
I mean. for him. the idea of dying
has its own sort of appeal.

185
00:09:46.848 --> 00:09:49.373
except that he'd have
to say goodbye to Bella.

186
00:09:49.451 --> 00:09:53.285
But as an immortal who has doubts
about his own soul.

187
00:09:53.355 --> 00:09:57.314
the idea of ending his existence
is less upsetting

188
00:09:57.392 --> 00:10:00.828
than it is to Bella who. of course.
can't stand the notion.

189
00:10:01.563 --> 00:10:04.327
Flashback to Twilight. and we're back.

190
00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:07.295
What was the plan?

191
00:10:08.436 --> 00:10:10.768
WEITZ: Moment of silence
as I think of what to say.

192
00:10:10.839 --> 00:10:15.469
Anyway. I quite enjoy
Rob's performance here.

193
00:10:16.144 --> 00:10:22.549
and I can't let a sentimental moment go by
without interrupting it with a bit of comedy.

194
00:10:23.718 --> 00:10:27.415
So. Mr. Berty messes with Edward.

195
00:10:28.123 --> 00:10:29.920
and the entire class turns.

196
00:10:29.991 --> 00:10:34.394
and then suddenly we realize
that vampires have perfect recall.

197
00:10:35.230 --> 00:10:39.189
So. for him. he's been through high school
a bunch of times.

198
00:10:39.267 --> 00:10:41.394
Probably everyone who's listening to this.
by the way. is like.

199
00:10:41.469 --> 00:10:43.403
"Shut up and just let me listen to Rob. "

200
00:10:43.471 --> 00:10:46.668
but you can just turn this off
and watch the regular DVD.

201
00:10:46.741 --> 00:10:49.209
LAMBERT: This is a classic
Edward Cullen moment. I think.

202
00:10:49.277 --> 00:10:51.575
and I remember we actually experimented.

203
00:10:51.646 --> 00:10:54.274
we flirted with cutting it out
in order to get through

204
00:10:54.349 --> 00:10:56.340
to the next section of the movie
as quickly as possible.

205
00:10:56.418 --> 00:11:00.081
but we realized it was a mistake.
'cause Rob completely nails it.

206
00:11:00.155 --> 00:11:03.921
WEITZ: Well. and also. this is not in the book.
but I think Stephenie rather liked it.

207
00:11:04.125 --> 00:11:06.457
and that's actually one of the fun things
of working with Stephenie

208
00:11:06.528 --> 00:11:09.725
is that occasionally you come up
with a little bit that she likes.

209
00:11:09.798 --> 00:11:13.234
and she's like. "That's a really cool idea.
Let's have more of that. "

210
00:11:13.301 --> 00:11:16.964
So. now we're in Carlisle's room.
and you can see sort of the...

211
00:11:17.038 --> 00:11:20.974
Well. inside his room.
you'll see later all of the art

212
00:11:21.042 --> 00:11:24.978
that he's accumulated throughout his life.
but here come the Volturi.

213
00:11:25.046 --> 00:11:28.675
LAMBERT: Can you explain how
the painting was done. this visual effect?

214
00:11:28.750 --> 00:11:30.513
WEITZ: I can't explain it. It's magic.

215
00:11:30.585 --> 00:11:31.916
(BOTH LAUGHING)

216
00:11:31.986 --> 00:11:34.648
Oh. my God. how did we do it?

217
00:11:34.723 --> 00:11:38.716
Well. first we had an idea of what the
painting's dimensions were gonna be like.

218
00:11:38.793 --> 00:11:42.126
but there's a big green screen that they're
looking at as they're talking about it.

219
00:11:42.197 --> 00:11:43.721
and saying. "Is Carlisle there?"

220
00:11:43.798 --> 00:11:49.430
Then we shot the actual performance
of the Volturi later.

221
00:11:49.504 --> 00:11:53.099
and then we chose a starting frame.
freeze-frame.

222
00:11:53.742 --> 00:11:58.145
which was then painted by the painter
as a separate oil painting.

223
00:11:58.213 --> 00:12:01.649
which was then composited
into the green screen in the first place.

224
00:12:01.716 --> 00:12:07.348
So. really very. very complicated.
and a lot of other people doing hard work.

225
00:12:07.422 --> 00:12:09.413
which is how I like it.

226
00:12:11.025 --> 00:12:15.018
There's the wonderful
Christopher Heyerdahl. Canadian actor.

227
00:12:15.096 --> 00:12:17.189
amazing face. fantastic performer.

228
00:12:17.265 --> 00:12:22.430
and. of course. Jamie Campbell Bower.
who shocked people by saying that

229
00:12:22.504 --> 00:12:25.473
the Volturi scenes were going
to be shot in the nude.

230
00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:29.306
and then I had to go online to convince
people that that was not gonna happen.

231
00:12:29.377 --> 00:12:30.935
(BOTH LAUGHING)

232
00:12:31.012 --> 00:12:34.140
At any rate. Carlisle really shouldn't have
been hanging around with the Volturi.

233
00:12:34.215 --> 00:12:36.115
given that he doesn't seem
to hold the same ideas

234
00:12:36.184 --> 00:12:40.518
about capital punishment as they do.
but such is life.

235
00:12:40.588 --> 00:12:43.079
-LAMBERT: That's why he went to Forks.
-Yeah.

236
00:12:43.825 --> 00:12:45.588
LAMBERT: What was the name
of the rogue vampire. the actor?

237
00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:49.357
-He had a great name. I remember.
-WEITZ: Curtis Caravaggio is his name.

238
00:12:49.430 --> 00:12:51.557
-It's a fantastic name.
-LAMBERT: Great name. great guy.

239
00:12:51.633 --> 00:12:54.761
WEITZ: Yeah. great guy.
didn't mind getting his head torn off.

240
00:12:54.869 --> 00:12:56.598
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

241
00:12:56.671 --> 00:12:59.538
He was willing to end his career
on that one moment.

242
00:12:59.607 --> 00:13:03.407
No. just kidding. he's still alive.
Hire him. He's brilliant.

243
00:13:05.446 --> 00:13:10.474
(IN FRENCH ACCENT) Now. what do we have
to say here? It's a beautiful love scene.

244
00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:14.681
But it's my job to protect you.

245
00:13:14.756 --> 00:13:17.316
LAMBERT: This was a Chris Weitz line.
I remember. you were proud of this.

246
00:13:17.392 --> 00:13:18.484
-WEITZ: Is it?
-Yeah.

247
00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:19.788
WEITZ: What. "It's my job to protect you"?

248
00:13:19.861 --> 00:13:22.625
LAMBERT: Yeah. "It's my job to protect you
from everything except my sister. "

249
00:13:22.697 --> 00:13:23.925
WEITZ: No. no. I think
that was in the script.

250
00:13:23.998 --> 00:13:26.193
LAMBERT: Was it? Maybe the line before
was a Chris Weitz line.

251
00:13:26.267 --> 00:13:28.462
There was something you were proud about
in that area.

252
00:13:28.536 --> 00:13:31.164
WEITZ: (CHUCKLES)
Well. I'm a prideful person.

253
00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:32.729
All right. now we arranged this shot.

254
00:13:32.807 --> 00:13:37.574
which is Bella's POV. as kind of
almost like a conversation piece.

255
00:13:37.645 --> 00:13:39.977
which is a certain 18th century
kind of painting

256
00:13:40.048 --> 00:13:43.814
where a family is arranged
in a very specific way.

257
00:13:43.885 --> 00:13:47.878
and our wonderful cinematographer.
Javier Aguirresarobe.

258
00:13:47.956 --> 00:13:52.825
lit this in such a way that
it's kind of got a lovely golden mood to it.

259
00:13:53.394 --> 00:13:57.524
and part of our intention
was to make the colors in this film

260
00:13:57.599 --> 00:14:00.159
much more golden and red and warm

261
00:14:00.235 --> 00:14:03.932
than in the first film
just to kind of switch things up.

262
00:14:04.005 --> 00:14:07.497
And also because I think there's
a sort of an epic romantic feel to this.

263
00:14:07.575 --> 00:14:12.274
and I wanted things to look
like a Pre-Raphaelite painting.

264
00:14:12.847 --> 00:14:16.044
Look it up on Wikipedia. "Pre-Raphaelites. "

265
00:14:17.151 --> 00:14:19.312
LAMBERT: That's what I did.
That's what Javier did.

266
00:14:19.387 --> 00:14:20.445
WEITZ: Yeah.

267
00:14:20.521 --> 00:14:21.818
(BOTH LAUGHING)

268
00:14:23.358 --> 00:14:25.326
LAMBERT: This was the first night
of night shooting. wasn't it?

269
00:14:25.393 --> 00:14:27.725
WEITZ: Yeah. and the funny thing was.
about halfway through the night.

270
00:14:27.795 --> 00:14:29.228
I realized that most of the shots
were against walls.

271
00:14:29.297 --> 00:14:31.265
so we could have shot this during the day.

272
00:14:31.332 --> 00:14:35.632
and because Javier and I

273
00:14:35.703 --> 00:14:39.104
were communicating
through high school French.

274
00:14:39.173 --> 00:14:41.937
because he speaks mostly Spanish
and I speak mostly English.

275
00:14:42.010 --> 00:14:43.637
there had been a misunderstanding.

276
00:14:43.711 --> 00:14:46.271
And there we were.
in the middle of the night.

277
00:14:46.347 --> 00:14:49.180
really not having to be there. so sleepless.

278
00:14:49.250 --> 00:14:51.445
Okay. big moment.

279
00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:54.454
Woops. World's worst paper cut.

280
00:14:54.522 --> 00:14:55.853
(WEITZ EXCLAIMING)

281
00:14:56.724 --> 00:14:58.783
What can we say about this?

282
00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:03.024
You will notice.
this is giving away all of the magic.

283
00:15:03.097 --> 00:15:05.759
that in a lot of these stunt scenes.
people are looking away.

284
00:15:05.833 --> 00:15:09.269
and that's because
they are not the actual actors.

285
00:15:09.337 --> 00:15:12.829
They are the stunt actors. the stuntcators.

286
00:15:12.907 --> 00:15:14.932
LAMBERT: I've got to say.
they were pretty convincing. though.

287
00:15:15.009 --> 00:15:17.307
-WEITZ: Yeah. they were very good.
-Jasper's double looked amazing.

288
00:15:17.378 --> 00:15:19.778
WEITZ: I love that shot. by the way.
where she's looking up

289
00:15:19.847 --> 00:15:25.080
and her hair is kind of mussed in such
a way that it curls up around her eye.

290
00:15:25.553 --> 00:15:31.788
Now. when Carlisle rushes over to Bella.
it's called a whip pan.

291
00:15:31.859 --> 00:15:34.692
and it's a very. very old-fashioned way

292
00:15:34.762 --> 00:15:37.162
of showing someone
getting somewhere quickly.

293
00:15:37.231 --> 00:15:42.225
There's no CGI involved. You just take
the camera. whip it quickly off someone.

294
00:15:42.303 --> 00:15:44.965
and then later sit them down
and whip it onto them.

295
00:15:45.039 --> 00:15:46.563
It looks like they've moved very quickly.

296
00:15:46.641 --> 00:15:51.578
So. part of the issue in this movie
was how to establish vampire speed

297
00:15:53.314 --> 00:15:57.774
and make it realistic and fun and dynamic.

298
00:15:58.186 --> 00:16:00.450
And part of it was to just do it in camera.

299
00:16:00.521 --> 00:16:03.319
Okay. so that's a Hogarth engraving.
by the way.

300
00:16:03.391 --> 00:16:06.258
More art for you guys.
I know you're big art fans.

301
00:16:06.894 --> 00:16:09.454
That is part of The Rake's Progress.

302
00:16:10.198 --> 00:16:12.666
And you'll see throughout Carlisle's study.

303
00:16:12.734 --> 00:16:19.105
there's a Tibetan Buddhist Thangka.
spelled T-H-A-N-G-K-A.

304
00:16:19.574 --> 00:16:22.270
I mean. I know there are a lot
of Thangka fans out there

305
00:16:22.343 --> 00:16:24.470
who are really pleased about that.

306
00:16:24.545 --> 00:16:29.983
The Dalai Lama. huge Twihard fan.
so he will definitely appreciate that.

307
00:16:30.051 --> 00:16:32.042
LAMBERT: It's actually product placement
from the Dalai Lama.

308
00:16:32.120 --> 00:16:34.953
-WEITZ: (LAUGHS) Yeah.
-He paid a lot of money for that.

309
00:16:35.823 --> 00:16:40.954
WEITZ: He said that our next incarnation
would be much better if we just put it in.

310
00:16:42.096 --> 00:16:47.432
Lovely little moment. actually.
between Peter and Kristen.

311
00:16:48.469 --> 00:16:52.303
I like these sort of scenes
where characters are interacting

312
00:16:52.373 --> 00:16:55.467
in a way you wouldn't necessarily expect.

313
00:16:55.543 --> 00:16:58.774
and it's a nice fatherly sort of moment.

314
00:16:58.846 --> 00:17:01.838
LAMBERT: The music is also appropriate
in this scene. Sorry to interrupt. Chris.

315
00:17:01.916 --> 00:17:03.008
WEITZ: No. please. go ahead.

316
00:17:03.084 --> 00:17:04.244
LAMBERT: 'Cause I just remember.

317
00:17:04.318 --> 00:17:06.616
we spent a lot of time
looking for the right track for this.

318
00:17:06.687 --> 00:17:08.416
and I was pleased when we found one

319
00:17:08.489 --> 00:17:14.428
that the translation is about sort of things
being in peace or implying dying.

320
00:17:14.495 --> 00:17:20.127
It's like a Goethe poem that ends on.
"Soon you. too. will be at rest. "

321
00:17:20.201 --> 00:17:22.863
which seems appropriate
for those Goethe fans. as well.

322
00:17:22.937 --> 00:17:26.600
WEITZ: Yeah. I know. we are making big fans.

323
00:17:26.674 --> 00:17:28.642
LAMBERT: That's the most pretentious scene
in the movie.

324
00:17:28.709 --> 00:17:29.835
(WEITZ LAUGHS)

325
00:17:29.911 --> 00:17:33.472
WEITZ: I rather love that shot of the bowl.
of the flaming bowl.

326
00:17:33.548 --> 00:17:36.574
and partly because the gauze there
looks like a heart.

327
00:17:36.651 --> 00:17:41.111
and so it evokes. to me. some of this
kind of wonderful old-fashioned imagery.

328
00:17:41.189 --> 00:17:45.819
but also you can see an upside-down wolf
engraving in the shot. if you look carefully.

329
00:17:47.261 --> 00:17:52.631
Anya Marina's Satellite Heart is playing on
the radio here. a really lovely. lovely song.

330
00:17:53.634 --> 00:17:55.033
...or old age...

331
00:17:55.203 --> 00:18:00.732
WEITZ: And what I really like
about these sorts of scenes

332
00:18:00.808 --> 00:18:05.745
between Kristen and Rob is that
the situations are utterly bizarre.

333
00:18:05.813 --> 00:18:08.247
I mean. she's talking about
being turned into a vampire.

334
00:18:08.316 --> 00:18:12.047
and he's thinking about leaving
because he's going to kill her.

335
00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:18.025
but in some ways. it's like these horrible
pre-breakup conversations that you have.

336
00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:23.026
LAMBERT: Yeah. they play it so well.
'cause they just play it completely straight.

337
00:18:23.097 --> 00:18:28.057
WEITZ: And here. this is a nice little shot
where they're separated by the door. there.

338
00:18:29.470 --> 00:18:31.438
I think Kristen just has
this wonderful ability

339
00:18:31.506 --> 00:18:36.341
to make lines which are
about the soul or big ideas.

340
00:18:36.410 --> 00:18:38.469
but to somehow sell them.

341
00:18:40.548 --> 00:18:41.810
There's gonna be a lovely moment here

342
00:18:41.883 --> 00:18:46.217
where even though Edward is usually
the strong one. the aggressor.

343
00:18:46.854 --> 00:18:50.449
Bella. just by kind of force of character.
backs him up.

344
00:18:51.425 --> 00:18:55.885
You know. she is the one
who's forcing the issue here. really.

345
00:18:55.963 --> 00:18:58.329
and although Edward cannot be moved.
you know.

346
00:18:58.399 --> 00:19:02.597
he's practically made of stone.
she backs him up here.

347
00:19:03.337 --> 00:19:05.328
So can I ask one thing?

348
00:19:06.908 --> 00:19:09.274
WEITZ: "What. Bella? What do you want?"

349
00:19:10.144 --> 00:19:15.081
Okay. now. when...

350
00:19:16.784 --> 00:19:19.776
Usually in these kisses.
we're on Bella's side. as it were.

351
00:19:19.854 --> 00:19:22.982
So. you have 2 sides to choose from
when you're shooting a kiss.

352
00:19:23.057 --> 00:19:26.151
and I would say...

353
00:19:27.161 --> 00:19:28.628
Now I'm gonna get myself in trouble.

354
00:19:28.696 --> 00:19:31.790
Bella looks better when she's kissing
than Rob does.

355
00:19:31.866 --> 00:19:33.561
Kristen looks better when she's kissing
than Rob does.

356
00:19:33.634 --> 00:19:36.125
LAMBERT: You're only saying that because
you ate her burger the other day.

357
00:19:36.204 --> 00:19:37.933
WEITZ: Yeah. that's true. Sorry. Kristen.

358
00:19:38.005 --> 00:19:40.769
I know you were hungry.
but it was so delicious.

359
00:19:40.841 --> 00:19:44.106
That burger was just...
There are burger salvage rights.

360
00:19:44.178 --> 00:19:47.875
If you leave a burger for long enough.
someone's allowed to eat it. Anyway...

361
00:19:48.549 --> 00:19:51.017
LAMBERT: The "I love you. " should we give
the game away about that line.

362
00:19:51.085 --> 00:19:52.518
-"I love you. " from Kristen?
-WEITZ: Yes. Absolutely.

363
00:19:52.587 --> 00:19:54.282
LAMBERT:
It's a little bit of a sneaky cheat.

364
00:19:54.355 --> 00:19:58.587
WEITZ: Yeah. well. that's an ADR line.
which is a line that was recorded

365
00:19:58.859 --> 00:20:01.885
after the fact. in which Bella says.
"I love you. " And in fact.

366
00:20:01.963 --> 00:20:03.430
she's saying something else
at that moment.

367
00:20:03.497 --> 00:20:04.486
but you can barely tell.

368
00:20:04.565 --> 00:20:05.623
LAMBERT: I don't think
she's saying anything.

369
00:20:05.700 --> 00:20:06.792
I think she's just taking a breath

370
00:20:06.867 --> 00:20:08.596
and about to say
something completely different.

371
00:20:08.669 --> 00:20:11.832
WEITZ: Interesting. Okay.
So we wanted this moment.

372
00:20:11.906 --> 00:20:15.205
And. you know. in the first film.
they hadn't said. "I love you. " at all.

373
00:20:15.276 --> 00:20:19.872
and we thought that it would be very.
very interesting to have her say that.

374
00:20:19.947 --> 00:20:23.041
It's actually Kristen and Rob
who came up with the idea.

375
00:20:23.117 --> 00:20:25.711
At this moment where things
are really just going wrong.

376
00:20:25.786 --> 00:20:28.346
rather than in the moment
where things are going quite right.

377
00:20:28.422 --> 00:20:32.051
And it's kind of. you know.
strange and upsetting.

378
00:20:32.126 --> 00:20:36.324
but the whole point about this sequence
of the movie is things going wrong

379
00:20:36.397 --> 00:20:40.231
and sort of what happens
after "happily ever after"

380
00:20:40.301 --> 00:20:44.032
and the kind of weird. tragic beauty
of a romance going wrong.

381
00:20:44.572 --> 00:20:48.872
-I'm sure you know all about that. Peter.
-LAMBERT: I certainly do. yeah. Yeah.

382
00:20:49.477 --> 00:20:50.705
This music's beautiful.

383
00:20:50.778 --> 00:20:52.746
WEITZ: This is Bon Iver.
and it is a beautiful track.

384
00:20:52.813 --> 00:20:55.577
And St. Vincent.
and it is a gorgeous. gorgeous track.

385
00:20:55.650 --> 00:21:00.451
And this shot of Kristen is fantastic
in the way that she transitions

386
00:21:00.521 --> 00:21:06.949
between the relief of seeing Edward.
and then realizing something's wrong.

387
00:21:07.028 --> 00:21:09.394
in part because
he's still wearing the same clothes.

388
00:21:09.463 --> 00:21:13.399
Now. it should be pointed out
that vampires do not have body odor.

389
00:21:13.467 --> 00:21:19.838
so when he wears clothes for several
days in a row. or for months. in fact.

390
00:21:20.975 --> 00:21:25.002
it's okay. It's all right. It's just
the clothes are getting worn down.

391
00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:32.785
Anyway. here we are. and I believe
this is near Capilano Gorge in Vancouver.

392
00:21:33.487 --> 00:21:36.081
And this is the big breakup scene.

393
00:21:36.157 --> 00:21:39.285
and this is the scene that killed me
when it got out on the Net.

394
00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:43.091
I was so sad. because I wanted audiences
to see it for the first time

395
00:21:43.164 --> 00:21:45.598
as part of the whole picture.

396
00:21:45.700 --> 00:21:46.724
Why?

397
00:21:48.803 --> 00:21:51.738
LAMBERT: I love the way the camera works
on this scene.

398
00:21:51.806 --> 00:21:57.244
the kind of slightly sort of nauseous sense
of it moving in and then falling back again

399
00:21:57.311 --> 00:22:01.577
and then moving in.
It's kind of like waves of badness.

400
00:22:02.116 --> 00:22:03.174
WEITZ: There's...

401
00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:07.846
We had Dave Crone.
who's a fantastic Steadicam operator.

402
00:22:07.922 --> 00:22:10.550
Steadicam is a system
whereby you've got a guy

403
00:22:10.624 --> 00:22:14.355
who's essentially holding up the camera.
and it kind of floats.

404
00:22:15.229 --> 00:22:18.096
And you can see there's
a floatiness to this.

405
00:22:18.165 --> 00:22:22.693
And it works here because
her world is sort of floating away from her.

406
00:22:23.237 --> 00:22:27.799
And. you know.
we started with them together.

407
00:22:27.875 --> 00:22:31.003
we're separating them gradually.

408
00:22:31.078 --> 00:22:34.206
forcing into them so that we get the impact.

409
00:22:34.281 --> 00:22:37.341
Then we'll jump back.
and you'll feel sort of a distance

410
00:22:37.418 --> 00:22:40.148
in an over-the-shoulder shot like this.

411
00:22:40.221 --> 00:22:42.348
And then you'll see we cut to a 2-shot.

412
00:22:42.423 --> 00:22:45.017
We cut to the 2-shot
just when Edward says.

413
00:22:45.092 --> 00:22:46.719
"You don't belong in my world. " I think.

414
00:22:46.794 --> 00:22:52.426
And you know. a 2-shot
is a very emotionally inert shot.

415
00:22:52.500 --> 00:22:56.436
and you get this feeling...
Here we go. there's that 2-shot.

416
00:22:57.838 --> 00:22:59.169
There's no emotion at this moment.

417
00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:02.368
and then we cut right back in to her. close.

418
00:23:02.443 --> 00:23:05.970
Feeling it very. very. very seriously.

419
00:23:06.680 --> 00:23:10.172
And the camera is always moving
in this kind of queasy way.

420
00:23:10.251 --> 00:23:12.481
LAMBERT: There's something queasy
about the music. as well. I think.

421
00:23:12.553 --> 00:23:18.514
the way it kind of swells in waves.
and it's like the waves of bad news

422
00:23:18.592 --> 00:23:21.220
that Edward keeps kind of
crashing down on Bella.

423
00:23:21.295 --> 00:23:23.695
and she keeps trying to sort of
deflect or defend it.

424
00:23:23.764 --> 00:23:25.061
-WEITZ: Yeah.
-Defend herself from it.

425
00:23:25.132 --> 00:23:27.123
but it just keeps swelling again.

426
00:23:27.201 --> 00:23:30.398
WEITZ: And here where he says. "No. "
we're tighter than we've been ever.

427
00:23:31.672 --> 00:23:32.969
more fascinated with him.

428
00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:36.840
the camera's more fascinated on him
than it ever has been before.

429
00:23:38.546 --> 00:23:41.014
But if it's not too much to ask...

430
00:23:41.215 --> 00:23:45.379
WEITZ: And you'll see eventually
that it gets so much for Bella

431
00:23:45.453 --> 00:23:48.650
that the actual kind of access of the camera

432
00:23:48.722 --> 00:23:53.125
starts to tilt into
what is called a Dutch angle.

433
00:23:53.928 --> 00:23:59.389
where the camera
isn't parallel to the ground.

434
00:23:59.467 --> 00:24:04.461
It starts kind of tilting off
in a somewhat sickening way.

435
00:24:06.373 --> 00:24:08.500
LAMBERT: Not something that
we used very often. in the end.

436
00:24:08.576 --> 00:24:14.879
WEITZ: No. I don't like Dutch angles
except when it's for a good purpose.

437
00:24:16.417 --> 00:24:18.908
It's coming in a while. Now I've kind of...

438
00:24:18.986 --> 00:24:20.351
LAMBERT: You've pre-empted
the Dutch angle.

439
00:24:20.421 --> 00:24:22.446
WEITZ: I did. I pre-empted the Dutch.

440
00:24:22.523 --> 00:24:23.683
(BOTH LAUGHING)

441
00:24:23.757 --> 00:24:25.520
-LAMBERT: Never pre-empt a Dutch.
-No.

442
00:24:25.593 --> 00:24:30.656
And you can see. also.
that the backgrounds in these shots.

443
00:24:30.731 --> 00:24:33.427
having established
what the forest looked like.

444
00:24:33.501 --> 00:24:37.460
now become these kind of impressionistic
colors. and it's really... Here we go.

445
00:24:38.772 --> 00:24:43.766
It's shifting so that she's looking
right up at him at this sort of angle.

446
00:24:44.278 --> 00:24:46.246
and something feels quite wrong about it.

447
00:24:46.313 --> 00:24:50.374
He's quite static and controlled.
She is off angle.

448
00:24:51.418 --> 00:24:54.615
And now it's righting itself as he comes in.

449
00:24:54.688 --> 00:24:59.250
and when he leaves.
there's a discontinuity here.

450
00:24:59.326 --> 00:25:01.794
Normally you'd show him in space.

451
00:25:01.862 --> 00:25:06.322
but he actually leaves quicker than...
He's gone.

452
00:25:06.400 --> 00:25:09.631
Normally. if you were trying to convey
continuity of a person walking away.

453
00:25:09.703 --> 00:25:12.069
you'd see him in this shot.
you'd see him in the previous shot.

454
00:25:12.139 --> 00:25:14.437
But that's another way
that we kind of conveyed vampire speed

455
00:25:14.508 --> 00:25:17.705
was just in the cut. where suddenly
someone's not there anymore

456
00:25:17.778 --> 00:25:20.576
or someone is there
when they hadn't been moments ago.

457
00:25:21.248 --> 00:25:25.014
Now. these are jump cuts. which.
you either like them or you don't.

458
00:25:25.085 --> 00:25:26.814
but when you do them.
they're very obvious.

459
00:25:26.887 --> 00:25:30.323
and this conveys
the kind of frantic nature of things.

460
00:25:31.325 --> 00:25:33.919
Pete. you talk about jump cuts a bit.

461
00:25:35.062 --> 00:25:37.030
LAMBERT: Jump cuts convey
the frantic nature of things.

462
00:25:37.097 --> 00:25:39.327
and that's why we used them there.
'cause it's frantic.

463
00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:41.868
WEITZ: Wow. that's really incisive.

464
00:25:41.936 --> 00:25:48.637
LAMBERT: Okay. They're jump cuts
because the camera is at the same angle

465
00:25:48.709 --> 00:25:51.405
in relation to Bella
and the composition is the same.

466
00:25:51.478 --> 00:25:54.675
Normally. when you'd make a cut.
you would cut a different angle

467
00:25:54.748 --> 00:25:58.684
and maybe a different lens. so there would
be. in fact. a huge visual discontinuity

468
00:25:58.752 --> 00:26:00.049
between one shot and the next.

469
00:26:00.120 --> 00:26:05.183
which your brain would interpret
as a kind of fluid cut.

470
00:26:05.559 --> 00:26:09.461
When you actually cut from one angle
to another identical angle.

471
00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:11.430
it creates a kind of visual jolt.

472
00:26:11.498 --> 00:26:17.027
which gives you a sense of anxiety.
Is that right?

473
00:26:17.104 --> 00:26:18.765
-Have I nailed it?
-WEITZ: There you go.

474
00:26:18.839 --> 00:26:21.808
Yeah. yeah. no. and then we just had
another jump cut right there.

475
00:26:22.109 --> 00:26:26.011
And also. I should say.
okay. there was a rather groovy shot

476
00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:29.208
where we turned down the light
on this long walking shot.

477
00:26:29.283 --> 00:26:32.480
so that we transitioned from day into night
within one shot.

478
00:26:32.553 --> 00:26:37.490
And here now is a shot that I love to do.
which is a crane shot.

479
00:26:37.558 --> 00:26:39.492
pushing down on someone. circling.

480
00:26:41.295 --> 00:26:47.359
I mean. I feel that audiences understand
where someone is oriented in space.

481
00:26:47.468 --> 00:26:51.564
so they're not going to be like.
"Whoa. Bella is floating upside down. "

482
00:26:52.039 --> 00:26:53.836
LAMBERT: "The whole floor is moving. "

483
00:26:53.907 --> 00:26:57.536
WEITZ: So. they know that. okay.
Bella ends up upside down.

484
00:26:57.611 --> 00:26:59.340
obviously her world
has been turned upside down.

485
00:26:59.413 --> 00:27:04.077
and this thing is forcing down on her.
just the horrific moment.

486
00:27:04.151 --> 00:27:07.245
and so we use the camera
to kind of convey that.

487
00:27:08.022 --> 00:27:12.982
And here's our first shot of the wolves.
and the tough thing was to make it seem

488
00:27:13.060 --> 00:27:16.393
like it might be a wolf.
it might be a bear. what the heck is it?

489
00:27:16.764 --> 00:27:19.927
LAMBERT: We had a whole little
mini scene here. didn't we.

490
00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.401
of Bella waking up and actually explicitly
seeing the shape in the woods.

491
00:27:23.470 --> 00:27:25.335
WEITZ: And then she runs off.
and then she falls asleep again.

492
00:27:25.406 --> 00:27:27.237
but it was really hard to believe
that she fell asleep again

493
00:27:27.307 --> 00:27:29.468
having been so scared.

494
00:27:29.543 --> 00:27:31.704
LAMBERT: It was also kind of...
When you saw it that explicitly

495
00:27:31.779 --> 00:27:34.475
rather than in that kind of dreamy way
that we actually ended up cutting it.

496
00:27:34.548 --> 00:27:36.482
it just felt like too direct a connection

497
00:27:36.550 --> 00:27:38.643
between the werewolf and Sam Uley.
didn't it?

498
00:27:38.719 --> 00:27:43.918
WEITZ: Yeah. it did.
We wanted to preserve a bit of mystery to it.

499
00:27:45.092 --> 00:27:46.992
There is lovely Graham Greene.

500
00:27:47.061 --> 00:27:48.926
LAMBERT: There's also Bob Marks
in that scene.

501
00:27:48.996 --> 00:27:52.523
who deserves a shout out because
he doesn't appear elsewhere in the film.

502
00:27:52.599 --> 00:27:55.067
WEITZ: Yeah.
you'll see him in deleted scenes.

503
00:27:55.135 --> 00:27:58.764
and he was not deleted
for any reason other than for time.

504
00:27:59.339 --> 00:28:02.706
Bob Marks. played by Adrien Dorval.
good man.

505
00:28:03.911 --> 00:28:09.508
Now. Graham Greene and Chaske Spencer
having a little moment

506
00:28:09.616 --> 00:28:11.914
'cause they both know
about the werewolves.

507
00:28:11.985 --> 00:28:14.078
Jacob doesn't know
what the heck is going on.

508
00:28:14.154 --> 00:28:17.590
and Chaske is giving him the stink eye.
and he walks off.

509
00:28:19.293 --> 00:28:21.227
LAMBERT: There's this creepy naked guy
looking at him.

510
00:28:21.295 --> 00:28:22.421
(BOTH LAUGHING)

511
00:28:22.496 --> 00:28:26.489
WEITZ: So now we're going into this lovely
Lykke Li song.

512
00:28:26.567 --> 00:28:30.765
and also this very complicated
CG sequence.

513
00:28:31.071 --> 00:28:36.304
which involved first shooting
the element of Bella with a Steadicam.

514
00:28:36.376 --> 00:28:40.813
but having markers on the set
so that we could match exactly the move

515
00:28:40.881 --> 00:28:45.682
that Dave Crone did with the Steadicam.
with a robotic camera.

516
00:28:45.753 --> 00:28:47.721
which moved precisely the way that he did.

517
00:28:47.788 --> 00:28:52.282
so that we could do multiple passes and
that every time we looked out the window.

518
00:28:52.860 --> 00:28:56.728
we would see a new month.

519
00:28:57.631 --> 00:29:02.227
This corresponds directly
to these chapter headings in the book.

520
00:29:02.603 --> 00:29:06.039
which were rather clever and fun.
where time just doesn't pass.

521
00:29:06.106 --> 00:29:08.734
but you see the name of another month.

522
00:29:08.976 --> 00:29:11.570
It's also worth noting
that each time you go around

523
00:29:11.645 --> 00:29:15.376
there are fewer and fewer photographs
and paintings up on the wall.

524
00:29:15.449 --> 00:29:21.149
You just see the marks
that sun makes when it's covered up

525
00:29:22.289 --> 00:29:23.586
the absence of photos.

526
00:29:23.657 --> 00:29:27.184
so that her life is kind of
becoming less and less full.

527
00:29:27.261 --> 00:29:29.195
She's losing touch with her friends.

528
00:29:29.263 --> 00:29:34.496
She is just becoming kind of dead
to the world. really.

529
00:29:37.504 --> 00:29:40.769
And this shot is still going on.

530
00:29:41.742 --> 00:29:46.179
and this is just a match dissolve.

531
00:29:46.547 --> 00:29:49.516
Okay. no CG here.
Just very carefully positioning her

532
00:29:49.583 --> 00:29:53.280
on 2 totally different days
so that her position matches.

533
00:29:53.587 --> 00:29:56.181
You get the sense of her not moving ahead.

534
00:29:56.590 --> 00:30:00.026
Now some people think
that Bella screams like a stuck pig here.

535
00:30:00.093 --> 00:30:04.894
I rather enjoyed Kristen's first instinct.
which was that she was in so much pain

536
00:30:04.965 --> 00:30:07.695
that. you know. it wasn't just waking up
from a nightmare.

537
00:30:07.768 --> 00:30:10.498
but it was really like being stabbed
in the gut.

538
00:30:10.571 --> 00:30:13.836
LAMBERT: I think it's great.
and she's been so restrained in a way

539
00:30:13.907 --> 00:30:15.875
in terms of trying to keep it in
throughout the break up.

540
00:30:15.943 --> 00:30:17.205
it's like a big moment. I think.

541
00:30:17.277 --> 00:30:20.178
-when that happens.
-WEITZ: Yeah. I think it's a nice kind of jolt.

542
00:30:20.581 --> 00:30:25.075
Oh. Charlie. asleep on the couch
after watching his favorite sports team.

543
00:30:25.152 --> 00:30:27.814
LAMBERT: (LAUGHING) A night on the beer!

544
00:30:29.790 --> 00:30:32.315
WEITZ: And. yes.

545
00:30:37.030 --> 00:30:41.126
so. very kind of Norman Rockwelly
framing here...

546
00:30:42.269 --> 00:30:45.602
I don't believe Norman Rockwell's
a trademark. so I'm allowed to say that.

547
00:30:46.406 --> 00:30:49.603
You know. the house.
the very straight on shot of the house there.

548
00:30:50.711 --> 00:30:55.114
but things are not so good
with family at all.

549
00:30:57.551 --> 00:31:04.013
And Bella is going to lie now. leading
to a disastrous night out at the movies.

550
00:31:05.092 --> 00:31:07.287
Movies don't really go well in this movie.

551
00:31:07.594 --> 00:31:11.496
I don't. but just go. Go to Jacksonville.

552
00:31:11.565 --> 00:31:13.226
WEITZ: Go on.
say something interesting. Peter.

553
00:31:13.300 --> 00:31:16.292
LAMBERT: I think that Bella looks amazing
in this scene.

554
00:31:16.370 --> 00:31:21.307
-She looks so emaciated and unhappy.
-WEITZ: Yeah. yeah.

555
00:31:21.708 --> 00:31:25.735
LAMBERT: It's great the way her hair and
makeup transforms throughout the movie.

556
00:31:25.812 --> 00:31:30.977
WEITZ: Yeah. very nice makeup by Robin
Mathews. very nice hair by Thom Maclntyre.

557
00:31:33.353 --> 00:31:34.718
Yeah. and also I think the way

558
00:31:34.788 --> 00:31:37.086
that Tish Monaghan designed her clothing
at this point.

559
00:31:37.157 --> 00:31:41.116
she's really not bothering
to put herself together.

560
00:31:41.561 --> 00:31:46.555
and a nice'stache by Billy.
still there. the'stache remains.

561
00:31:46.633 --> 00:31:48.260
LAMBERT: The'tache always remains.

562
00:31:53.907 --> 00:31:55.898
Muse. the music of a liar.

563
00:31:56.877 --> 00:31:57.901
WEITZ: The music of a liar?

564
00:31:57.978 --> 00:32:01.345
LAMBERT: Yeah. when someone lies.
Muse always plays in the background.

565
00:32:01.415 --> 00:32:02.643
(WEITZ LAUGHING)

566
00:32:02.716 --> 00:32:04.115
That's the rule.

567
00:32:04.184 --> 00:32:05.651
JESSICA: I don't know why you want to
sit through...

568
00:32:05.719 --> 00:32:07.687
WEITZ: I don't know what that means.
but I'll go with it.

569
00:32:08.355 --> 00:32:14.055
Okay. so they've seen a zombie movie.
We cleared this one title

570
00:32:14.127 --> 00:32:17.187
as the one zombie movie title
that's never been used.

571
00:32:17.264 --> 00:32:21.325
and. of course.
it refers back to the possibility.

572
00:32:21.401 --> 00:32:26.065
or Bella's hope. that someday
that Edward would come back.

573
00:32:26.606 --> 00:32:28.039
-And actually...
-LAMBERT: This was all...

574
00:32:28.108 --> 00:32:30.804
Sorry. this was all ad-libbing
from Anna Kendrick. wasn't it?

575
00:32:30.877 --> 00:32:35.507
WEITZ: It was. except that I told her
to do the thing where her cousin has leprosy.

576
00:32:35.582 --> 00:32:40.315
I take full credit for that.

577
00:32:41.088 --> 00:32:43.716
LAMBERT: Well. there were lots of different
versions of this. I remember.

578
00:32:43.790 --> 00:32:46.350
She gave lots of different things.

579
00:32:46.426 --> 00:32:48.121
WEITZ: They're quite funny.

580
00:32:48.195 --> 00:32:51.562
Now we're flashing back
to the frat boys in Twilight.

581
00:32:52.099 --> 00:32:54.294
LAMBERT: This was the first sequence I cut

582
00:32:54.501 --> 00:32:56.867
because I could cut it
before any dailies came in from the shoot.

583
00:32:56.937 --> 00:32:58.529
WEITZ: Of course. there you go.

584
00:32:59.072 --> 00:33:01.870
And here's our first view of Edward.

585
00:33:01.942 --> 00:33:08.575
Controversially. we used visuals
of Edward as well as just the aural.

586
00:33:08.648 --> 00:33:12.914
A-U-R-A-L. hallucinations
that Bella experiences.

587
00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:18.084
I thought it was a worthwhile
use of the power of film

588
00:33:19.026 --> 00:33:22.553
and enough Edward
without being too much.

589
00:33:24.064 --> 00:33:26.555
Well. they seem great. Can we go?

590
00:33:27.134 --> 00:33:30.194
WEITZ: I think that that's a very funny
line reading by Anna there.

591
00:33:30.904 --> 00:33:32.337
CHET: Hey. girlie!

592
00:33:32.572 --> 00:33:35.871
WEITZ: You may have noticed that Port
Angeles has become a larger city recently

593
00:33:35.942 --> 00:33:38.376
and also a bit more
of a post-industrial town.

594
00:33:39.146 --> 00:33:40.511
(BOTH LAUGHING)

595
00:33:40.580 --> 00:33:44.880
It was a charming town in Twilight.
but it's really seen better days now.

596
00:33:44.951 --> 00:33:46.714
LAMBERT: This is like
the dark end of Port Angeles.

597
00:33:46.787 --> 00:33:48.584
The bit you don't wanna hang out in.

598
00:33:48.655 --> 00:33:50.850
WEITZ: Yeah. right near the movie theater.

599
00:33:50.924 --> 00:33:52.050
(LAMBERT CHUCKLING)

600
00:33:52.926 --> 00:33:56.760
LAMBERT: There's also a completely
empty street just around the corner.

601
00:34:04.971 --> 00:34:06.165
I'm sorry. I thought you
were somebody else.

602
00:34:06.239 --> 00:34:09.072
No. that's cool.
I'll be whoever you want me to be. honey.

603
00:34:09.142 --> 00:34:11.804
So. what do you say?

604
00:34:16.383 --> 00:34:18.977
You promised me. nothing reckless.

605
00:34:19.052 --> 00:34:20.280
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

606
00:34:22.889 --> 00:34:26.120
You promised it would be
as if you never existed.

607
00:34:26.293 --> 00:34:27.317
(CHET CLEARS THROAT)

608
00:34:31.631 --> 00:34:34.395
-You lied.
-You say something. babe?

609
00:34:34.468 --> 00:34:35.958
You know what? Never mind.

610
00:34:36.036 --> 00:34:37.628
(ENGINE ROARING)

611
00:34:53.120 --> 00:34:55.748
Stop! Stop. stop. stop!

612
00:34:55.922 --> 00:34:57.787
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

613
00:35:03.330 --> 00:35:05.525
WEITZ: Anyway. all that stuff
that we just saw. of course.

614
00:35:05.599 --> 00:35:10.036
was using CGI and modulating it

615
00:35:10.103 --> 00:35:13.664
as much as we could
to give Bella the notion

616
00:35:13.740 --> 00:35:17.870
that she needed to put herself in danger.

617
00:35:17.944 --> 00:35:21.903
which leads her to Jacob
via the bikes. basically.

618
00:35:22.182 --> 00:35:26.084
I was about to end up in an FBI
interview room like some lame TV show.

619
00:35:26.386 --> 00:35:28.445
God. that was such a rush.

620
00:35:30.157 --> 00:35:32.717
Awesome.
So you're an adrenaline junkie now?

621
00:35:32.792 --> 00:35:34.054
That's cool. You can go bungee jumping.

622
00:35:34.127 --> 00:35:37.392
You don't get on the back
of some random loser's motorcycle.

623
00:35:37.464 --> 00:35:38.624
Crazy.

624
00:35:43.303 --> 00:35:45.965
BELLA: Alice. I saw him.

625
00:35:47.874 --> 00:35:50.707
Maybe I'm crazy now. I guess that's okay.

626
00:35:52.479 --> 00:35:58.475
WEITZ: So here she comes to Jacob's house.
which we now see for the first time.

627
00:35:59.486 --> 00:36:03.388
this lovely barn. which was green.
which we repainted red

628
00:36:03.456 --> 00:36:09.053
to be like in the book. and we put
a lot of Quileute-type fishing gear around it

629
00:36:09.396 --> 00:36:13.560
even though this was once
a goat pasture. actually.

630
00:36:13.833 --> 00:36:14.891
LAMBERT: Wow.

631
00:36:14.968 --> 00:36:18.631
WEITZ: We moved away all the goats
and replaced it with actors.

632
00:36:18.705 --> 00:36:21.833
LAMBERT: And Bella's house
was next to a turkey abattoir. as well.

633
00:36:22.008 --> 00:36:28.880
WEITZ: Yes. abattoir being a slaughterhouse.
by the way. for the non-British world.

634
00:36:31.418 --> 00:36:34.717
Taylor hates this wig.
and in a way. I can't blame him.

635
00:36:36.156 --> 00:36:40.559
because I suppose it's kind of like.
you know. being Chewbacca.

636
00:36:42.028 --> 00:36:43.256
LAMBERT: Michael Sheen. of course. loved it.

637
00:36:43.330 --> 00:36:45.560
and that's why he is wearing it
at the end of the movie.

638
00:36:45.632 --> 00:36:46.690
(WEITZ EXCLAIMS)

639
00:36:46.766 --> 00:36:47.790
(BOTH LAUGHING)

640
00:36:47.867 --> 00:36:51.064
WEITZ: Oh. yes. we like to joke about
reusing wigs. but we didn't. We really didn't.

641
00:36:51.137 --> 00:36:52.661
-LAMBERT: No. it's a different wig.
-Yeah.

642
00:36:52.806 --> 00:36:54.603
...really stupid and reckless.

643
00:36:54.674 --> 00:36:56.369
Yeah. I mean.
it's completely stupid...

644
00:36:56.443 --> 00:37:03.212
WEITZ: So. we're gonna do a little thing here
where Jacob manages to lift this bike.

645
00:37:03.283 --> 00:37:09.085
and what it involves is having it
on a very strong crane rig

646
00:37:09.155 --> 00:37:13.148
which can lift it. making it look
as though Jacob is actually putting in

647
00:37:13.226 --> 00:37:15.160
just enough force to lift it.

648
00:37:15.228 --> 00:37:18.254
and then erasing the wires
that were holding it up.

649
00:37:18.331 --> 00:37:22.290
And that thing is fricking heavy.
I tried lifting it myself.

650
00:37:22.369 --> 00:37:25.338
There is no way that even Taylor Lautner.

651
00:37:25.705 --> 00:37:30.267
with his improved Taylor Lautner 2. 0 body.
could have done it.

652
00:37:30.944 --> 00:37:34.345
So. it's a nice little moment there.

653
00:37:34.814 --> 00:37:37.112
It feels like that sometimes.

654
00:37:38.151 --> 00:37:40.415
WEITZ: And this song is
by the Magic Numbers.

655
00:37:40.487 --> 00:37:42.011
but what you don't get to in this part of it

656
00:37:42.088 --> 00:37:47.856
is the part by Amadou and Mariam.
who are this Senegalese duo.

657
00:37:47.927 --> 00:37:52.057
and I recommend their music very highly.
They're on our soundtrack.

658
00:37:53.600 --> 00:37:54.658
Did I just see a mike?

659
00:37:54.734 --> 00:37:56.793
I thought I saw a boom up there.
Oh. wait. never mind. anyway.

660
00:37:56.870 --> 00:37:58.770
LAMBERT: Maybe you're looking at it
in the wrong aspect ratio.

661
00:37:58.838 --> 00:38:01.102
WEITZ: I think I'm probably looking
at the wrong aspect ratio. yeah.

662
00:38:01.174 --> 00:38:02.971
LAMBERT: Yeah. that'll be it.

663
00:38:04.511 --> 00:38:07.071
WEITZ: Okay. well. this lovely barn here.

664
00:38:07.147 --> 00:38:09.945
designed by David Brisbin.
our production designer.

665
00:38:10.016 --> 00:38:13.179
and his wonderful crew.
filled with lovely stuff.

666
00:38:13.253 --> 00:38:16.381
and when you build these interiors.

667
00:38:16.456 --> 00:38:19.983
you want it to be full of detail and interest

668
00:38:20.460 --> 00:38:25.864
and lovely. crunchy texture
for the light to play off of.

669
00:38:25.932 --> 00:38:27.923
but you don't want things
to pop out so much

670
00:38:28.001 --> 00:38:30.299
that you're not paying attention
to the actors.

671
00:38:31.304 --> 00:38:35.240
And so now we're establishing
this lovely friendship

672
00:38:35.308 --> 00:38:37.868
that's forming between him and Kristen.

673
00:38:37.944 --> 00:38:43.314
I think it conveys very well the life
that he's kind of infusing into her.

674
00:38:43.383 --> 00:38:48.218
and that's kind of what Taylor is like.
He's just such a wonderful. warm person.

675
00:38:49.255 --> 00:38:52.019
Now. here come Quil and Embry.

676
00:38:54.027 --> 00:38:56.894
The guy who's playing Quil.
Tyson Houseman...

677
00:38:57.330 --> 00:39:00.663
I love this joke. by the way.
where he's just so keen on himself.

678
00:39:01.735 --> 00:39:03.532
I think he was just kind of walking around

679
00:39:03.603 --> 00:39:06.436
and saw a big line of people and said.
"What's going on?"

680
00:39:06.506 --> 00:39:08.997
And they're like. "Somebody's lining up.
people are lining up

681
00:39:09.075 --> 00:39:11.236
"to audition for this movie. "

682
00:39:11.311 --> 00:39:16.442
and then he found himself.
about a week later. cast as Quil.

683
00:39:16.916 --> 00:39:18.315
-LAMBERT: That's pretty cool.
-Yeah.

684
00:39:19.486 --> 00:39:24.947
And Kiowa does not have hair like that.
That is a wig. also.

685
00:39:25.291 --> 00:39:26.315
A rather good wig.

686
00:39:26.393 --> 00:39:29.123
You want funny. Black? I'll give you funny.

687
00:39:29.295 --> 00:39:34.028
WEITZ: The thing here. I think. was to cast
guys who just seemed like regular kids.

688
00:39:35.568 --> 00:39:38.298
All the Quileutes
were played by First Nations.

689
00:39:38.371 --> 00:39:41.306
as they call them in Canada.
or Native American actors.

690
00:39:42.542 --> 00:39:46.273
And also. they don't talk about "my tribe"
and "my people" all the time.

691
00:39:46.346 --> 00:39:49.679
which I think Native Americans
and First Nations people

692
00:39:49.749 --> 00:39:51.979
are really sick of hearing in everything.

693
00:39:52.051 --> 00:39:56.010
every piece of popular culture
that involves an Indian.

694
00:39:56.089 --> 00:39:58.523
as they're often called.

695
00:39:59.192 --> 00:40:01.683
Okay. this is another motion control shot.

696
00:40:01.761 --> 00:40:07.666
which means that you can sort of stay
within the same atmosphere.

697
00:40:08.067 --> 00:40:11.002
but pick it up at very different times of day

698
00:40:11.070 --> 00:40:14.164
with the actors in positions it would have
been impossible for them to reach.

699
00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:17.334
So. very subtly.
you see their relationship developing

700
00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:20.937
as this bike comes together.
as the time of day changes.

701
00:40:21.347 --> 00:40:27.343
And you hardly notice it happening.
but they're changing positions.

702
00:40:27.554 --> 00:40:29.818
they're changing relative to one another.

703
00:40:29.889 --> 00:40:32.949
and things are coming together.
especially motorbikes.

704
00:40:33.493 --> 00:40:34.721
(LAMBERT LAUGHING)

705
00:40:35.829 --> 00:40:38.627
-And I think...
-LAMBERT: Until Jacob messes it up.

706
00:40:39.065 --> 00:40:45.095
WEITZ: I know. Poor Jake. He's kind of
always saying the wrong thing at the time.

707
00:40:45.605 --> 00:40:47.835
Why is he talking
about Edward Cullen now?

708
00:40:47.907 --> 00:40:51.001
He's like. "I shouldn't have said that.
That was a mistake. "

709
00:40:51.177 --> 00:40:54.340
LAMBERT: And it did lead
to an entire nightmare scene. didn't it?

710
00:40:54.414 --> 00:40:55.438
WEITZ: Yeah.

711
00:40:55.515 --> 00:40:58.040
LAMBERT: Which we took out
for various reasons.

712
00:40:58.418 --> 00:41:02.650
We felt that it kind of lessened the impact
of the apparitions

713
00:41:02.722 --> 00:41:05.953
if you saw Edward too much.
as you had done in a nightmare.

714
00:41:06.025 --> 00:41:07.117
which we cut from that.

715
00:41:07.193 --> 00:41:10.390
WEITZ: Yeah. and also. I think that with film.
there's always a danger

716
00:41:10.463 --> 00:41:12.829
-of one dream sequence too many.
-LAMBERT: Yeah.

717
00:41:14.434 --> 00:41:18.564
WEITZ: Some films that I love. they just put in
one darn dream sequence too many.

718
00:41:19.138 --> 00:41:22.130
There's the evil dream catcher again.

719
00:41:24.143 --> 00:41:25.735
(WEITZ MIMICKING DRAMATIC MUSIC)

720
00:41:28.982 --> 00:41:33.681
This is a sweet little scene
with Billy and Kristen

721
00:41:35.555 --> 00:41:38.991
where he gives the conventional
wisdom of love the one you're with.

722
00:41:39.092 --> 00:41:43.461
And for a second. you'll see
in the very first shot of the next scene.

723
00:41:43.530 --> 00:41:48.832
she'll even consider it.
She'll be thinking. "Should I settle?"

724
00:41:48.902 --> 00:41:53.669
And I think that
that's part of the book of New Moon.

725
00:41:53.740 --> 00:41:57.676
the notion that...
I mean. she knows in her mind.

726
00:41:58.244 --> 00:42:02.908
she feels so low. She feels Edward is way
above her and will never come back.

727
00:42:03.249 --> 00:42:08.915
And here is Jacob who is warm and special
and loves her. and what should she do?

728
00:42:12.025 --> 00:42:14.789
But she never does. She never quite does.

729
00:42:16.329 --> 00:42:19.696
There. she's looking at him.
She's thinking about it.

730
00:42:20.266 --> 00:42:22.666
And then her head quickly goes away

731
00:42:22.735 --> 00:42:26.899
as she notices Jacob
possibly catching her in that moment.

732
00:42:26.973 --> 00:42:28.873
Are you doubting your mad skills?

733
00:42:30.076 --> 00:42:33.011
WEITZ: Now. it should be said
that this was shot against a green screen.

734
00:42:33.346 --> 00:42:40.081
None of these trees that are currently
kind of flying across the windscreen.

735
00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:43.653
There is no windscreen.
That windscreen was put in digitally.

736
00:42:43.723 --> 00:42:47.386
The trees were put in digitally.
Anything that runs by the window is digital.

737
00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:49.894
It was all shot in a barn.

738
00:42:49.963 --> 00:42:53.330
which we had to use
when it was snowing one day

739
00:42:53.399 --> 00:42:55.560
-in the middle of the sequence...
-LAMBERT: Right. It was a meadow.

740
00:42:55.635 --> 00:42:59.594
WEITZ: Yeah. in the middle of the meadow
sequence with Laurent and Kristen.

741
00:42:59.672 --> 00:43:03.472
it snowed. and we showed up one day
at 5:00 in the morning.

742
00:43:03.543 --> 00:43:06.273
and there was no way to shoot there.

743
00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:10.205
LAMBERT: But there was a barn
with a green screen ready to put in it.

744
00:43:10.383 --> 00:43:13.284
WEITZ: Yeah. and so we did

745
00:43:13.353 --> 00:43:17.983
all of our green screen car work
during that time.

746
00:43:18.858 --> 00:43:22.726
Here is a cliff.
which was put together from a real cliff.

747
00:43:22.795 --> 00:43:27.732
CG additions to the cliff.
guys shot against green screen.

748
00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:31.998
now that is Alex Meraz first jumping.

749
00:43:32.071 --> 00:43:35.336
but about half way down.
he's taken over by CGI

750
00:43:35.408 --> 00:43:40.539
and turned into a CGI Alex
who splashes into CGI water.

751
00:43:41.547 --> 00:43:43.071
I don't know.

752
00:43:43.149 --> 00:43:45.709
They just think they run this place.

753
00:43:46.285 --> 00:43:48.276
Embry used to call them
hall monitors on steroids.

754
00:43:48.354 --> 00:43:49.844
WEITZ: Yeah. now you'll notice

755
00:43:49.922 --> 00:43:56.725
that Sam Uley favors Capri length shorts.

756
00:43:57.764 --> 00:44:01.325
and that's because the guy who was gonna
do the groovy stunt that's coming up

757
00:44:01.401 --> 00:44:04.131
had injured his knee recently
and had to wear a brace.

758
00:44:04.203 --> 00:44:07.866
So. JJ. the stunt coordinator
came to me and said.

759
00:44:08.107 --> 00:44:11.076
"Is it possible for Sam
to wear extra long shorts?"

760
00:44:11.144 --> 00:44:13.476
And I said. "Okay. "

761
00:44:14.113 --> 00:44:15.705
(BOTH LAUGHING)

762
00:44:15.782 --> 00:44:17.750
Hence Sam's fashion choice.

763
00:44:18.551 --> 00:44:20.519
Now. I've taken a lot of flak
in the press recently

764
00:44:20.586 --> 00:44:24.147
for why the Quileutes are always shirtless.

765
00:44:25.291 --> 00:44:30.251
as though I were some creepy old man
who just wanted to show guys with abs

766
00:44:31.898 --> 00:44:33.126
and 6-packs.

767
00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:35.390
That was the shot. by the way.

768
00:44:35.968 --> 00:44:38.266
That was put together
from about 3 different elements.

769
00:44:38.337 --> 00:44:40.897
a guy jumping off a huge tower and...

770
00:44:40.973 --> 00:44:45.706
But let me finish talking
about these lack of shirts.

771
00:44:46.079 --> 00:44:48.639
My answer's always that
the Quileutes do not have a lot of money

772
00:44:48.715 --> 00:44:52.811
to waste on T-shirts.

773
00:44:52.885 --> 00:44:56.286
so if you're running 108 fever.

774
00:44:56.723 --> 00:44:58.918
you're gonna walk around
in a bunch of shorts.

775
00:44:58.991 --> 00:45:01.755
LAMBERT: And more to the point. if you're
gonna turn into a wolf the whole time

776
00:45:01.828 --> 00:45:03.659
and lose your T-shirt
every time you transform...

777
00:45:03.730 --> 00:45:04.788
WEITZ: Exactly.

778
00:45:04.864 --> 00:45:06.058
LAMBERT:... that's gonna
start getting expensive.

779
00:45:06.132 --> 00:45:08.566
WEITZ: It will get costly. and it gets tiresome

780
00:45:08.634 --> 00:45:13.230
to have stashes of clothes
all around the woods.

781
00:45:13.639 --> 00:45:16.403
I love this shot 'cause it looks like
a Magritte painting.

782
00:45:16.476 --> 00:45:18.569
LAMBERT: That's my favorite apparition.

783
00:45:18.644 --> 00:45:21.704
WEITZ: Yeah. I think it's mine. too.
I think it's mine. too.

784
00:45:23.015 --> 00:45:26.109
I think it's rather nice how
the bike's stalling out

785
00:45:26.185 --> 00:45:29.382
kind of conveys her shock at that moment.

786
00:45:30.957 --> 00:45:35.826
And also Alexandre's weird music here
conveys adrenaline

787
00:45:35.895 --> 00:45:39.126
and blood sort of pumping
through her head.

788
00:45:44.003 --> 00:45:47.302
Notice. is this Kristen?

789
00:45:47.640 --> 00:45:50.234
-Not so much.
-LAMBERT: It's Christopher.

790
00:45:50.309 --> 00:45:51.640
(BOTH LAUGHING)

791
00:45:52.612 --> 00:45:54.910
WEITZ: Okay. that was a dude.

792
00:45:55.982 --> 00:45:58.746
-But you know...
-LAMBERT: The rest is all Kristen.

793
00:45:58.818 --> 00:45:59.842
WEITZ: The rest is all Kristen.

794
00:45:59.919 --> 00:46:01.011
LAMBERT: And the person
driving the motorbike

795
00:46:01.087 --> 00:46:02.850
when Jacob comes up is. in fact. a woman.

796
00:46:03.356 --> 00:46:05.187
No. it's not. That's Taylor.

797
00:46:05.258 --> 00:46:06.919
(BOTH LAUGHING)

798
00:46:06.993 --> 00:46:08.654
No more bikes.

799
00:46:10.263 --> 00:46:13.096
-LAMBERT: Here comes a big moment.
-Here comes a big moment.

800
00:46:13.166 --> 00:46:14.895
Now. this used to be a wider shot.

801
00:46:14.967 --> 00:46:21.497
All you ladies who wanted a wider shot
of Taylor taking his shirt off.

802
00:46:22.008 --> 00:46:24.875
I had it in
and then Stephenie Meyer called it

803
00:46:25.211 --> 00:46:29.739
Jacob's Chippendales audition.
and so we went to a tighter shot of it.

804
00:46:29.949 --> 00:46:31.246
LAMBERT: A tighter and quicker shot.
as well.

805
00:46:31.317 --> 00:46:33.114
where he kind of does it all a bit quicker.

806
00:46:33.186 --> 00:46:35.279
The one we originally had.
which I think you could probably see

807
00:46:35.354 --> 00:46:36.821
in the Comic-Con footage online.

808
00:46:36.889 --> 00:46:39.414
-he kind of labors it a little.
-WEITZ: He sort of luxuriates in it.

809
00:46:39.492 --> 00:46:42.052
It is a bit much. It's true.

810
00:46:42.128 --> 00:46:46.462
LAMBERT: Good for Comic-Con
but not necessary at this stage.

811
00:46:46.532 --> 00:46:48.466
You're sort of beautiful.

812
00:46:50.436 --> 00:46:51.596
LAMBERT: Now this is
when he should kiss her.

813
00:46:51.671 --> 00:46:54.697
WEITZ: Yeah. here's where Jacob loses
another great chance.

814
00:46:55.308 --> 00:46:58.209
but he's too nice a guy.
She's just hit her head. so...

815
00:46:58.277 --> 00:47:00.768
LAMBERT: No. you don't kiss a girl
when she's just hit her head.

816
00:47:00.847 --> 00:47:02.371
WEITZ: Why don't we count out
the number of times

817
00:47:02.448 --> 00:47:07.147
he has missed opportunities?
Twice so far. I'd say. at least.

818
00:47:09.121 --> 00:47:09.951
LAMBERT: What was the first time again?
I've forgotten.

819
00:47:10.690 --> 00:47:12.851
WEITZ: I think it was when he started talking
about Edward Cullen.

820
00:47:12.925 --> 00:47:15.416
He couldn't have kissed her then.
but he really shouldn't have said that.

821
00:47:15.494 --> 00:47:18.930
so 2 mistakes.
2 Jacob romantic mistakes.

822
00:47:18.998 --> 00:47:22.092
guys. anyone out there listening.

823
00:47:22.768 --> 00:47:26.727
So now. Kristen has been
sort of pulled back into the world

824
00:47:26.806 --> 00:47:32.244
by her association with Jacob.
She's ready to deal with

825
00:47:32.311 --> 00:47:34.541
-humanity again.
-LAMBERT: It's nice the way the music

826
00:47:34.614 --> 00:47:38.675
that's kind of represented
her sort of tender feelings towards Jacob

827
00:47:38.751 --> 00:47:40.776
at the end of the last scene
continues through

828
00:47:40.853 --> 00:47:43.788
to the moment where she decides
to join her friends.

829
00:47:43.856 --> 00:47:45.881
It's like somehow there's a link.

830
00:47:47.326 --> 00:47:52.992
WEITZ: And she goes to join
her unfeasibly attractive normal friends.

831
00:47:53.966 --> 00:47:55.695
(BOTH LAUGHING)

832
00:47:56.569 --> 00:48:01.302
And I really like this bit with Mike here.

833
00:48:01.374 --> 00:48:06.835
It's really well-delivered. his kind of...
I don't know. It's terribly funny.

834
00:48:06.913 --> 00:48:08.312
but it's also rather touching at the moment.

835
00:48:08.381 --> 00:48:11.976
I mean. the guy who really loses
in all of this is Mike.

836
00:48:13.185 --> 00:48:15.676
-much worse than Jacob. I think. in a way.
-LAMBERT: Yeah.

837
00:48:15.755 --> 00:48:18.155
WEITZ: Although. Jacob goes through
a lot more with Bella.

838
00:48:18.224 --> 00:48:20.920
so I suppose he's got more to lose.
but Mike. Mike is just...

839
00:48:20.993 --> 00:48:23.018
LAMBERT: And Jacob also has to turn
into a wolf. as well.

840
00:48:23.095 --> 00:48:24.960
Mike doesn't have to live with that.

841
00:48:25.031 --> 00:48:27.591
WEITZ: And also. Mike could have gone out
with Jessica. and he dumped her.

842
00:48:27.667 --> 00:48:28.895
That was probably

843
00:48:28.968 --> 00:48:31.027
-the biggest mistake of his life.
-LAMBERT: Douche. Douche move.

844
00:48:31.103 --> 00:48:34.004
WEITZ: They might get back together.
Who knows? Do they?

845
00:48:34.073 --> 00:48:35.768
LAMBERT: I'm trying to remember.

846
00:48:35.841 --> 00:48:39.538
We'll have to watch
The Twilight Saga: Eclipse to find out.

847
00:48:39.612 --> 00:48:40.636
(WEITZ LAUGHING)

848
00:48:40.713 --> 00:48:42.681
Coming out in June 2010.

849
00:48:45.217 --> 00:48:48.744
WEITZ: I love this moment here where...
Oh. no. we missed it.

850
00:48:48.821 --> 00:48:53.053
Where Kristen says. "Yeah. I'd like to go. "
and then she has nothing to add.

851
00:48:53.125 --> 00:48:56.891
and you sort of see her opening her mouth
and closing it.

852
00:48:58.097 --> 00:49:00.292
Now. Face Punch is a title

853
00:49:00.366 --> 00:49:04.996
that my brother and I always thought
would be a great name for a hockey movie.

854
00:49:05.071 --> 00:49:09.701
and so I had to give a list of clearable titles
for action movies.

855
00:49:10.276 --> 00:49:12.506
and Face Punch was 1 of the 2
that cleared.

856
00:49:12.578 --> 00:49:15.843
You'd be surprised the number
of stupid names for action movies

857
00:49:15.915 --> 00:49:18.850
that have actually been turned
into stupid action movies.

858
00:49:18.918 --> 00:49:22.877
The only choices we had
were Face Punch and Kill Hunt.

859
00:49:22.955 --> 00:49:24.081
We went with Face Punch.

860
00:49:24.156 --> 00:49:25.783
LAMBERT: Yeah.
I think that was the right choice.

861
00:49:25.858 --> 00:49:27.450
WEITZ: Yeah. Definitely.

862
00:49:30.329 --> 00:49:31.421
LAMBERT: I love this scene. as well.

863
00:49:31.497 --> 00:49:34.432
-WEITZ: I do. too. where Jacob is kind of...
-He's so sweet.

864
00:49:34.500 --> 00:49:37.162
WEITZ: Jacob's sweet.
but he's also sort of messing with Mike.

865
00:49:37.236 --> 00:49:43.607
and Mike is really being a bit pissy
with Jacob. but Jacob is unflappable.

866
00:49:43.676 --> 00:49:44.665
LAMBERT: Did you just use
our one curse word?

867
00:49:44.744 --> 00:49:45.836
WEITZ: Was that our one swear word?

868
00:49:45.911 --> 00:49:47.879
I don't think that counts. does it?

869
00:49:47.947 --> 00:49:49.676
LAMBERT: I don't know.
I'm not gonna say it again. though.

870
00:49:49.749 --> 00:49:51.410
WEITZ: Well. if I haven't.
I'm just gonna swear at you.

871
00:49:51.484 --> 00:49:54.544
I think we get one swear word
in this entire commentary.

872
00:49:54.620 --> 00:49:56.713
so I'm just gonna swear at you
at the end of this whole thing.

873
00:49:56.789 --> 00:49:57.778
LAMBERT: Okay. okay.

874
00:49:57.890 --> 00:50:00.552
MAN 2 ON SCREEN: Put your gun down
or I'm gonna blow your frickin' head off.

875
00:50:00.626 --> 00:50:03.060
MAN 3 ON SCREEN: Both of you put both
of your guns down

876
00:50:03.129 --> 00:50:05.723
or I'm gonna blow both
of your frickin' heads off.

877
00:50:07.666 --> 00:50:09.133
MAN 1 ON SCREEN: All right. forget it.
let's do this!

878
00:50:09.201 --> 00:50:10.293
(GUNS FIRING)

879
00:50:10.369 --> 00:50:11.961
(MAN SCREAMS)

880
00:50:12.038 --> 00:50:13.699
(GUNS FIRING)

881
00:50:16.942 --> 00:50:18.432
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

882
00:50:27.253 --> 00:50:29.050
Okay. I think I'm gonna throw up.

883
00:50:29.555 --> 00:50:30.544
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

884
00:50:35.895 --> 00:50:37.294
He's...

885
00:50:37.797 --> 00:50:39.765
(SCOFFS) What a marshmallow!

886
00:50:40.566 --> 00:50:42.796
LAMBERT: Always gets a line. that laugh.

887
00:50:43.502 --> 00:50:45.333
WEITZ: I think you just did a spoonerism.

888
00:50:45.404 --> 00:50:47.998
"Always gets a laugh. that line. "
you meant. surely?

889
00:50:48.074 --> 00:50:50.372
-LAMBERT: What did I say?
-Always get a line. that laugh.

890
00:50:50.443 --> 00:50:51.501
-LAMBERT: Did I?
-Yeah.

891
00:50:51.577 --> 00:50:53.477
-LAMBERT: Okay. can I explain why?
-Yeah.

892
00:50:53.546 --> 00:50:56.379
LAMBERT: It's 'cause
I haven't slept for 32 hours

893
00:50:56.449 --> 00:50:59.782
'cause I flew back from Los Angeles
to London yesterday.

894
00:50:59.852 --> 00:51:01.149
WEITZ: Oh. I see. All right.

895
00:51:01.220 --> 00:51:03.450
LAMBERT: That's why.
There'll be more of those.

896
00:51:07.293 --> 00:51:08.988
WEITZ: Now. funny...
We just saw the premiere.

897
00:51:09.061 --> 00:51:13.327
and people laugh when Bella disengages
her hand from Jacob's.

898
00:51:13.399 --> 00:51:18.393
I think perhaps because girls feel
that's a very identifiable moment for them.

899
00:51:18.471 --> 00:51:24.137
when a guy kind of gets a bit closer
than you are ready for them to be.

900
00:51:24.210 --> 00:51:28.306
LAMBERT: I would add that that is probably
a 3rd mistaken moment from Jacob.

901
00:51:28.380 --> 00:51:30.712
because I think he times it very badly.

902
00:51:30.783 --> 00:51:34.082
-the hand-holding.
-WEITZ: Yeah. what he should do is...

903
00:51:35.287 --> 00:51:37.551
Well. I don't know.

904
00:51:37.623 --> 00:51:40.285
I rather admire Jacob's persistence
at this moment.

905
00:51:40.359 --> 00:51:42.259
because I think sometimes
if you're gonna go for it.

906
00:51:42.328 --> 00:51:46.526
you should just lay out your case
and not try to play any games

907
00:51:46.599 --> 00:51:48.726
and just tell someone
what you feel about them.

908
00:51:48.801 --> 00:51:52.168
-I admire him for how he does that here.
-LAMBERT: Okay. I'll retract that.

909
00:51:52.271 --> 00:51:55.729
WEITZ: Well. I don't know. I mean. maybe
you wanna go about it differently. Pete.

910
00:51:55.808 --> 00:51:57.742
-It's up to you.
-LAMBERT: Okay.

911
00:51:57.810 --> 00:52:02.804
WEITZ: But all I'm saying is that's. I think.
how I first got to date my wife.

912
00:52:02.882 --> 00:52:05.851
-was just by being straight with her.
-LAMBERT: Belligerent.

913
00:52:05.918 --> 00:52:07.112
WEITZ: And grabbing her.

914
00:52:07.186 --> 00:52:11.486
No. it was by...
I said. you know. "I like you and I think

915
00:52:11.557 --> 00:52:14.549
"that we could have a relationship.
and I'd like to see if that's possible. "

916
00:52:14.627 --> 00:52:16.254
-LAMBERT: Wow. that's amazing.
-Yeah.

917
00:52:16.328 --> 00:52:20.059
-LAMBERT: That's really touching.
-And it worked. I think.

918
00:52:20.132 --> 00:52:21.793
-She's still here.
-LAMBERT: I think it did.

919
00:52:21.867 --> 00:52:23.425
WEITZ: She's waving at me right now.
yeah. yeah.

920
00:52:23.502 --> 00:52:24.901
LAMBERT: Aw...

921
00:52:24.970 --> 00:52:27.962
Should we explain that we're not
in the same room at the moment?

922
00:52:28.040 --> 00:52:30.270
-WEITZ: I think we did at the beginning.
-Oh. we did. really? Okay.

923
00:52:30.342 --> 00:52:34.335
WEITZ: Yeah. But. yeah.
you are connected via the magic of ISDN.

924
00:52:34.413 --> 00:52:35.573
I don't even know
what the heck that means.

925
00:52:35.648 --> 00:52:37.343
LAMBERT: I'm not actually watching
the movie at the moment.

926
00:52:37.416 --> 00:52:38.508
WEITZ: All you can do is hear it.

927
00:52:38.584 --> 00:52:41.519
so that's why occasionally
I describe what's happening.

928
00:52:44.323 --> 00:52:45.654
LAMBERT: Now. maybe we should
talk about the movie.

929
00:52:45.724 --> 00:52:49.285
WEITZ: Yeah. okay. now Jacob's doing
what he should do. I think.

930
00:52:49.929 --> 00:52:51.556
LAMBERT: Yeah. definitely.

931
00:52:52.498 --> 00:52:55.023
WEITZ: But Bella can't. Bella can't do it.

932
00:52:56.001 --> 00:53:01.098
And this is a very sad moment here.
They're both trapped. really.

933
00:53:02.875 --> 00:53:04.843
LAMBERT: This music.
which is Jacob's theme.

934
00:53:04.910 --> 00:53:08.641
has a great quality
of being kind of unresolved.

935
00:53:10.115 --> 00:53:12.913
You get a lot with the music
that accompanies him

936
00:53:12.985 --> 00:53:15.146
a sort of a repetitive motif

937
00:53:15.221 --> 00:53:18.315
that never quite lands
where you hope it will.

938
00:53:18.390 --> 00:53:19.823
which I think is a really nice way

939
00:53:19.892 --> 00:53:22.156
-of illustrating Jacob's feelings.
-WEITZ: Notice also. though.

940
00:53:22.228 --> 00:53:23.991
if you go back about 5 seconds.

941
00:53:24.063 --> 00:53:27.829
old Jacob had snuck his left hand
onto Bella's right knee.

942
00:53:27.900 --> 00:53:31.495
-LAMBERT: Yeah.
-You know. cheeky.

943
00:53:31.570 --> 00:53:35.006
LAMBERT: Yeah. there's a couple
of little cheeky continuity errors. as well.

944
00:53:35.074 --> 00:53:37.872
if you wanna look carefully
around that area.

945
00:53:37.943 --> 00:53:40.411
WEITZ: Continuity. by the way.
being in editing terms.

946
00:53:40.479 --> 00:53:45.007
making sure that things match.
so you don't cut from one moment

947
00:53:45.084 --> 00:53:46.676
where a guy is standing
with his arms crossed.

948
00:53:46.752 --> 00:53:49.516
and then the next moment his hands are up
in the air.

949
00:53:50.089 --> 00:53:54.219
Now. when I worked on this scene
in the script.

950
00:53:55.160 --> 00:54:00.655
I pushed for Jacob to be suddenly
and unexpectedly aggressive.

951
00:54:02.268 --> 00:54:06.261
And people were like.
"Well. that's weird. Why would he do that?"

952
00:54:07.072 --> 00:54:09.404
And I thought. "Well. this will be good.

953
00:54:09.475 --> 00:54:11.500
"It'll signal something is up.
something's wrong here.

954
00:54:12.645 --> 00:54:17.105
"and this usually very sweet-natured Jacob
is acting very odd. "

955
00:54:17.983 --> 00:54:21.043
BELLA: (ON PHONE) He won't let me visit.
but would you call me?

956
00:54:21.120 --> 00:54:23.486
LAMBERT: And it's a little gesture

957
00:54:23.555 --> 00:54:27.582
towards the sort of sudden nature
of the transformation

958
00:54:27.660 --> 00:54:30.925
from human being to wolf.
which is gonna come later. as well. isn't it?

959
00:54:30.996 --> 00:54:33.829
WEITZ: Yeah. that it's very. very rapid-fire.

960
00:54:34.667 --> 00:54:37.693
BELLA: I just wanted to hear your voice.
so no pressure.

961
00:54:40.873 --> 00:54:42.101
Jacob. please...

962
00:54:44.009 --> 00:54:45.169
Call me.

963
00:54:45.244 --> 00:54:49.704
WEITZ: Okay. so that was fake rain.
by the way. amazing fake rain.

964
00:54:51.016 --> 00:54:53.109
What the heck is going on
with that salmon up there.

965
00:54:53.185 --> 00:54:55.153
which seems to be swimming around
without any skin?

966
00:54:55.220 --> 00:54:57.313
He's a pre-smoked salmon.

967
00:54:57.389 --> 00:55:01.587
It's amazing that you can catch
pre-smoked salmon in Forks. Washington.

968
00:55:02.428 --> 00:55:07.866
Anyway...
So. okay. Bella's very much realizing

969
00:55:07.933 --> 00:55:14.236
how much of a lifesaver Jacob has been.
and is about to go over to him.

970
00:55:14.306 --> 00:55:20.336
But meanwhile. we're still trying to press
the fact that people are dying in Forks.

971
00:55:21.213 --> 00:55:24.740
leading to the question.
why is Charlie going fishing?

972
00:55:25.317 --> 00:55:27.308
Why isn't he on the case?

973
00:55:27.386 --> 00:55:31.186
Okay. well. this moment usually leads
to some hoots and hollers.

974
00:55:31.957 --> 00:55:38.658
Jacob. short hair. buffed out. tattoo. damn.

975
00:55:39.131 --> 00:55:41.258
I think that was my swear. wasn't it?

976
00:55:41.333 --> 00:55:44.325
LAMBERT: I don't know.
I think you may have used 2 now. Chris.

977
00:55:44.403 --> 00:55:46.268
WEITZ: Oh. no. Oh. dear.

978
00:55:46.338 --> 00:55:48.738
LAMBERT: We'll have to
do the whole thing again.

979
00:55:49.475 --> 00:55:51.966
WEITZ: Well. now. I love this sequence.

980
00:55:52.044 --> 00:55:54.274
although it really involved
torturing the poor actors.

981
00:55:54.346 --> 00:55:56.940
because all this rain is fake rain.
but it's very. very cold.

982
00:55:57.015 --> 00:55:59.540
Imagine. it's very cold
here in British Columbia.

983
00:56:00.018 --> 00:56:04.717
I'm all dressed up in a parka. you know.
with a scarf and a nice hat.

984
00:56:04.790 --> 00:56:08.726
and poor Taylor is naked from the waist up.

985
00:56:08.827 --> 00:56:13.924
and we're dumping ice cold water
from these towers onto them.

986
00:56:16.135 --> 00:56:19.730
For about the first few takes.
Kristen's contacts.

987
00:56:19.805 --> 00:56:22.205
because you know
she has these hazel eyes.

988
00:56:22.274 --> 00:56:25.641
which are. you know. quite a special color.

989
00:56:25.711 --> 00:56:30.944
and they're re-colored with brown contacts.

990
00:56:31.283 --> 00:56:32.477
they were getting washed out.

991
00:56:32.551 --> 00:56:36.612
So. eventually the eye color
that was put back in was done with CGI.

992
00:56:39.825 --> 00:56:42.385
Yeah. poor Taylor here is...

993
00:56:42.461 --> 00:56:44.656
I mean. you can tell. actually.
from some of these shots

994
00:56:44.730 --> 00:56:49.099
that the water's so cold
that steam is rising off him.

995
00:56:49.168 --> 00:56:51.636
which only works to my advantage

996
00:56:51.703 --> 00:56:56.299
because. of course. he's supposed to be
a wolf running a very high temperature.

997
00:56:56.375 --> 00:56:58.741
But there are moments
where you can almost tell

998
00:56:58.811 --> 00:57:02.406
that he's shivering with the cold.
but I see it as intense emotion.

999
00:57:03.715 --> 00:57:06.912
LAMBERT: I remember this was shot
within the first week of shooting. I think.

1000
00:57:06.985 --> 00:57:08.612
-WEITZ: Yeah.
-And I remember

1001
00:57:08.687 --> 00:57:11.053
it was definitely one of Taylor's
first big scenes.

1002
00:57:11.123 --> 00:57:14.581
and I remember just watching.
the day after in the dailies trailer.

1003
00:57:14.660 --> 00:57:16.651
all of the material that was shot for this

1004
00:57:16.728 --> 00:57:19.629
and there just being
this kind of palpable feeling of excitement

1005
00:57:19.698 --> 00:57:21.666
that he was really nailing it.

1006
00:57:21.733 --> 00:57:25.567
-It's a good scene.
WEITZ: Yeah. it's a really lovely one.

1007
00:57:25.637 --> 00:57:27.161
and Taylor is great in it.

1008
00:57:27.239 --> 00:57:30.333
and I always knew
he was gonna bring it home.

1009
00:57:30.409 --> 00:57:32.274
which makes me so proud of him.

1010
00:57:32.344 --> 00:57:33.436
Maybe give me. like.

1011
00:57:33.512 --> 00:57:34.570
some time or something.

1012
00:57:34.646 --> 00:57:37.206
LAMBERT: Incidentally.
there's a little musical motif coming up.

1013
00:57:37.282 --> 00:57:39.716
which is almost my favorite bit
of music in the movie.

1014
00:57:39.785 --> 00:57:42.083
and it never recurs anywhere else in it.

1015
00:57:42.154 --> 00:57:45.954
-but it's an absolute humdinger.
-WEITZ: Which bit?

1016
00:57:46.391 --> 00:57:48.791
LAMBERT: It's literally about to happen

1017
00:57:48.861 --> 00:57:51.659
if I'm hearing this at the same time
as you are.

1018
00:57:51.730 --> 00:57:54.290
It's coming up now. It's just amazing.

1019
00:57:55.133 --> 00:57:59.194
It kind of swells. They swell it in the mix.
and here it goes. Now.

1020
00:57:59.738 --> 00:58:01.467
Not anymore.

1021
00:58:02.407 --> 00:58:04.568
This doesn't even matter. All right?

1022
00:58:04.977 --> 00:58:06.274
LAMBERT: And Alexandre's
only used it once.

1023
00:58:06.345 --> 00:58:08.575
so he could probably get away
with ripping himself off

1024
00:58:08.647 --> 00:58:11.275
-and putting it in another film a lot.
-WEITZ: Why not?

1025
00:58:11.350 --> 00:58:15.309
Yeah. no. that is nice.
the way those strings are

1026
00:58:15.787 --> 00:58:20.554
sort of competing with each other
and swelling.

1027
00:58:21.159 --> 00:58:23.389
I don't know much about music.

1028
00:58:24.763 --> 00:58:27.163
Anyway. this is a very sad scene.

1029
00:58:27.566 --> 00:58:31.002
LAMBERT: Should we talk about
what the rain did to the microphones.

1030
00:58:31.069 --> 00:58:33.196
-that it made it a little difficult?
-WEITZ: Oh. yeah. of course.

1031
00:58:33.272 --> 00:58:35.035
We had to rerecord all the dialogue here

1032
00:58:35.107 --> 00:58:37.541
because the rain
was hitting the microphones.

1033
00:58:37.609 --> 00:58:41.306
Taylor couldn't wear a microphone
on his body

1034
00:58:41.380 --> 00:58:43.780
because there's nothing to attach it to.

1035
00:58:44.483 --> 00:58:47.543
So all of this is rerecorded.
but it's rerecorded to match

1036
00:58:47.619 --> 00:58:53.080
exactly the sort of tone
in which they said it the first time.

1037
00:58:53.559 --> 00:58:56.687
So. it's pretty much just what we had.

1038
00:58:56.795 --> 00:59:00.993
LAMBERT: Now. is there something
hanging off the back of Bella's rucksack?

1039
00:59:01.066 --> 00:59:04.001
WEITZ: There is something. which might
refer to a previous movie of mine.

1040
00:59:04.069 --> 00:59:06.128
which did not go as well as this one.

1041
00:59:06.572 --> 00:59:08.199
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1042
00:59:08.273 --> 00:59:10.901
LAMBERT: That's right.
There's an American Pie in her backpack.

1043
00:59:10.976 --> 00:59:12.034
WEITZ: Yes.

1044
00:59:14.613 --> 00:59:16.137
Okay. so...

1045
00:59:17.649 --> 00:59:19.014
(WEITZ SNORTS)

1046
00:59:19.084 --> 00:59:21.416
Sorry that was just me snorting.

1047
00:59:22.888 --> 00:59:28.087
I think some of these diamond shots
are not our best. I'll be honest about it.

1048
00:59:28.160 --> 00:59:30.924
And. you know. you get the effect
and then it goes...

1049
00:59:30.996 --> 00:59:32.088
Oh. that's a nice one. though.

1050
00:59:32.164 --> 00:59:34.928
-This is nice. when he's doing this.
-LAMBERT: The one on the side is amazing.

1051
00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:36.024
-the top shots...
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1052
00:59:36.101 --> 00:59:39.434
LAMBERT: We were just like. "If we'd had
one more day before our deadline... "

1053
00:59:39.504 --> 00:59:41.529
WEITZ: Yeah.
the top shots we dialed up too high.

1054
00:59:41.607 --> 00:59:44.940
and I apologize to Susan MacLeod.
our visual effects supervisor.

1055
00:59:45.010 --> 00:59:46.409
for having done that.

1056
00:59:46.478 --> 00:59:48.446
You have to be very careful
when these effects come in

1057
00:59:48.513 --> 00:59:51.414
and then you start treating things in the DI.
the digital intermediate.

1058
00:59:51.483 --> 00:59:56.420
where you can change the lighting
and color on things.

1059
00:59:56.488 --> 00:59:58.979
and these effects are very fragile
when you receive them.

1060
00:59:59.057 --> 01:00:02.288
and just one little tweak
one way or the other

1061
01:00:02.861 --> 01:00:08.231
can make them kind of buzz
or can completely make them disappear.

1062
01:00:08.300 --> 01:00:11.133
Anyway. Bella has a terrible stomachache
at this moment.

1063
01:00:11.203 --> 01:00:14.195
and then who should appear but Laurent?

1064
01:00:16.208 --> 01:00:19.143
Well. of course. we did all this stuff.

1065
01:00:19.211 --> 01:00:24.012
all this beautiful reshooting
of this meadow.

1066
01:00:24.349 --> 01:00:29.878
in order to then establish that it looked
terrible and depressing and dead now.

1067
01:00:29.955 --> 01:00:34.756
So. the garden sequences
from the first movie we reshot in this place

1068
01:00:35.127 --> 01:00:37.721
in order to proliferate it
with flowers and what not.

1069
01:00:37.796 --> 01:00:41.789
And here comes Edi Gathegi.
very good man.

1070
01:00:43.135 --> 01:00:46.298
Not a Rastafarian. actually.
that is also a wig.

1071
01:00:48.473 --> 01:00:53.877
And. again. the danger brings on
the apparition of Edward.

1072
01:00:53.945 --> 01:00:55.640
One thing we should say
about the apparition shots

1073
01:00:55.714 --> 01:00:59.844
is that when we decided to do it.

1074
01:00:59.918 --> 01:01:02.216
I wanted them to be as subtle as possible

1075
01:01:02.287 --> 01:01:05.882
and impose some kind of elegant metaphor
on them.

1076
01:01:05.957 --> 01:01:08.892
visual metaphor.
so that they turned out a certain way.

1077
01:01:08.994 --> 01:01:13.931
And in this case. we used elements
of a candle's flame moving very slowly.

1078
01:01:13.999 --> 01:01:16.968
so that when he flickers.
the bits of him that are opaque

1079
01:01:17.035 --> 01:01:19.003
and the bits that are translucent

1080
01:01:22.007 --> 01:01:25.909
are mapped onto an image
of a candle's flame.

1081
01:01:26.278 --> 01:01:29.111
So that is what is determining
the kind of physics

1082
01:01:29.181 --> 01:01:32.014
of how we're seeing him
and not seeing him.

1083
01:01:34.319 --> 01:01:40.417
Now. Laurent. wearing what I like to call
his vampire pimp outfit.

1084
01:01:40.659 --> 01:01:42.217
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1085
01:01:44.129 --> 01:01:46.427
'Cause I think
that's what a vampire pimp would wear.

1086
01:01:46.498 --> 01:01:47.988
-LAMBERT: Totally.
-Yeah.

1087
01:01:50.068 --> 01:01:53.834
Here to inject a little fright
into the proceedings.

1088
01:01:56.074 --> 01:02:01.979
Rather fun because. of course. we seem
to remember him as a positive figure

1089
01:02:02.047 --> 01:02:04.538
from the last one.
where he was cooperative with the Cullens.

1090
01:02:04.616 --> 01:02:05.844
-LAMBERT: He's fickle.
-Yeah.

1091
01:02:05.917 --> 01:02:08.442
He is fickle.
Well. you can't depend on Laurent.

1092
01:02:08.520 --> 01:02:11.045
We're not gonna have to worry
about him much anymore after this

1093
01:02:12.190 --> 01:02:14.715
'cause the wolves are gonna get him.

1094
01:02:18.363 --> 01:02:22.493
You'll notice that there was a little bit there
where we changed Bella's eye line

1095
01:02:22.567 --> 01:02:26.435
to represent it as though she were looking
at someone far away

1096
01:02:26.505 --> 01:02:27.995
and then at someone very close.

1097
01:02:28.073 --> 01:02:32.134
Another very simple in-camera way
to show the vampires moving quickly

1098
01:02:32.210 --> 01:02:33.700
without having to show them.

1099
01:02:36.548 --> 01:02:39.483
-WEITZ: "I don't believe it. "
-"I don't believe it. "

1100
01:02:41.453 --> 01:02:43.751
WEITZ: Here come the wolves.

1101
01:02:45.023 --> 01:02:50.586
So. here is Sam-wolf. and this went through
hundreds of iterations

1102
01:02:50.662 --> 01:02:52.357
to make him dark enough.

1103
01:02:52.430 --> 01:02:54.455
to make him reflect the light
in the right way.

1104
01:02:54.533 --> 01:02:56.524
to make the wind move him enough.

1105
01:02:56.601 --> 01:03:01.095
to make sure that when he breathed.
it'd reflect the cold of the atmosphere.

1106
01:03:01.907 --> 01:03:05.343
And in this shot.
he always reminds me of a friend of mine's.

1107
01:03:05.410 --> 01:03:08.243
now passed away. Pomeranian.

1108
01:03:08.313 --> 01:03:09.803
(LAMBERT CHUCKLES)

1109
01:03:09.881 --> 01:03:10.939
LAMBERT: But not for long.

1110
01:03:11.016 --> 01:03:15.510
WEITZ: Okay.
here's our first vampire speed shot.

1111
01:03:15.821 --> 01:03:17.550
Well. actually.
we've seen little bits of it here.

1112
01:03:17.622 --> 01:03:20.182
I love this shot. This is gorgeous.

1113
01:03:20.258 --> 01:03:22.692
That's a gorgeous little CGI shot
with Bella reflected.

1114
01:03:22.761 --> 01:03:26.822
We took an element of Bella
and mapped it onto an eye.

1115
01:03:27.098 --> 01:03:31.899
The iris was colored based upon Taylor's.

1116
01:03:32.037 --> 01:03:34.130
and it all turned out lovely.

1117
01:03:34.906 --> 01:03:40.970
Here is Laurent ready to pimp slap a wolf.

1118
01:03:41.313 --> 01:03:44.646
LAMBERT: Great bit of sound work there
from Scott Hecker and the sound guys.

1119
01:03:44.716 --> 01:03:47.082
WEITZ: Lovely stuff
of the galloping wolves coming up.

1120
01:03:47.152 --> 01:03:51.316
And so now we're gonna...
You know. Bella has run away

1121
01:03:51.389 --> 01:03:53.755
before she's seen
the conclusion of this fight.

1122
01:03:53.825 --> 01:03:58.990
so there's kind of a Laurent wolf fight
Rashômon thing that's gonna go on.

1123
01:03:59.064 --> 01:04:05.765
Where she perceives it as impossible
that the wolves could have killed Laurent.

1124
01:04:06.872 --> 01:04:11.536
Also notice Harry looking very antsy

1125
01:04:11.610 --> 01:04:14.010
about the wolves having been discovered.

1126
01:04:14.746 --> 01:04:16.373
Not stoked.

1127
01:04:16.448 --> 01:04:18.177
LAMBERT: We notice it. but Charlie doesn't.

1128
01:04:18.250 --> 01:04:19.308
WEITZ: Yeah. Charlie. Charlie...

1129
01:04:19.384 --> 01:04:21.045
LAMBERT: He's
the least perceptive policeman.

1130
01:04:21.119 --> 01:04:24.418
WEITZ: Super cop Charlie.
not noticing these subtleties.

1131
01:04:24.489 --> 01:04:27.117
Okay. here's Bella's imagining.
I love this shot.

1132
01:04:27.192 --> 01:04:30.958
of what Laurent's gonna do to these guys.

1133
01:04:31.029 --> 01:04:34.260
which is. you know. take them out.

1134
01:04:34.599 --> 01:04:36.999
LAMBERT: This was a kind of
completely unscripted thing. wasn't it?

1135
01:04:39.871 --> 01:04:43.272
As I remember it. there was a weather issue
when this stuff was being shot

1136
01:04:43.508 --> 01:04:47.205
of Laurent running from the wolves
with the visual effects guys.

1137
01:04:47.279 --> 01:04:49.907
-WEITZ: Correct.
-And they had a bit of extra time.

1138
01:04:49.981 --> 01:04:53.781
and Edi said.
"I would love to fight the wolves. "

1139
01:04:53.852 --> 01:04:57.413
So they shot a bunch of stuff.
and then later in the edit we sort of...

1140
01:04:57.489 --> 01:04:59.184
-WEITZ: We added in some wolves.
-...just suddenly realized

1141
01:04:59.257 --> 01:05:01.054
it would be really cool to drop it in
in different places.

1142
01:05:01.126 --> 01:05:02.684
WEITZ: I mean. Edi basically said.

1143
01:05:02.761 --> 01:05:06.390
"Laurent would not go out like that.
just running. He would turn and fight. "

1144
01:05:06.464 --> 01:05:08.830
And so we ended up
with this kind of cool stuff.

1145
01:05:08.900 --> 01:05:11.835
LAMBERT: And then. prudent actor that he is.
he then gave a series of interviews

1146
01:05:11.903 --> 01:05:13.666
where he told people
that we were gonna see him

1147
01:05:13.738 --> 01:05:15.865
being attacked by the wolves
at the end of the movie.

1148
01:05:15.941 --> 01:05:17.909
at which point we were pretty much tied
into doing it.

1149
01:05:17.976 --> 01:05:19.034
and it works well.

1150
01:05:19.110 --> 01:05:24.446
WEITZ: So there's this lovely parkour moment
or free running moment.

1151
01:05:24.516 --> 01:05:26.177
where Jacob jumps up.

1152
01:05:26.251 --> 01:05:27.741
And that's really Taylor
doing his own stunt.

1153
01:05:27.819 --> 01:05:31.482
He had a wire on him. but only to keep him
from falling to his death.

1154
01:05:31.556 --> 01:05:33.148
not to help him jump.

1155
01:05:33.658 --> 01:05:37.651
And the tree outside Bella's window
was constructed specifically.

1156
01:05:37.729 --> 01:05:40.630
it was made in order to allow for that gag.

1157
01:05:43.902 --> 01:05:46.700
And I always wanted to put a little music
over this shot of the...

1158
01:05:48.873 --> 01:05:52.434
-LAMBERT: The evil Brady Bunch music?
-Yeah.

1159
01:05:53.278 --> 01:05:55.906
But it seemed a bit too much.

1160
01:05:55.981 --> 01:05:57.346
LAMBERT: Alexandre did
write something for that.

1161
01:05:57.415 --> 01:05:58.473
WEITZ: He did.

1162
01:05:58.550 --> 01:06:01.451
LAMBERT: But we'd had music so recently
that it was just a real push.

1163
01:06:01.519 --> 01:06:03.714
WEITZ: Yeah. it seemed like we were trying
to push it too much.

1164
01:06:03.788 --> 01:06:10.421
But people sort of get it
that Jacob is heartened by this view

1165
01:06:10.729 --> 01:06:14.130
and the fact that she's actually got it
hanging over her head

1166
01:06:14.199 --> 01:06:16.929
when she sleeps is very touching to him.

1167
01:06:17.002 --> 01:06:18.867
And now they realize how much
they have in common.

1168
01:06:18.937 --> 01:06:23.397
How they've both been trapped
in this kind of web of supernatural terror.

1169
01:06:23.475 --> 01:06:26.774
I suppose. when he sees the bite

1170
01:06:29.447 --> 01:06:34.180
-that James inflicted on Bella.
-LAMBERT: Yes. yes.

1171
01:06:35.653 --> 01:06:40.386
Bella. do you remember
when we walked on the beach at La Push?

1172
01:06:40.925 --> 01:06:42.517
WEITZ: Yeah.
there's a rather touching moment now

1173
01:06:42.594 --> 01:06:46.997
where Bella can't remember
Jacob's side of the story.

1174
01:06:47.465 --> 01:06:50.866
He's trying to tell her. but she can
only remember the Eddy part of it.

1175
01:06:52.003 --> 01:06:54.904
the Ed part of it.
the Edward part of it. rather.

1176
01:06:54.973 --> 01:06:57.703
I guess I understand
why that's the only part you remember.

1177
01:06:57.776 --> 01:07:00.711
WEITZ: This is very sweet.
the way he says that.

1178
01:07:03.615 --> 01:07:08.882
And then Bella says the most extraordinary
thing. which is. "Let's run away. "

1179
01:07:08.953 --> 01:07:12.389
And I think it's allowable.

1180
01:07:12.457 --> 01:07:16.757
You know. you think she wouldn't say that.
what with Ed and her mind the way it is.

1181
01:07:16.828 --> 01:07:18.921
but she says it before
she even realizes what she's saying.

1182
01:07:19.064 --> 01:07:24.092
And it's out of the deep.
you know. friendship.

1183
01:07:24.169 --> 01:07:26.160
the love that comes from friendship.

1184
01:07:26.237 --> 01:07:28.569
And I think she says it before
she's realized she has.

1185
01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:30.631
-And then it kind of leads...
-LAMBERT: Then you see her.

1186
01:07:30.708 --> 01:07:33.677
and she does a good job
of then double-taking almost.

1187
01:07:33.745 --> 01:07:36.339
-as she realizes what she said.
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1188
01:07:36.714 --> 01:07:40.206
But I would run away with you

1189
01:07:44.489 --> 01:07:45.581
if I could.

1190
01:07:45.657 --> 01:07:48.057
WEITZ: This is another "Aw" moment for me.

1191
01:07:50.929 --> 01:07:52.897
-LAMBERT: Back in with the color.
-I think Alexandre's music is

1192
01:07:52.964 --> 01:07:55.865
-very lovely here. the way it comes back in.
-LAMBERT: Yeah. yeah.

1193
01:07:57.268 --> 01:08:00.863
WEITZ: Now we stay out in the 2-shot here.
rather than going to close-ups.

1194
01:08:00.939 --> 01:08:03.305
Why? Because...

1195
01:08:04.075 --> 01:08:07.442
Well. because you can see the way
that Bella's touching his back.

1196
01:08:07.512 --> 01:08:10.413
you can see the way
that she leans against his chest

1197
01:08:10.482 --> 01:08:14.578
and you can guess at their emotions
rather than seeing it in their faces.

1198
01:08:14.652 --> 01:08:17.018
I think there's something rather touching
about that.

1199
01:08:19.324 --> 01:08:22.293
Uh-oh. nightmare coming.

1200
01:08:24.529 --> 01:08:26.588
LAMBERT: Again. no CG there.
He really jumped out of that window

1201
01:08:26.664 --> 01:08:28.188
-with a cable.
-WEITZ: He really jumped.

1202
01:08:28.266 --> 01:08:30.325
He really jumped on a cable.

1203
01:08:31.402 --> 01:08:34.030
He's very daring. I would not do that.

1204
01:08:35.940 --> 01:08:40.400
LAMBERT: So the leaves that we keep
coming back to. to represent nightmares.

1205
01:08:40.478 --> 01:08:43.242
I can't even remember
where we found those in the dailies.

1206
01:08:43.314 --> 01:08:45.214
-WEITZ: But they were from...
-They became a kind of shorthand.

1207
01:08:45.283 --> 01:08:46.511
-didn't they?
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1208
01:08:46.584 --> 01:08:48.347
LAMBERT: You know what.
they were from the actual...

1209
01:08:48.419 --> 01:08:50.410
They were outtakes
from when Sam is carrying her.

1210
01:08:50.488 --> 01:08:55.425
WEITZ: Yeah. exactly. They were the moment
when the camera is sliding into position.

1211
01:08:55.493 --> 01:08:57.427
but not quite there yet.

1212
01:08:59.297 --> 01:09:03.700
And. well. this dream
is. of course. about Bella's realizing

1213
01:09:04.369 --> 01:09:06.701
that Jacob is a wolf. somehow.

1214
01:09:06.771 --> 01:09:10.537
although not fully viscerally realizing it.
'cause that's yet to come.

1215
01:09:10.608 --> 01:09:13.076
But she's starting
to put the pieces together.

1216
01:09:14.412 --> 01:09:16.277
And in the book in fact. though.

1217
01:09:16.347 --> 01:09:19.441
vis-à-vis the leaves. her nightmares
are really about emptiness. I think.

1218
01:09:19.517 --> 01:09:23.453
LAMBERT: Yeah. they're about
her being in the woods. aren't they?

1219
01:09:23.521 --> 01:09:25.079
WEITZ: Indeed they are.

1220
01:09:26.658 --> 01:09:28.216
Okay. I'm sorry. I really need to see him.

1221
01:09:28.293 --> 01:09:31.126
LAMBERT: This is great. this little set.

1222
01:09:31.429 --> 01:09:33.158
-So. then anytime you see...
-WEITZ: Yeah. fantastic set

1223
01:09:33.231 --> 01:09:36.064
which functions for what. 7 seconds.

1224
01:09:36.134 --> 01:09:40.969
But when the kids who are cast
as the Quileutes came and saw it.

1225
01:09:41.039 --> 01:09:44.497
they said "Wow. this is like... "

1226
01:09:44.576 --> 01:09:47.909
-LAMBERT: Were they? Oh. that's good.
-"This is like it is on the rez. "

1227
01:09:48.613 --> 01:09:49.807
-Okay. what did you do?
-Hey.

1228
01:09:49.881 --> 01:09:51.542
-What did you do to him?
-Easy!

1229
01:09:51.616 --> 01:09:53.675
WEITZ: Now. Bella's getting a bit aggro here.
but I love it.

1230
01:09:53.751 --> 01:09:55.582
because she's defending her friend.

1231
01:09:56.154 --> 01:09:58.520
He tells me nothing
because he's scared of you.

1232
01:09:58.590 --> 01:09:59.921
(SNICKERING)

1233
01:10:00.291 --> 01:10:02.054
WEITZ: Oh. you're gonna get a smack.

1234
01:10:02.927 --> 01:10:04.155
(BOTH EXCLAIMING)

1235
01:10:04.796 --> 01:10:06.787
-WEITZ: Oh. no. you didn't.
-Face punch.

1236
01:10:07.131 --> 01:10:08.223
WEITZ: That was a face punch.

1237
01:10:08.299 --> 01:10:10.995
-LAMBERT: Actually it was a face slap.
-It was a face slap. yeah.

1238
01:10:11.069 --> 01:10:12.832
Well. it was slunch.

1239
01:10:13.705 --> 01:10:14.967
A plap.

1240
01:10:16.474 --> 01:10:18.669
Yeah. that was. you know.
obviously a mistake on her part.

1241
01:10:18.743 --> 01:10:21.234
because now he turned into a werewolf.

1242
01:10:21.346 --> 01:10:22.438
Run!

1243
01:10:22.513 --> 01:10:26.415
WEITZ: And here we're setting up this kind of
hug moment. which doesn't happen.

1244
01:10:26.484 --> 01:10:29.851
I rather like setting it up
as though they're going to embrace.

1245
01:10:29.921 --> 01:10:31.650
and then over he goes.

1246
01:10:31.723 --> 01:10:33.088
And. of course. this would have been
a great moment

1247
01:10:33.157 --> 01:10:37.389
had it been seen first in the movie.
but instead we showed it in the 1st trailer.

1248
01:10:37.595 --> 01:10:38.994
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1249
01:10:39.063 --> 01:10:41.657
LAMBERT: And then again in the 2nd
and 3rd and several other trailers.

1250
01:10:41.733 --> 01:10:43.826
WEITZ: Yeah. so that everybody knew.

1251
01:10:43.901 --> 01:10:46.062
LAMBERT: But probably if you looked at
each of those trailers now.

1252
01:10:46.137 --> 01:10:48.731
you could see the development of the wolf
from one to another.

1253
01:10:48.806 --> 01:10:50.865
'cause it's definitely different now
than at the start.

1254
01:10:50.942 --> 01:10:56.608
WEITZ: Definitely that shot went through
550 something different versions.

1255
01:10:56.681 --> 01:11:01.084
And each time. as you progress.
the musculature moves differently.

1256
01:11:01.152 --> 01:11:04.144
the fur behaves differently.
the wind goes through the fur.

1257
01:11:04.522 --> 01:11:09.323
And here I played a little trick where the
camera gets knocked over by the wolves.

1258
01:11:09.394 --> 01:11:11.191
and you sort of hardly notice it.

1259
01:11:11.262 --> 01:11:15.892
but it was to sort of lend
a little extra credibility to the moment.

1260
01:11:17.702 --> 01:11:22.036
I suppose it's a bit of a joke. too.
an in-joke to oneself.

1261
01:11:22.106 --> 01:11:25.439
Of course the wolves are not real and
they wouldn't knock over a camera ever.

1262
01:11:25.510 --> 01:11:30.413
but it's as though it's a camera
standing there on a tripod

1263
01:11:30.481 --> 01:11:32.506
and the wolves knock it over.

1264
01:11:32.583 --> 01:11:34.414
Now that sound they just made...

1265
01:11:34.485 --> 01:11:35.474
(MIMICKS SOUND)

1266
01:11:35.553 --> 01:11:37.111
...is actually a Quileute thing.

1267
01:11:37.188 --> 01:11:41.591
and it's actually at a higher pitch
than I can do with my voice.

1268
01:11:42.060 --> 01:11:48.488
but it's the kind of thing that young
Quileute dudes do to say hey to each other.

1269
01:11:54.272 --> 01:11:58.868
Oh. hey. about Emily. Sam's fiancée?
Don't stare. It bugs Sam.

1270
01:12:01.512 --> 01:12:03.207
Why would I stare?

1271
01:12:03.281 --> 01:12:06.409
Are you guys hungry? Like I have to ask.

1272
01:12:06.651 --> 01:12:08.118
(EMILY LAUGHING)

1273
01:12:13.825 --> 01:12:15.417
Who's this?

1274
01:12:15.560 --> 01:12:16.618
JARED: Bella Swan

1275
01:12:16.694 --> 01:12:19.060
WEITZ: This is Tinsel Korey.
who does a lovely job as Emily.

1276
01:12:19.130 --> 01:12:20.859
LAMBERT: She's about to call Bella "Muffin. "

1277
01:12:20.932 --> 01:12:23.298
as was always our joke
in the cutting rooms.

1278
01:12:23.368 --> 01:12:25.029
-Or has she done it already?
-WEITZ: Nope.

1279
01:12:25.103 --> 01:12:30.234
She's going to. and we always laughed.

1280
01:12:30.541 --> 01:12:33.738
-We snickered like a couple of school girls.
-LAMBERT: Oh. how we laughed.

1281
01:12:34.178 --> 01:12:37.375
WEITZ: Now. of course
she's really offering Bella a muffin.

1282
01:12:37.448 --> 01:12:40.383
but we thought it almost seemed like
she was calling her muffin.

1283
01:12:40.451 --> 01:12:43.420
and that was the funniest thing
we'd ever heard in our lives.

1284
01:12:43.488 --> 01:12:46.286
LAMBERT: (LAUGHING)
I still laugh thinking about it now.

1285
01:12:46.357 --> 01:12:49.258
You've got to understand that we spent
a lot of hours in the cutting rooms

1286
01:12:49.327 --> 01:12:50.351
on this movie.

1287
01:12:50.428 --> 01:12:53.864
WEITZ: Yeah.
We go a little crazy in a dark room

1288
01:12:55.233 --> 01:12:57.394
looking at footage again and again.

1289
01:12:57.769 --> 01:13:01.000
Would you shut up?
These are trade secrets. Damn it!

1290
01:13:01.072 --> 01:13:02.471
LAMBERT: Bella makes a little joke here.

1291
01:13:02.540 --> 01:13:06.374
WEITZ: Yeah. she tries to be funny.
"You can't run with vampires. "

1292
01:13:08.713 --> 01:13:10.704
Emily gets it. The other kids don't.

1293
01:13:12.917 --> 01:13:15.147
Now this is a beautiful decoration job

1294
01:13:15.219 --> 01:13:18.677
done by the production design team.
set decoration team.

1295
01:13:18.756 --> 01:13:23.625
because this was a kind of
abandoned little shed

1296
01:13:24.095 --> 01:13:26.427
that was turned into this lovely.

1297
01:13:28.900 --> 01:13:32.734
you know. homey. sort of fairy tale
little cottage.

1298
01:13:33.905 --> 01:13:36.874
And here it was very important to me
that we see that Bella can't look.

1299
01:13:36.941 --> 01:13:38.135
but it's not because of the scar.

1300
01:13:38.209 --> 01:13:41.872
It's because Sam and Emily are in love
and are together.

1301
01:13:46.717 --> 01:13:47.775
Sorry.

1302
01:13:47.852 --> 01:13:51.549
WEITZ: I love that little moment.
That was an ad-lib by Alex. very. very funny.

1303
01:13:54.959 --> 01:13:57.154
Now they have the werewolf talk.

1304
01:13:57.228 --> 01:13:58.991
LAMBERT: First day of shooting was this.
the wolf talk?

1305
01:13:59.063 --> 01:14:01.258
WEITZ: Yeah. this was the first day
of shooting on Vancouver Island.

1306
01:14:01.332 --> 01:14:05.462
Those were skip dissolves
where you maintain exactly the same frame

1307
01:14:05.536 --> 01:14:09.973
but you position and dissolve the actors
into different places.

1308
01:14:10.041 --> 01:14:12.874
LAMBERT: If we hadn't dissolved.
they would be jump cuts.

1309
01:14:12.944 --> 01:14:15.310
-WEITZ: They would be. But they're not.
-To continue the lesson. yeah.

1310
01:14:15.379 --> 01:14:17.643
WEITZ: Or it would have been
an extraordinarily long shot.

1311
01:14:17.715 --> 01:14:19.114
LAMBERT: Yeah. Okay. yeah.

1312
01:14:20.451 --> 01:14:25.013
WEITZ: So. yes. this is our very first day.
and while we were shooting this scene...

1313
01:14:25.089 --> 01:14:29.389
We shot this scene and
the beach rescue scene on the same day.

1314
01:14:29.460 --> 01:14:31.485
And during the time that
we were shooting this scene.

1315
01:14:31.562 --> 01:14:35.965
there was this overcast.
there was direct sunshine.

1316
01:14:36.400 --> 01:14:40.393
there was hail. unbelievably. there was hail.

1317
01:14:40.471 --> 01:14:43.372
and I just thought.
what more can Mother Nature throw at us

1318
01:14:43.441 --> 01:14:48.401
to mess up our shooting day?
But somehow we managed.

1319
01:14:48.980 --> 01:14:53.041
You know. the shot back towards
Jacob was actually much more sunny.

1320
01:14:53.117 --> 01:14:57.713
and what we did was take the blue
from the sky and desaturate it.

1321
01:14:57.788 --> 01:15:02.225
so that it's gray. which matches
with the look back at Bella.

1322
01:15:02.760 --> 01:15:05.058
and it all kind of matches together.

1323
01:15:05.696 --> 01:15:08.688
Now we're gonna find out
what really happened to Laurent.

1324
01:15:09.100 --> 01:15:11.967
-The one thing we do kill. Rastafarians.
-LAMBERT: Rastafarians.

1325
01:15:12.069 --> 01:15:13.536
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1326
01:15:14.672 --> 01:15:15.730
Wait. Jake. you can't.

1327
01:15:15.806 --> 01:15:18.070
Don't worry.
We can't touch your little precious Cullens...

1328
01:15:18.609 --> 01:15:20.167
WEITZ: A little reference to the treaty

1329
01:15:20.244 --> 01:15:24.044
and then we'll see Laurent
getting ripped up.

1330
01:15:24.382 --> 01:15:27.613
LAMBERT: I think the flash of Laurent
was really also a useful way of us

1331
01:15:27.685 --> 01:15:30.518
cutting some unnecessary dialogue
out of this scene. wasn't it?

1332
01:15:30.588 --> 01:15:33.352
We used it as a way to skip around a bit.

1333
01:15:34.158 --> 01:15:36.490
WEITZ: Yeah. well. there is a bit where

1334
01:15:37.495 --> 01:15:40.521
Bella thinks for quite a long time

1335
01:15:41.465 --> 01:15:44.332
that Jacob is responsible for all the deaths
that have been occurring.

1336
01:15:44.402 --> 01:15:46.267
having just encountered Laurent.

1337
01:15:46.337 --> 01:15:49.932
So I think that it was better
to move on quickly to the fact that

1338
01:15:50.007 --> 01:15:52.567
Laurent is the murderer in question.

1339
01:15:53.544 --> 01:15:54.909
The butler did it.

1340
01:15:59.050 --> 01:16:01.450
And now. this is just pushing in on Jacob.
He's mad.

1341
01:16:01.519 --> 01:16:04.317
Now he's got it in for Victoria big time.

1342
01:16:05.523 --> 01:16:11.792
So that shot. rather nicely opened
with Bella alone before we rejoined Jacob.

1343
01:16:11.862 --> 01:16:15.491
so it had a sense of her vulnerability
before he shows up.

1344
01:16:16.834 --> 01:16:19.064
And now this great Thom Yorke...

1345
01:16:19.804 --> 01:16:22.898
Oh. wait. okay.
here's another mistake by Jacob.

1346
01:16:23.708 --> 01:16:25.573
LAMBERT: Yeah. yeah.
go inside. Unbelievable.

1347
01:16:25.643 --> 01:16:27.543
WEITZ: "Come in for a cup of tea. Jacob. "

1348
01:16:27.612 --> 01:16:31.309
Have some tea before you go off
chasing vampires. See what happens.

1349
01:16:31.382 --> 01:16:32.974
Something might happen.

1350
01:16:33.050 --> 01:16:36.247
Look. she wants you to hang around.
Don't go.

1351
01:16:36.320 --> 01:16:38.652
-Oh. he's gone.
-LAMBERT: He's got a vampire to kill.

1352
01:16:38.723 --> 01:16:41.123
WEITZ: Yeah. I know. but I mean.
it can wait 10 minutes.

1353
01:16:41.192 --> 01:16:45.151
LAMBERT: Yeah. I'd let Sam do that.
Let Sam take that on.

1354
01:16:45.229 --> 01:16:48.130
WEITZ: I know. she's like.
"Why did he just... All right. "

1355
01:16:48.199 --> 01:16:49.928
BELLA: Until I'm alone.

1356
01:16:50.001 --> 01:16:52.367
-LAMBERT: This track is great.
-This track is great.

1357
01:16:52.436 --> 01:16:54.700
This shot is very nicely done
by Javier Aguirresarobe.

1358
01:16:54.772 --> 01:16:56.763
because it doesn't just go
from dark to light.

1359
01:16:56.841 --> 01:17:00.607
it goes through the different color
temperatures that it would go through.

1360
01:17:02.146 --> 01:17:06.242
And she's trying to imagine Edward
but can't.

1361
01:17:06.317 --> 01:17:09.013
and there are happy couples all around.

1362
01:17:10.287 --> 01:17:14.724
And so this song from Thom Yorke came in.
and it was a surprising song.

1363
01:17:14.792 --> 01:17:20.526
because it was kind of a bit techno.
and yet it had a tremendous amount of soul.

1364
01:17:20.598 --> 01:17:22.190
but it also had a beat.

1365
01:17:22.266 --> 01:17:26.430
and weirdly. it just fit perfectly
into this kind of action sequence.

1366
01:17:27.905 --> 01:17:30.305
LAMBERT: As our temporary music score.

1367
01:17:30.374 --> 01:17:33.070
we'd had much more kind of
conventional action-y music

1368
01:17:33.144 --> 01:17:36.580
under the whole
wolf-chasing-Victoria sequence.

1369
01:17:36.647 --> 01:17:39.514
And then we put this on. and it turned it
into something a bit more dreamy

1370
01:17:39.583 --> 01:17:41.608
-and strange. And lovely. yeah.
-WEITZ: And weird. yeah.

1371
01:17:41.686 --> 01:17:45.019
LAMBERT: And the whole sentiment
of the lyrics if you pick it up being.

1372
01:17:45.089 --> 01:17:46.920
"You can do no wrong in my eyes. "

1373
01:17:46.991 --> 01:17:49.892
seems very appropriate
for everything that's going on.

1374
01:17:50.528 --> 01:17:53.861
WEITZ: 'Cause this sequence. you know.
really is about

1375
01:17:56.067 --> 01:17:59.468
Jacob protecting Bella.

1376
01:18:00.271 --> 01:18:02.330
LAMBERT: And meanwhile
Bella trying to get Edward.

1377
01:18:02.406 --> 01:18:04.271
WEITZ: Bella seeking Edward.

1378
01:18:05.209 --> 01:18:07.336
LAMBERT: And Victoria mourning James.

1379
01:18:07.411 --> 01:18:08.878
WEITZ: Victoria mourning James.

1380
01:18:08.946 --> 01:18:10.140
-And then...
-LAMBERT: Yeah. and of course.

1381
01:18:10.214 --> 01:18:11.909
poor Charlie's love for Harry.

1382
01:18:11.982 --> 01:18:14.450
WEITZ: Charlie's friend dying.

1383
01:18:15.352 --> 01:18:17.286
which is V sad.

1384
01:18:17.354 --> 01:18:19.948
LAMBERT: (LAUGHS) V sad.
I'm sorry. I didn't mean to make light.

1385
01:18:20.024 --> 01:18:22.015
-WEITZ: Yeah. don't laugh.
-I'm sorry.

1386
01:18:22.093 --> 01:18:27.190
WEITZ: All right. so here's Jacob.
He's had enough of this red-haired chick.

1387
01:18:29.400 --> 01:18:33.564
Okay. there's the shot
that's too cool for school for me.

1388
01:18:34.638 --> 01:18:38.540
You know. I always like CGI shots
to not be too cool.

1389
01:18:39.310 --> 01:18:40.402
LAMBERT: What was that shot? Sorry?

1390
01:18:40.478 --> 01:18:44.574
WEITZ: The first shot where Jacob-wolf
is charging towards Victoria...

1391
01:18:44.648 --> 01:18:45.774
LAMBERT: And it goes in slow mo.

1392
01:18:45.850 --> 01:18:47.750
WEITZ: And there's some distortion
and slow mo.

1393
01:18:47.818 --> 01:18:48.944
LAMBERT: Yeah.

1394
01:18:49.520 --> 01:18:50.544
WEITZ: But it is beautiful.

1395
01:18:50.621 --> 01:18:53.146
That's the very first shot of the movie
that we're looking at right now.

1396
01:18:53.224 --> 01:18:57.422
The very first shot that we took
on Vancouver Island.

1397
01:18:57.495 --> 01:19:02.125
Love this shot because you show how
she's moving so much faster than the crow

1398
01:19:02.199 --> 01:19:04.929
who's just moving backwards in the screen.

1399
01:19:05.002 --> 01:19:08.028
Here comes Victoria running towards us.
camera drops down.

1400
01:19:08.105 --> 01:19:10.198
I should say. I didn't film any of this shot.

1401
01:19:10.274 --> 01:19:13.607
This is all Phil Neilson.
our amazing second unit director.

1402
01:19:13.677 --> 01:19:17.738
and all this stunt-y stuff. all the great stuff
is done by someone other than me.

1403
01:19:19.583 --> 01:19:20.675
But...

1404
01:19:20.751 --> 01:19:22.446
LAMBERT: We should talk about
the vampire speed effect.

1405
01:19:22.520 --> 01:19:25.489
'cause that was a kind of
a last-minute addition. really. wasn't it?

1406
01:19:25.556 --> 01:19:27.080
WEITZ: Yeah.

1407
01:19:27.158 --> 01:19:32.528
LAMBERT: We always planned that we would
never make the vampires run any faster than.

1408
01:19:32.596 --> 01:19:34.962
effectively. as if they'd been shot
at 24 frames per second.

1409
01:19:35.032 --> 01:19:36.056
-WEITZ: Right.
-So in other words.

1410
01:19:36.133 --> 01:19:38.966
faster than a human being would run.
we would only go slower

1411
01:19:39.036 --> 01:19:40.264
-and go into slow motion.
-WEITZ: Right.

1412
01:19:40.337 --> 01:19:43.329
LAMBERT: But we suddenly realized
that we could. well. we couldn't.

1413
01:19:43.407 --> 01:19:45.773
but the visual effects guys
could do these cool little effects

1414
01:19:45.843 --> 01:19:47.572
-to sort of shoot them forward.
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1415
01:19:47.645 --> 01:19:50.136
LAMBERT: And suddenly they did it once.
and we were like. "That's cool. "

1416
01:19:50.214 --> 01:19:54.275
and then Susan MacLeod.
the visual effects supervisor. kept pushing.

1417
01:19:54.351 --> 01:19:56.182
And then suddenly it was everywhere.

1418
01:19:56.253 --> 01:19:58.244
WEITZ: Her jumping off the cliff.

1419
01:19:58.322 --> 01:20:02.952
Yeah. at first.
the technique was to slow them down

1420
01:20:03.027 --> 01:20:04.324
in order show them going faster.

1421
01:20:04.395 --> 01:20:06.829
We would only shoot them in slow mo.
as it were.

1422
01:20:06.897 --> 01:20:11.425
And then we saw
some kind of time-space distortion effects

1423
01:20:11.902 --> 01:20:14.427
that conveyed the idea
of someone going so quickly

1424
01:20:14.505 --> 01:20:17.065
that the space around them
was kind of warped.

1425
01:20:17.842 --> 01:20:20.106
which worked rather nicely.

1426
01:20:21.145 --> 01:20:23.272
And here's just the really perverse moment

1427
01:20:23.347 --> 01:20:27.647
where Bella is doing something
extraordinarily dangerous and near suicidal.

1428
01:20:27.718 --> 01:20:30.881
just to get another taste
of Edward's presence.

1429
01:20:32.056 --> 01:20:33.080
LAMBERT: It's kind of interesting

1430
01:20:33.157 --> 01:20:37.025
the music choice that ended up
for the score here. as well.

1431
01:20:37.094 --> 01:20:40.154
'Cause I always thought this would be
kind of a big adrenaline-y thing

1432
01:20:40.231 --> 01:20:41.357
of her at the top of the cliff.

1433
01:20:41.432 --> 01:20:44.401
And then Alexandre wrote
this really lush. romantic music.

1434
01:20:44.468 --> 01:20:47.926
the kind of music of longing. which comes
up every now and again in the movie.

1435
01:20:48.005 --> 01:20:51.873
and. again. it changes. it transforms it into
something kind of romantic and beautiful.

1436
01:20:51.942 --> 01:20:56.140
WEITZ: Right.
Yeah. very weird stuff happening here.

1437
01:21:00.718 --> 01:21:04.210
Okay. so. now we're in a swimming pool
in Vancouver.

1438
01:21:05.322 --> 01:21:07.620
And anything that you see
which doesn't look like a swimming pool

1439
01:21:07.691 --> 01:21:09.955
in Vancouver is added with CGI.

1440
01:21:10.027 --> 01:21:14.726
So. the color of the water.
those waves in the background. CGI.

1441
01:21:14.798 --> 01:21:18.825
That cliff there. CGI.
This wave. CGI.

1442
01:21:18.903 --> 01:21:22.600
This is real. because poor Kristen.
with a cold.

1443
01:21:22.673 --> 01:21:27.042
was slammed
with hundreds of gallons of water.

1444
01:21:27.511 --> 01:21:32.175
producing these beautiful
kind of bubble effects that are going on.

1445
01:21:32.249 --> 01:21:35.047
But this. however
is Rachelle Lefevre swimming

1446
01:21:35.119 --> 01:21:38.748
in a swimming pool in Vancouver.

1447
01:21:38.956 --> 01:21:45.293
But with all the water around her turned
into what looks like murky. cliff side water.

1448
01:21:46.163 --> 01:21:50.759
And now we go into sort of a dream state
where she's close to death.

1449
01:21:50.834 --> 01:21:52.563
She's close to drowning and...

1450
01:21:52.636 --> 01:21:55.537
LAMBERT: This again was Kristen and Rob
with weights in their pockets. wasn't it?

1451
01:21:55.606 --> 01:21:57.130
-WEITZ: Yes.
-Just dragging them down.

1452
01:21:57.207 --> 01:22:01.371
WEITZ: Although. Rob actually did sit
at the bottom of the pool.

1453
01:22:01.445 --> 01:22:02.707
-LAMBERT: That's right.
-We filmed them separately.

1454
01:22:02.780 --> 01:22:05.305
-LAMBERT: Someone had to hold him down.
-Rob was at the bottom of the pool

1455
01:22:05.382 --> 01:22:06.542
with weights in his pockets.

1456
01:22:06.617 --> 01:22:09.177
And then Kristen was feeling
a bit worried about that.

1457
01:22:09.253 --> 01:22:11.118
so I said. "Oh. that's no big deal. come on. "

1458
01:22:11.188 --> 01:22:15.124
and I got into the pool
with some weights on me.

1459
01:22:15.192 --> 01:22:17.956
went to the bottom of the pool
and started panicking immediately.

1460
01:22:18.028 --> 01:22:21.259
And so I thought.
"Okay. I'm not gonna make Kristen do this. "

1461
01:22:21.332 --> 01:22:24.927
So we actually filmed her
laterally. sideways.

1462
01:22:25.002 --> 01:22:29.029
but of course. you know. when you can't
tell the background. you don't know.

1463
01:22:29.106 --> 01:22:33.566
So she looks like she's floating downwards.
Edward's floating upwards.

1464
01:22:33.644 --> 01:22:37.444
and since he was shot separately.
we could dissolve him in that manner.

1465
01:22:37.514 --> 01:22:39.880
And that beautiful Grizzly Bear track

1466
01:22:39.950 --> 01:22:44.819
keeps on going at a very. very. very.
very subtle level until she wakes up.

1467
01:22:44.888 --> 01:22:46.913
so even when she's on the beach there.

1468
01:22:46.991 --> 01:22:49.016
And this again was
what we shot that first day.

1469
01:22:49.093 --> 01:22:53.257
when I was saying that
we had all this kind of crazy. crazy weather.

1470
01:22:54.198 --> 01:22:56.826
and was the beginning of the torture
that I was inflicting on our actors.

1471
01:22:56.900 --> 01:23:00.768
Because. there's poor Taylor.
on Vancouver Island.

1472
01:23:00.838 --> 01:23:04.399
it is cold. it is cold. cold. cold.
and they're wet down.

1473
01:23:06.977 --> 01:23:09.571
And now here's the hardest line
to say in the movie.

1474
01:23:09.646 --> 01:23:14.709
"Harry Clearwater had a heart attack. "
4 H's in very quick succession.

1475
01:23:14.818 --> 01:23:16.479
LAMBERT: It was good that the Clearwater
was put in there.

1476
01:23:16.553 --> 01:23:18.487
'cause I think originally it was.
"Harry had a heart attack. "

1477
01:23:18.555 --> 01:23:19.579
WEITZ: Harry had a heart attack.

1478
01:23:19.656 --> 01:23:20.782
LAMBERT: It sounded like
a kind of ABC primer.

1479
01:23:20.858 --> 01:23:24.726
WEITZ: Actually. it sounds like sort of a band
that plays at your prom or something.

1480
01:23:25.863 --> 01:23:29.390
Come on. I'll get you something dry
and drive you home.

1481
01:23:29.600 --> 01:23:32.569
WEITZ: Anyway. A beautiful beach.

1482
01:23:33.103 --> 01:23:36.436
LAMBERT: A little outtake there.
that wide shot of him. lifting her up.

1483
01:23:36.807 --> 01:23:39.833
WEITZ: Outtake. It wasn't.
It was after we had said cut. wasn't it?

1484
01:23:39.910 --> 01:23:41.434
LAMBERT: Yeah. it was indeed. yeah.

1485
01:23:41.512 --> 01:23:43.946
WEITZ: Okay. again. we're shooting in a barn
on a green screen.

1486
01:23:44.014 --> 01:23:48.178
but. you know.
CG is able to put in this lovely road.

1487
01:23:48.252 --> 01:23:53.588
and the beautiful kind of sense of shadow
of these trees above them

1488
01:23:53.657 --> 01:23:57.821
and passing over them and the opacity
of them and the translucence of them.

1489
01:23:58.829 --> 01:24:00.660
It's a Jacob thing.

1490
01:24:01.198 --> 01:24:03.029
You're just warm.

1491
01:24:05.402 --> 01:24:07.370
You're like your own sun.

1492
01:24:07.638 --> 01:24:10.300
LAMBERT: I always think it sounds like
she says. "You like your own son. "

1493
01:24:10.374 --> 01:24:11.500
WEITZ: Oh. right.

1494
01:24:11.575 --> 01:24:14.043
LAMBERT: Which is ironic 'cause
he's gonna end up liking her daughter.

1495
01:24:14.111 --> 01:24:18.912
WEITZ: Well. I thought it was even more
confusing. "You are like your own son. "

1496
01:24:18.982 --> 01:24:21.314
which would be deeply. deeply confusing.

1497
01:24:21.385 --> 01:24:23.376
LAMBERT: Okay. yeah. Is that compliment?

1498
01:24:24.488 --> 01:24:26.854
You saw what happened to Emily.

1499
01:24:28.025 --> 01:24:29.652
-WEITZ: Now we deal with...
-Now. we're not in a barn.

1500
01:24:29.726 --> 01:24:32.024
-Now we're in real.
-WEITZ: No. this is real.

1501
01:24:32.729 --> 01:24:35.630
This is real. and we are shooting.

1502
01:24:36.266 --> 01:24:39.793
you know. 1 single long take
of the 2 of them together.

1503
01:24:39.870 --> 01:24:44.170
as Jacob kind of explains his fears

1504
01:24:45.342 --> 01:24:47.276
of hurting her really.

1505
01:24:49.947 --> 01:24:52.245
And there were several takes
to choose from here.

1506
01:24:52.316 --> 01:24:57.652
and it was really about choosing
the near kiss that was

1507
01:24:57.721 --> 01:25:00.246
I suppose the most tortuous. really.

1508
01:25:00.324 --> 01:25:05.227
and one in which it didn't seem like
she was suddenly saying talk to the hand.

1509
01:25:06.196 --> 01:25:09.029
But where you could tell
in her thought processes

1510
01:25:09.099 --> 01:25:12.125
that this was a possibility for her.

1511
01:25:12.870 --> 01:25:17.000
And. in the book. I believe
Edward pops up over Jacob's shoulder

1512
01:25:17.074 --> 01:25:18.302
and says. "Be happy. "

1513
01:25:18.375 --> 01:25:20.138
-LAMBERT: "Be happy. "
-"Be happy. "

1514
01:25:20.210 --> 01:25:21.973
Thereby totally spoiling the moment

1515
01:25:22.045 --> 01:25:25.503
in a kind of passive aggressive apparition
sort of way.

1516
01:25:27.951 --> 01:25:31.614
But here it's just sort of Bella
recalling herself

1517
01:25:32.489 --> 01:25:38.428
from this moment of intense gratitude

1518
01:25:38.495 --> 01:25:42.124
of emotionalism
and of deep. deep friendship.

1519
01:25:42.966 --> 01:25:46.231
which almost pulls her into Jacob's orbit.

1520
01:25:48.438 --> 01:25:51.669
Now Jake's making the right move here
for once in his life.

1521
01:25:52.309 --> 01:25:53.867
Still doesn't work. though.

1522
01:25:54.578 --> 01:25:57.069
Close. no. No cigar.

1523
01:25:57.147 --> 01:26:03.279
That little micro movement there by Bella.
that says. no. no. thanks.

1524
01:26:03.353 --> 01:26:06.322
LAMBERT: ll think we put a little sound.
a kind of...sound.

1525
01:26:06.390 --> 01:26:07.414
I don't know if that can be picked up

1526
01:26:07.491 --> 01:26:08.549
-on the microphone.
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1527
01:26:08.625 --> 01:26:11.185
LAMBERT: Which actually. amazingly.
is Taylor making that noise.

1528
01:26:11.261 --> 01:26:14.094
but we shifted it so it sounded
like it was Bella as a kind of...

1529
01:26:14.164 --> 01:26:16.530
-WEITZ: Oh. how creepy.
-A little rejection sound.

1530
01:26:16.600 --> 01:26:18.397
WEITZ: This look here.
before he says there's a vampire.

1531
01:26:18.468 --> 01:26:21.494
almost looks like Bella is saying.
"Wow. he's actually gonna go for it. "

1532
01:26:21.572 --> 01:26:23.335
LAMBERT: Yeah. yeah. it's cool.

1533
01:26:23.407 --> 01:26:25.739
WEITZ: It's kind of a cool. confusing moment.

1534
01:26:26.443 --> 01:26:30.402
There's Carlisle's car.

1535
01:26:31.248 --> 01:26:35.582
Now here. this is kind of an interesting
moment. where he actually hurts her.

1536
01:26:35.652 --> 01:26:37.347
He grabs her so hard that he hurts her.

1537
01:26:37.421 --> 01:26:40.584
and it's kind of this little reminder
of the moment earlier

1538
01:26:40.657 --> 01:26:45.390
where he said that he's a bit afraid
of the danger that he might pose to her.

1539
01:26:47.097 --> 01:26:50.794
LAMBERT: Amazingly. coincidentally.
he grabs her in roughly the place

1540
01:26:50.867 --> 01:26:53.461
where I believe a bruise ends up
on Kristen's arm.

1541
01:26:53.537 --> 01:26:55.596
which you can see later in the movie.
in Italy.

1542
01:26:55.672 --> 01:26:58.232
which actually came
from her running into the fountain.

1543
01:26:58.308 --> 01:26:59.605
WEITZ: Yes. we'll talk about that later.

1544
01:26:59.676 --> 01:27:02.338
-That's a good one.
-LAMBERT: That will be a fun one.

1545
01:27:10.754 --> 01:27:13.518
WEITZ: You can actually hear Alice
give a little "huh" of surprise

1546
01:27:13.590 --> 01:27:17.458
when Bella is surprised.
which I find kind of charming.

1547
01:27:17.527 --> 01:27:21.293
which we had to position very carefully
when it came to doing the sound.

1548
01:27:23.667 --> 01:27:25.862
Now. there are moments where
they're just about to talk about Edward

1549
01:27:25.936 --> 01:27:27.767
but they don't. here.

1550
01:27:29.072 --> 01:27:31.233
which is probably
very frustrating to the audience.

1551
01:27:31.308 --> 01:27:35.472
but don't want to get them
to quite talking about him yet.

1552
01:27:37.414 --> 01:27:38.881
I was cliff jumping.

1553
01:27:38.949 --> 01:27:40.712
Recreationally.

1554
01:27:40.784 --> 01:27:42.183
It was fun.

1555
01:27:43.287 --> 01:27:44.345
(EXHALES)

1556
01:27:44.688 --> 01:27:48.419
I have never met anyone
more prone to life-threatening idiocy.

1557
01:27:53.930 --> 01:27:55.022
Does...

1558
01:27:55.599 --> 01:27:57.658
Did you tell him?

1559
01:27:57.734 --> 01:27:58.792
No.

1560
01:28:00.470 --> 01:28:03.200
He only calls in once every few months.

1561
01:28:04.808 --> 01:28:07.072
He said he wants to be alone.

1562
01:28:12.916 --> 01:28:16.283
Bella. what is that
God-awful wet dog smell?

1563
01:28:17.721 --> 01:28:18.710
Um...

1564
01:28:19.556 --> 01:28:21.319
That's probably me.

1565
01:28:22.893 --> 01:28:25.589
WEITZ: There's a lovely look
that we kind of cheated in there.

1566
01:28:25.662 --> 01:28:30.361
where Bella looks just so terribly defeated
at the mention of Edward.

1567
01:28:30.434 --> 01:28:32.959
And it's like when. you know.

1568
01:28:33.036 --> 01:28:36.062
someone has broken your heart
and their name comes up.

1569
01:28:36.139 --> 01:28:38.403
and there's just nothing to do about it.

1570
01:28:38.475 --> 01:28:41.933
And here. to me. is a really nice moment
where this theme comes in.

1571
01:28:43.113 --> 01:28:45.081
and so she's just been slammed again

1572
01:28:45.148 --> 01:28:49.847
with the fact of Edward's seeming
non-interest in her. and here comes Jacob.

1573
01:28:49.920 --> 01:28:55.381
who. against the treaty. against all odds.
is still coming back for her.

1574
01:28:55.459 --> 01:29:00.453
which to me. justifies the moment
that we're about to have in the kitchen.

1575
01:29:01.531 --> 01:29:04.967
I'm talking about the other bloodsucker
who tried to kill Bella because of you.

1576
01:29:05.035 --> 01:29:06.093
Victoria?

1577
01:29:06.169 --> 01:29:08.296
Yeah. Victoria's been around.

1578
01:29:08.372 --> 01:29:10.135
I didn't see her.

1579
01:29:10.941 --> 01:29:13.842
LAMBERT: This always. for me.
kind of puts paid to Edward's theory

1580
01:29:13.910 --> 01:29:15.673
that he was going away to protect her.

1581
01:29:15.746 --> 01:29:19.739
It's like. he really should have picked up
on the fact that Victoria was in town.

1582
01:29:19.816 --> 01:29:22.410
rather than going to South America
to hunt her.

1583
01:29:22.486 --> 01:29:26.650
WEITZ: Yeah.
Well. not a great decision by Edward.

1584
01:29:26.723 --> 01:29:28.384
-LAMBERT: Bad decision.
-Not one of the great decisions

1585
01:29:28.458 --> 01:29:30.085
of all time. let's be honest.

1586
01:29:30.160 --> 01:29:32.219
But without that.
we wouldn't have a movie. really.

1587
01:29:32.295 --> 01:29:33.762
LAMBERT: Good point.
yeah. okay. yeah. fair enough.

1588
01:29:33.830 --> 01:29:35.889
WEITZ: So. thank you. Edward.

1589
01:29:35.966 --> 01:29:37.763
And I think in a weird way...

1590
01:29:38.602 --> 01:29:40.593
That's part of the reason
that Romeo and Juliet

1591
01:29:40.670 --> 01:29:44.868
sort of plays a big function in this movie.
because in Romeo and Juliet.

1592
01:29:44.941 --> 01:29:47.842
there are just a bunch of horrible mistakes
that people make.

1593
01:29:47.911 --> 01:29:49.003
-LAMBERT: Yeah. yeah.
-And misunderstandings.

1594
01:29:49.079 --> 01:29:51.513
which could be rectified
in about 10 seconds

1595
01:29:51.581 --> 01:29:53.879
or by just waiting for just a minute.

1596
01:29:55.085 --> 01:29:57.280
And yet things go awfully. terribly wrong.

1597
01:29:57.354 --> 01:29:58.378
LAMBERT: Yeah.

1598
01:29:58.455 --> 01:30:00.946
WEITZ: And that Edward is
very kind of snooty about Romeo

1599
01:30:01.024 --> 01:30:02.082
at the beginning of the movie.

1600
01:30:02.159 --> 01:30:06.528
just saying how stupid he was.
and yet he does exactly the same thing.

1601
01:30:06.930 --> 01:30:08.056
LAMBERT: Yeah.

1602
01:30:12.235 --> 01:30:15.033
And she can stay as long as she'd like.

1603
01:30:16.840 --> 01:30:19.741
WEITZ: Bella's kind of annoyed at Jake now.

1604
01:30:19.810 --> 01:30:23.746
'cause it seems like all Jacob cares about
is the Cullens.

1605
01:30:24.881 --> 01:30:26.109
She hasn't quite twigged to the fact

1606
01:30:26.183 --> 01:30:29.550
that he's just threatened
by the possibility of Edward coming.

1607
01:30:31.655 --> 01:30:33.213
Anything else?

1608
01:30:35.759 --> 01:30:39.718
WEITZ: All right. Jacob's both about to make
his best move in the movie and his worst.

1609
01:30:40.363 --> 01:30:41.489
LAMBERT: Yeah.

1610
01:30:41.565 --> 01:30:43.556
Well. if that's all.
then you'd better go run back to Sam.

1611
01:30:43.633 --> 01:30:47.467
LAMBERT: This is exactly
the same little sting. musically here.

1612
01:30:47.537 --> 01:30:52.406
that we heard when Jacob comes in.
It's like he's picking it back up again.

1613
01:30:52.476 --> 01:30:55.104
-and then it develops.
-WEITZ: Now.

1614
01:30:56.079 --> 01:31:00.140
I think that her annoyance here.
you can interpret it any way you like.

1615
01:31:00.217 --> 01:31:04.984
but part of it is her annoyance at Jake

1616
01:31:05.055 --> 01:31:09.856
for not giving himself enough credit
in her life. in a weird way.

1617
01:31:12.262 --> 01:31:15.322
and being more of a werewolf than a suitor.

1618
01:31:15.765 --> 01:31:17.426
Okay. now. he's about to say something...

1619
01:31:17.501 --> 01:31:19.264
LAMBERT: Yeah. are you gonna tell people
what he's saying?

1620
01:31:19.336 --> 01:31:20.394
-WEITZ: No.
-Okay. good.

1621
01:31:20.470 --> 01:31:23.132
WEITZ: But I will tell you
that it is genuine Quileute.

1622
01:31:23.206 --> 01:31:26.607
a language spoken fluently
by only a few people in the world.

1623
01:31:26.676 --> 01:31:29.668
LAMBERT: And we hope that they've told us
the correct translation

1624
01:31:29.746 --> 01:31:31.441
of what we wanted them to say.

1625
01:31:31.515 --> 01:31:33.449
'Cause otherwise he might be saying
something terrible.

1626
01:31:33.517 --> 01:31:37.476
WEITZ: So somewhere in the background.
I am controlling the telephone.

1627
01:31:37.554 --> 01:31:42.184
Don't answer the phone. Jacob.
You idiot. Okay.

1628
01:31:42.259 --> 01:31:45.660
-LAMBERT: So. that ring. actually. you timed.
-Yeah.

1629
01:31:45.729 --> 01:31:47.959
LAMBERT: So you could decide
how long to let them

1630
01:31:48.031 --> 01:31:49.020
nearly kiss.

1631
01:31:49.099 --> 01:31:50.361
WEITZ: Well. that ring
was on a 2 second delay.

1632
01:31:50.433 --> 01:31:51.900
so I had to decide. actually...

1633
01:31:51.968 --> 01:31:53.765
LAMBERT: 2 seconds beforehand.

1634
01:31:53.837 --> 01:31:56.032
-how close their lips would be.
-LAMBERT: Wow.

1635
01:31:56.106 --> 01:31:59.803
WEITZ: And they just. just. just. just touch
or appear to touch.

1636
01:31:59.876 --> 01:32:01.434
LAMBERT: People think directing is easy.

1637
01:32:01.511 --> 01:32:03.570
-but when you hear stories like that...
-WEITZ: No. it's not easy.

1638
01:32:03.647 --> 01:32:06.047
It's not easy. It's very stressful.

1639
01:32:09.586 --> 01:32:13.545
Edward. a mistake by him. too.
destroying his cell phone.

1640
01:32:13.623 --> 01:32:14.681
LAMBERT: Yeah. they could have just done

1641
01:32:14.758 --> 01:32:16.692
-the reverse call thing.
-WEITZ: Instead of calling back.

1642
01:32:16.793 --> 01:32:18.090
-Yeah.
-LAMBERT: Otherwise. couldn't they?

1643
01:32:18.161 --> 01:32:21.597
She could have just done whatever
the American equivalent of 1471 is. yeah.

1644
01:32:21.665 --> 01:32:23.895
-It's star 69. and she doesn't do that.
-LAMBERT: Not that.

1645
01:32:23.967 --> 01:32:26.197
-Yeah.
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1646
01:32:26.636 --> 01:32:29.196
LAMBERT: She probably did do it.
but in the sort of time transition

1647
01:32:29.272 --> 01:32:31.297
-that we cut around...
-WEITZ: Yeah. we don't see that.

1648
01:32:31.374 --> 01:32:32.398
LAMBERT: But he'd smashed
the phone by then.

1649
01:32:32.475 --> 01:32:34.033
-She would have got voicemail.
-WEITZ: Yeah. yeah.

1650
01:32:34.110 --> 01:32:37.739
"Hi. this is Edward Cullen.
I'm away from the phone at the moment

1651
01:32:37.814 --> 01:32:40.009
"or I've crushed it in despair. "

1652
01:32:40.083 --> 01:32:41.516
(LAMBERT LAUGHING)

1653
01:32:41.585 --> 01:32:43.780
Okay. here comes another whip pan.

1654
01:32:43.853 --> 01:32:44.945
(WEITZ CHUCKLES)

1655
01:32:45.488 --> 01:32:47.456
The old whip pan. my fave.

1656
01:32:48.391 --> 01:32:51.087
Notice that Bella has a passport.

1657
01:32:51.161 --> 01:32:52.890
We just wanna make sure
that you know that.

1658
01:32:52.963 --> 01:32:54.988
-LAMBERT: Wow. I never even noticed that.
-Yeah.

1659
01:32:55.065 --> 01:32:57.260
LAMBERT: Where's she got her passport?

1660
01:32:57.334 --> 01:32:58.494
-WEITZ: In her hand.
-Oh. okay.

1661
01:32:58.568 --> 01:32:59.899
WEITZ: You mean. where'd she get it?
I don't know.

1662
01:32:59.970 --> 01:33:01.335
LAMBERT: No. no. Where is it?
I can't see the shot.

1663
01:33:01.404 --> 01:33:02.564
WEITZ: In Seattle.

1664
01:33:03.106 --> 01:33:05.768
LAMBERT: I don't know
why I didn't notice it before.

1665
01:33:09.512 --> 01:33:11.946
WEITZ: (EXCLAIMS)
Jacob takes a pounding again.

1666
01:33:12.015 --> 01:33:16.884
How much emotional letdown
can this kid take?

1667
01:33:19.522 --> 01:33:21.956
And I just realized. watching this
at the premiere. when he says.

1668
01:33:22.025 --> 01:33:26.359
"I'm begging you. " he's in the position
of a dog and he's begging like a dog.

1669
01:33:26.429 --> 01:33:27.589
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1670
01:33:27.664 --> 01:33:29.825
Which I suppose is either funny or sad.

1671
01:33:29.899 --> 01:33:30.923
LAMBERT: Yeah.

1672
01:33:37.140 --> 01:33:40.541
-WEITZ: And I rather like the look that...
-Alice gives.

1673
01:33:40.610 --> 01:33:43.875
WEITZ: That Alice gives
when Jacob first reaches in.

1674
01:33:43.947 --> 01:33:47.439
which is like "Girlfriend. what is he doing?"

1675
01:33:48.251 --> 01:33:51.243
Anyway. transition shot to this plane.

1676
01:33:51.321 --> 01:33:54.347
Let's just get them to Italy quickly.
shall we?

1677
01:33:54.424 --> 01:33:56.688
It was kind of the idea.
'cause we didn't really want to see them

1678
01:33:56.760 --> 01:34:00.628
in the waiting lounge
at Seattle Sea-Tac airport

1679
01:34:00.697 --> 01:34:02.858
and doing duty free shopping
and all that kind of stuff.

1680
01:34:02.932 --> 01:34:06.834
LAMBERT: Alice playing Tetris on her phone
while they wait.

1681
01:34:07.370 --> 01:34:09.429
WEITZ: Yeah. let's just get them there.

1682
01:34:09.839 --> 01:34:11.272
And the beloved yellow Porsche.

1683
01:34:20.483 --> 01:34:25.318
And here we are with the Volturi.

1684
01:34:27.390 --> 01:34:31.918
LAMBERT: We only added this scene back
into the movie at the last minute.

1685
01:34:31.995 --> 01:34:34.657
Amazingly. we were stupid enough
to cut it out

1686
01:34:34.731 --> 01:34:36.926
-for a long time. weren't we?
-WEITZ: Yeah. we did think for a while

1687
01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:38.900
that we shouldn't see Edward
until Bella sees him

1688
01:34:38.968 --> 01:34:41.061
and that we didn't want any
back-at-the-ranch scenes.

1689
01:34:41.137 --> 01:34:45.699
But this was a good way
to break up the rush. the headlong rush.

1690
01:34:46.443 --> 01:34:49.879
And so now.
when Bella first encounters Aro.

1691
01:34:49.946 --> 01:34:53.905
we know a bit more about him.
He isn't just some weirdo who pops up.

1692
01:34:54.417 --> 01:34:58.410
LAMBERT: I like the way you introduce the
Volturi so gradually throughout the movie.

1693
01:34:58.488 --> 01:35:02.288
And not just them as their characters.
but also the set.

1694
01:35:02.358 --> 01:35:07.193
The way. both in the first flashback
in the painting and in this scene.

1695
01:35:07.263 --> 01:35:10.130
you don't really get
a sense of the scale of the set.

1696
01:35:12.202 --> 01:35:13.760
Such a waste.

1697
01:35:15.605 --> 01:35:16.799
WEITZ: But in the movie. we very...

1698
01:35:16.873 --> 01:35:18.170
LAMBERT: But I don't think
anyone was doing it.

1699
01:35:18.241 --> 01:35:20.539
-to be honest.
-WEITZ: We very carefully...

1700
01:35:20.610 --> 01:35:22.373
No. people don't use the Internet.

1701
01:35:22.445 --> 01:35:28.384
We very carefully rationed out
what bits of that set that we would see

1702
01:35:28.451 --> 01:35:32.114
and in what degree of elimination.
so that when you finally saw it.

1703
01:35:32.188 --> 01:35:34.486
it was like. "Wow. this is really something. "

1704
01:35:34.591 --> 01:35:36.286
He's gonna make a scene.

1705
01:35:36.459 --> 01:35:38.154
Show himself to the humans.

1706
01:35:38.228 --> 01:35:40.219
LAMBERT: This was a great moment
of genius on your part.

1707
01:35:40.296 --> 01:35:42.230
throwing in this little vision.

1708
01:35:42.298 --> 01:35:43.356
WEITZ: Oh. was it? Thank you.

1709
01:35:43.433 --> 01:35:45.196
LAMBERT: Yeah. it was you.
You thought of it.

1710
01:35:45.268 --> 01:35:47.429
WEITZ: Yeah. we cheated a little vision there.

1711
01:35:47.504 --> 01:35:48.766
Well. now...

1712
01:35:50.607 --> 01:35:56.671
Ashley used her hands
on the steering wheel quite well.

1713
01:35:58.047 --> 01:36:00.572
and then someone told me
that it looked like she wasn't driving.

1714
01:36:00.650 --> 01:36:03.881
And then I told her to move it more.
which then became a bit

1715
01:36:03.953 --> 01:36:06.649
looking as though
she was Toonces. the driving cat.

1716
01:36:07.991 --> 01:36:12.257
making it very hard
to composite in the background.

1717
01:36:12.328 --> 01:36:16.128
LAMBERT: You'll notice that that sequence
is cut very fast. mostly in singles.

1718
01:36:16.199 --> 01:36:19.691
because we're trying to avoid it being
on her and the road long enough.

1719
01:36:19.769 --> 01:36:22.294
to see that the road does not match
her movements.

1720
01:36:22.372 --> 01:36:26.274
WEITZ: Now. there's the famous bruise
which we say

1721
01:36:26.943 --> 01:36:29.434
was made by Jacob grabbing her.

1722
01:36:29.512 --> 01:36:33.141
-LAMBERT: Is it on the same arm?
-These are real Italian cops

1723
01:36:35.351 --> 01:36:38.047
acting. actually. relatively unconcerned

1724
01:36:38.121 --> 01:36:39.110
given the speed at which...

1725
01:36:39.189 --> 01:36:40.554
LAMBERT: Did they know
that they were being filmed?

1726
01:36:40.623 --> 01:36:42.648
-WEITZ: They did. They did. yes.
-They were just doing their job.

1727
01:36:42.725 --> 01:36:44.522
WEITZ: Just doing their job.

1728
01:36:45.528 --> 01:36:48.463
Okay. notice now that we actually.
throughout this movie.

1729
01:36:48.531 --> 01:36:51.898
saved the color red for use here.

1730
01:36:51.968 --> 01:36:56.337
so that now you've suddenly got this sense
of blood and danger.

1731
01:36:56.406 --> 01:36:59.239
We really rarely. rarely. rarely used red.

1732
01:36:59.309 --> 01:37:02.904
There was kind of a prohibition against red
throughout the film. until this point.

1733
01:37:02.979 --> 01:37:05.277
And here we are in Italy. of course.
by the way.

1734
01:37:05.348 --> 01:37:09.682
Having finished in Vancouver.
we flew to Italy

1735
01:37:09.752 --> 01:37:12.983
for a week's work. 4 days of shooting.
2 days of prep.

1736
01:37:15.058 --> 01:37:17.253
And voilà.

1737
01:37:18.461 --> 01:37:19.860
(WEITZ SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

1738
01:37:20.797 --> 01:37:25.393
And about a thousand extras.
and this thing which is called a palanchino.

1739
01:37:25.468 --> 01:37:30.770
that saint's processional. palanquin thing.

1740
01:37:30.840 --> 01:37:36.801
And you'll see that that's a vampire
being chained by a golden saint.

1741
01:37:36.880 --> 01:37:40.111
which accords with what's talked about
in the book.

1742
01:37:40.550 --> 01:37:46.352
and here we're going in and out of various
speeds to get Bella to that moment.

1743
01:37:46.422 --> 01:37:48.788
That's where she scratched her arm.

1744
01:37:49.792 --> 01:37:52.283
and voilà. noon.

1745
01:37:54.597 --> 01:37:58.158
Now. very difficult to shoot. over
the course of several days.

1746
01:37:58.234 --> 01:38:00.395
a shot which is supposed to take place
at exactly noon.

1747
01:38:00.470 --> 01:38:04.600
You have to be careful to plan
your camera angles.

1748
01:38:04.674 --> 01:38:07.006
so that it falls just at the right time.

1749
01:38:08.511 --> 01:38:11.207
And poor Peter wasn't here
for the Italian part of the shoot.

1750
01:38:11.281 --> 01:38:12.839
LAMBERT: I was in LA having a great time.

1751
01:38:12.916 --> 01:38:17.114
WEITZ: Yeah. well. I was eating pasta
at the Relais San Bruno. buddy.

1752
01:38:17.186 --> 01:38:18.483
with homemade mozzarella.

1753
01:38:18.554 --> 01:38:19.885
-LAMBERT: That sounds good. though.
-Yeah.

1754
01:38:19.956 --> 01:38:22.322
LAMBERT: I can go to Italy whenever I want.

1755
01:38:22.725 --> 01:38:25.387
-I'm English. It's just around the corner.
-WEITZ: That's true.

1756
01:38:25.461 --> 01:38:28.225
-LAMBERT: LA was more exciting to me.
-It's a 2 hour drive.

1757
01:38:29.365 --> 01:38:32.266
Now these are the beautiful
diamond effects.

1758
01:38:32.735 --> 01:38:37.104
and now why is this little kid
suddenly interested.

1759
01:38:37.173 --> 01:38:40.472
I wanted to give some sense of threat
that somebody had noticed

1760
01:38:40.543 --> 01:38:43.637
but that they wouldn't ever be believed.
so that we were constantly kind of

1761
01:38:43.713 --> 01:38:47.046
riding the line between
the possibility of being noticed or not.

1762
01:38:47.116 --> 01:38:50.574
I thought it would be odd if you see him
and then nobody's looking at him.

1763
01:38:50.653 --> 01:38:55.613
But then we had this sweet little girl
who just couldn't stop smiling

1764
01:38:55.692 --> 01:38:57.387
'cause she was so happy to be in the movie.

1765
01:38:57.460 --> 01:39:00.588
We tried to make her look surprised
or amazed.

1766
01:39:00.663 --> 01:39:04.463
but all she could just do is smile.
Sweet little Italian girl.

1767
01:39:05.601 --> 01:39:06.625
I rather love this scene.

1768
01:39:06.703 --> 01:39:07.829
LAMBERT: Unfortunately.
she will now. of course.

1769
01:39:07.904 --> 01:39:11.203
have to be assassinated by the Volturi.
having seen this.

1770
01:39:16.212 --> 01:39:20.080
WEITZ: Now. the colors here. you know.

1771
01:39:20.149 --> 01:39:22.913
certainly if you compare this
to the first movie.

1772
01:39:22.986 --> 01:39:25.454
golds. gold. gold and red.

1773
01:39:28.891 --> 01:39:34.921
And. well. I don't know. I mean.
it's just a lovely little intimate scene.

1774
01:39:35.098 --> 01:39:39.535
And this is actually played out
in the city hall of Montepulciano.

1775
01:39:39.602 --> 01:39:43.265
-while business was being conducted.
-LAMBERT: Really?

1776
01:39:43.339 --> 01:39:46.502
WEITZ: Yeah. in between shots.
there are guys rushing around

1777
01:39:46.576 --> 01:39:48.237
with papers to Xerox and things.

1778
01:39:48.311 --> 01:39:51.109
And they're doing
this incredibly emotional scene.

1779
01:39:51.180 --> 01:39:53.648
And also. between every shot.
Kristen would run...

1780
01:39:53.716 --> 01:39:55.684
-LAMBERT: Kristen would run around.
-... up and down the corridor

1781
01:39:55.752 --> 01:40:00.121
in order to get as out of breath
as she would have been having just arrived.

1782
01:40:03.860 --> 01:40:05.623
We did some work on this dialogue.

1783
01:40:05.695 --> 01:40:09.222
I do love that she just says
she's human. she's nothing.

1784
01:40:10.233 --> 01:40:14.761
which I think we all sort of feel.
at certain points. in relationships.

1785
01:40:15.638 --> 01:40:18.539
when we've been missing someone
or lacking someone.

1786
01:40:18.608 --> 01:40:20.337
"I'm nothing. I'm human. "

1787
01:40:22.311 --> 01:40:25.212
And. of course.
that's what's most important to him.

1788
01:40:26.482 --> 01:40:28.109
LAMBERT: Epic. epic kissing here.

1789
01:40:28.184 --> 01:40:30.152
-WEITZ: Yeah. Yeah.
-Epic snog.

1790
01:40:30.219 --> 01:40:35.680
WEITZ: Epic snogage with dissolve.
snog dissolve.

1791
01:40:36.159 --> 01:40:40.493
and also Alexandre hitting his strings
at the highest.

1792
01:40:41.731 --> 01:40:44.325
Now. those guys were actually
wearing hoods.

1793
01:40:44.400 --> 01:40:46.163
which was supposed to keep them out
of the sunlight.

1794
01:40:46.235 --> 01:40:49.329
but actually just looks like they scratched
their heads in concert as they come in.

1795
01:40:49.405 --> 01:40:53.774
LAMBERT: I think it looks like they're doing
sort of teapot impressions when they walk in.

1796
01:40:54.977 --> 01:40:57.343
Bella. why don't you go
and enjoy the rest of the festival?

1797
01:40:57.413 --> 01:40:58.778
The girl comes with us.

1798
01:40:59.649 --> 01:41:04.484
WEITZ: The very large. intimidating.
but extraordinarily sweet Daniel Cudmore.

1799
01:41:04.554 --> 01:41:06.488
-6'8".
-LAMBERT: He's a big man.

1800
01:41:06.556 --> 01:41:10.287
WEITZ: All Canadian. all nice guy. actually.

1801
01:41:10.693 --> 01:41:12.718
And here comes Dakota.

1802
01:41:12.795 --> 01:41:16.458
who the moment she walks onto the screen.
it's just pow.

1803
01:41:17.600 --> 01:41:19.625
You know.
the camera's fascinated with her.

1804
01:41:19.702 --> 01:41:23.900
She's absolutely brilliant.
and her crazy praying mantis eyes.

1805
01:41:25.041 --> 01:41:27.202
and there's just a nice moment
where Bella's like.

1806
01:41:27.276 --> 01:41:29.267
"Why the heck are we following this chick?"

1807
01:41:29.378 --> 01:41:34.213
And the only explanation
is Jane's power. really.

1808
01:41:34.851 --> 01:41:37.843
And this is like.
"Put some clothes on for God's sake. "

1809
01:41:37.920 --> 01:41:41.083
Now then you see the little popping
of diamond on him

1810
01:41:41.157 --> 01:41:43.182
and Ashley. explaining why.

1811
01:41:43.259 --> 01:41:48.196
because in between that shot and this shot
where they're walking down the stairs.

1812
01:41:49.165 --> 01:41:52.760
they will have popped in the sun.
the diamond effect.

1813
01:41:53.870 --> 01:41:58.170
And there's Dakota snickering at the idea
that Edward would not be afraid.

1814
01:41:59.008 --> 01:42:00.908
So now here. when they walk into the...

1815
01:42:00.977 --> 01:42:02.638
This is sort of a series of transitions

1816
01:42:02.712 --> 01:42:05.476
from sort of what you expect
of Dracula's castle

1817
01:42:05.548 --> 01:42:11.714
to something more modern. dark to light.
menacing to clinical.

1818
01:42:12.021 --> 01:42:16.685
and there's this music from Die Fladermaus.

1819
01:42:16.759 --> 01:42:20.661
which. of course. means "the bat. "
playing in the elevator.

1820
01:42:20.730 --> 01:42:25.463
And at first I thought it was a bit of a risky.
cheeky thing to do.

1821
01:42:25.535 --> 01:42:29.562
but then Stephenie Meyer said.
"I love the vampire elevator music.

1822
01:42:29.639 --> 01:42:31.630
"Can we have more of it?"

1823
01:42:32.775 --> 01:42:38.736
So. then we see the sort of strange
office-like environment and a human.

1824
01:42:39.015 --> 01:42:41.609
LAMBERT: I love the fact that it's got
computer drives in it. that office.

1825
01:42:41.684 --> 01:42:46.621
WEITZ: Oh. yeah. it's got a couple of servers
there. so the Volturi keep track of.

1826
01:42:46.689 --> 01:42:49.419
I don't know what they do.
the vampire population or something.

1827
01:42:50.059 --> 01:42:51.083
LAMBERT: There's like a vampire

1828
01:42:51.160 --> 01:42:54.027
whose special skill is databasing.
in the background.

1829
01:42:54.096 --> 01:42:55.563
WEITZ: He's the world's
best system administrator.

1830
01:42:55.631 --> 01:42:57.531
LAMBERT: He was good at databasing
as a human being.

1831
01:42:57.600 --> 01:42:58.828
As a vampire. he's amazing.

1832
01:42:58.901 --> 01:43:00.493
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1833
01:43:03.172 --> 01:43:08.371
WEITZ: And here is the set.
Gorgeous. gorgeous set

1834
01:43:08.578 --> 01:43:13.106
designed by David Brisbin.
with his architectural background.

1835
01:43:13.950 --> 01:43:17.351
and here is wonderful Michael Sheen.

1836
01:43:17.987 --> 01:43:20.251
and this shot. I just love.

1837
01:43:21.757 --> 01:43:24.783
Right here. this is a painting. you know.

1838
01:43:25.461 --> 01:43:28.453
I happen to despise smoke.

1839
01:43:29.065 --> 01:43:34.867
which cinematographers use to layer
diffusion into the background. right.

1840
01:43:34.937 --> 01:43:37.838
It puts things out of focus
in a progressive fashion.

1841
01:43:37.907 --> 01:43:43.846
But Javier used smoke here in order to kind
of give a sense of depth to the background.

1842
01:43:43.913 --> 01:43:46.108
and it gives a kind of a softness
to the background

1843
01:43:46.182 --> 01:43:47.342
while in the front it's rather crisp.

1844
01:43:47.416 --> 01:43:49.043
LAMBERT: And it doesn't feel like smoke.
I don't think.

1845
01:43:49.118 --> 01:43:50.142
WEITZ: No. it doesn't.

1846
01:43:50.219 --> 01:43:51.345
LAMBERT: I don't think
it feels like atmosphere

1847
01:43:51.420 --> 01:43:53.786
-in the way you thought it was gonna.
-WEITZ: It doesn't. Yeah.

1848
01:43:53.856 --> 01:43:55.619
So get on with it.

1849
01:43:56.926 --> 01:44:03.229
WEITZ: Now. I talked with Michael Sheen
about Aro before doing this.

1850
01:44:03.299 --> 01:44:05.426
And I said. "Well. I think. you know.

1851
01:44:06.502 --> 01:44:09.960
"after about 2. 000 years.
you'd start to go kind of crazy. "

1852
01:44:10.039 --> 01:44:13.531
And so he plays him sort of like a mad man.

1853
01:44:18.481 --> 01:44:23.475
I mean he is both intrigued by
this relationship between Edward and Bella

1854
01:44:23.552 --> 01:44:27.147
and has this kind of vicarious pleasure
in them.

1855
01:44:27.223 --> 01:44:30.556
but is. at the same time. ready to kill them
at any moment.

1856
01:44:31.160 --> 01:44:36.393
And it's kind of one of the great
mad villain portrayals

1857
01:44:36.465 --> 01:44:38.729
since Hannibal Lecter I think.

1858
01:44:38.801 --> 01:44:40.598
And at this point in the movie...

1859
01:44:40.670 --> 01:44:44.231
Jamie Campbell Bower.
Christopher Heyerdahl. brilliant.

1860
01:44:44.307 --> 01:44:45.501
LAMBERT: Not naked.

1861
01:44:45.574 --> 01:44:47.542
WEITZ: Not naked. as you can see.
Proof positive.

1862
01:44:47.610 --> 01:44:49.373
LAMBERT: "In not-naked shocker!"

1863
01:44:49.445 --> 01:44:50.673
(WEITZ LAUGHING)

1864
01:44:53.582 --> 01:44:55.607
WEITZ: So. what the heck was I saying?

1865
01:44:55.685 --> 01:44:57.619
LAMBERT: You were talking
about Michael Sheen being Hannibal.

1866
01:44:57.687 --> 01:44:59.814
WEITZ: Oh. yeah.
I just love these looks that he's giving.

1867
01:44:59.889 --> 01:45:03.586
There's so much going on in his eyes
and in his expression.

1868
01:45:06.028 --> 01:45:09.657
And. you know.
he's really quite kind of sadistic. really.

1869
01:45:10.800 --> 01:45:13.894
But to him.
he's not really doing that much harm.

1870
01:45:14.937 --> 01:45:18.771
Here's evil little Dakota Fanning
showing her true self.

1871
01:45:19.041 --> 01:45:22.602
No. Actually. she's a delightful young lady.

1872
01:45:22.678 --> 01:45:26.011
Not at all like Jane.
but I think she enjoyed playing that part.

1873
01:45:26.916 --> 01:45:28.315
LAMBERT: Rob was on a cable.
wasn't he. for this?

1874
01:45:28.384 --> 01:45:30.716
WEITZ: Yeah. Rob was on a cable.

1875
01:45:30.786 --> 01:45:33.983
which kind of kept him suspended.

1876
01:45:34.056 --> 01:45:36.923
as though his whole body
had gone so rigid

1877
01:45:36.992 --> 01:45:39.756
that he was standing
in this unnatural position

1878
01:45:39.862 --> 01:45:41.625
before he dropped to the ground.

1879
01:45:41.697 --> 01:45:45.064
And I love the way that the sound effects
here end just as she blinks.

1880
01:45:45.134 --> 01:45:48.331
Wonderful job by Scott Hecker
and his guys. again.

1881
01:45:48.404 --> 01:45:50.133
Go ahead. my dear.

1882
01:45:52.975 --> 01:45:55.034
WEITZ: And lovely just
reading Dakota's face here

1883
01:45:55.111 --> 01:46:00.048
as she realizes
that her powers are just not happening.

1884
01:46:00.916 --> 01:46:02.645
LAMBERT: Kristen's very good in this.
as well.

1885
01:46:02.718 --> 01:46:04.583
WEITZ: Yeah. like. yeah. "What the H?"

1886
01:46:04.653 --> 01:46:06.382
LAMBERT: Sort of. she's taking her on.
in a way and then...

1887
01:46:06.455 --> 01:46:08.320
WEITZ: Yeah. there's some defiance there.

1888
01:46:13.562 --> 01:46:18.431
And Michael says he was channeling
the Blue Meanies from Y ellow Submarine.

1889
01:46:18.501 --> 01:46:23.131
but I think it's rather important
that we get to the point in this movie

1890
01:46:23.205 --> 01:46:26.197
and then something really strange
and new happens.

1891
01:46:26.275 --> 01:46:30.541
but which still somehow fits
into the context of the rest of the film.

1892
01:46:31.013 --> 01:46:36.974
but. you know. kind of reboots
the entire story at this point.

1893
01:46:37.052 --> 01:46:38.519
That's true.

1894
01:46:40.756 --> 01:46:44.692
WEITZ: Now. I worked on a bit
that's coming up here.

1895
01:46:44.760 --> 01:46:46.489
Oh. no. it's later.

1896
01:46:48.130 --> 01:46:49.358
No. it's coming up later.

1897
01:46:49.432 --> 01:46:51.866
Okay. so. big fight scene. yeah.

1898
01:46:51.934 --> 01:46:53.925
We use everything that we've learned.
up to this point.

1899
01:46:54.003 --> 01:46:58.440
We use high speed. we use sound effects

1900
01:46:58.507 --> 01:47:02.307
of stones smashing together.

1901
01:47:02.878 --> 01:47:05.108
LAMBERT: We used some whip pans.
I'm gonna mention that.

1902
01:47:05.214 --> 01:47:07.444
-WEITZ: Some whip pans.
-Yeah. for Alice. I think.

1903
01:47:07.550 --> 01:47:14.353
WEITZ: CG crack on Edward's face.
vampire speed. the whole 9 yards. really.

1904
01:47:14.423 --> 01:47:17.722
Wire work
in which somebody's thrown on a wire

1905
01:47:17.793 --> 01:47:21.786
but the wire is later removed.
like there. boom.

1906
01:47:23.299 --> 01:47:26.063
The old Styrofoam table gag.

1907
01:47:26.135 --> 01:47:30.162
CG dome up there. on top of the set.

1908
01:47:32.074 --> 01:47:36.067
LAMBERT: I think the... Almost the most
exciting thing about this sequence

1909
01:47:36.145 --> 01:47:39.444
is the fact that there's no music
and just this amazing sound.

1910
01:47:39.515 --> 01:47:41.608
-WEITZ: Right.
-Which becomes kind of...

1911
01:47:41.684 --> 01:47:44.551
It's so percussive
that it almost becomes like a soundtrack.

1912
01:47:44.620 --> 01:47:45.746
WEITZ: Right.

1913
01:47:45.821 --> 01:47:47.015
LAMBERT: It's quite an unusual choice
I think.

1914
01:47:47.089 --> 01:47:50.889
in a way. in that very often you would
have big music over this kind of thing.

1915
01:47:50.960 --> 01:47:52.018
WEITZ: Right.

1916
01:47:52.094 --> 01:47:53.118
LAMBERT: And it becomes
a bit more sadistic

1917
01:47:53.195 --> 01:47:56.323
and sort of real in a way
when you don't play music underneath.

1918
01:47:56.398 --> 01:47:59.663
WEITZ: Yeah. you do get sort of
vicariously involved.

1919
01:48:02.137 --> 01:48:04.435
Now. I love this look that Michael gives
as he's coming down.

1920
01:48:04.507 --> 01:48:09.444
He's utterly confused by the willingness
of a human to give their life up.

1921
01:48:10.946 --> 01:48:13.005
and fascinated by her.

1922
01:48:14.817 --> 01:48:16.978
You would give up your life...

1923
01:48:17.052 --> 01:48:21.716
WEITZ: This bit of dialogue. we worked on.
and it means a lot to me that Bella says.

1924
01:48:21.790 --> 01:48:26.386
and this is just a big F you
to Aro and to all the Volturi.

1925
01:48:27.062 --> 01:48:28.620
"You don't know a thing about his soul. "

1926
01:48:28.697 --> 01:48:31.188
Because they'd been talking
about the soul earlier.

1927
01:48:31.467 --> 01:48:35.904
You don't know a thing about his soul.

1928
01:48:37.306 --> 01:48:40.639
WEITZ: And I think when you love someone.
that's what you believe.

1929
01:48:40.709 --> 01:48:44.440
that you know about their soul
more than anyone else does.

1930
01:48:44.513 --> 01:48:50.474
That kind of sums up the movie for me.
or her feelings for him. for me.

1931
01:48:51.053 --> 01:48:56.081
Makes you understand
why she's obsessed with him.

1932
01:48:56.158 --> 01:48:59.127
It's not just about the surface of it.

1933
01:49:02.765 --> 01:49:04.824
And here was a cheat.

1934
01:49:04.900 --> 01:49:07.528
where we went for the traditional

1935
01:49:07.603 --> 01:49:10.037
vampire-about-to-bite-someone-on-the-neck
thing.

1936
01:49:10.105 --> 01:49:16.669
rather than. as Stephenie called it.
the vampire high five attack.

1937
01:49:16.745 --> 01:49:21.273
which Laurent employs. where the vampire
holds up his hand in readiness

1938
01:49:21.350 --> 01:49:23.375
to slash someone's throat.

1939
01:49:25.854 --> 01:49:29.551
And here's the moment. interestingly.
which provokes the only moment.

1940
01:49:29.625 --> 01:49:35.086
or at least when I saw it at the premiere.
the only moment of unintentional laughter.

1941
01:49:35.164 --> 01:49:38.099
-LAMBERT: Yeah.
-And I entirely blame Rob.

1942
01:49:38.167 --> 01:49:39.828
(LAMBERT LAUGHING)

1943
01:49:39.902 --> 01:49:43.269
-LAMBERT: Why'd you blame Rob?
-'Cause I think he runs like a girl.

1944
01:49:43.339 --> 01:49:48.038
LAMBERT: Yeah. I think it's hard to run in
slow motion without looking a bit like a girl.

1945
01:49:48.110 --> 01:49:52.376
unless. as your assistant. Dave Roker. said.
you are Sylvester Stallone.

1946
01:49:52.448 --> 01:49:54.348
in which case you can pull it off.

1947
01:49:54.416 --> 01:49:56.441
WEITZ: We should have used
Sylvester Stallone for that moment.

1948
01:49:56.518 --> 01:49:58.315
LAMBERT: Yeah. you're right. Yeah.

1949
01:49:58.387 --> 01:50:00.082
WEITZ: Well. hold on. Chariots of Fire.

1950
01:50:00.155 --> 01:50:01.884
they're running in slow motion
the whole time.

1951
01:50:01.957 --> 01:50:04.084
-LAMBERT: Good point. good point. Yeah.
-Yeah. Yeah.

1952
01:50:04.860 --> 01:50:08.591
-LAMBERT: They did look a bit like girls.
-Oh. all right. good point.

1953
01:50:11.133 --> 01:50:14.569
Anyways. Yes. so Aro discovers

1954
01:50:14.637 --> 01:50:18.266
that she'll be turned into a vampire.

1955
01:50:18.340 --> 01:50:20.501
Let us be done with this.

1956
01:50:21.043 --> 01:50:24.501
-LAMBERT: This guy is great. by the way.
-He just gives so much.

1957
01:50:26.181 --> 01:50:27.409
So much.

1958
01:50:28.350 --> 01:50:30.978
LAMBERT: My hope is that his line.
"Not without cause"

1959
01:50:31.053 --> 01:50:33.317
from the earlier scene
will actually become a catch phrase

1960
01:50:33.389 --> 01:50:36.449
which people will have on T-shirts
with pictures of his face. after this movie.

1961
01:50:36.525 --> 01:50:39.016
WEITZ: Yeah.
Or like it'll become a meme on the Internet.

1962
01:50:39.094 --> 01:50:42.222
-"Not without cause. "
-LAMBERT: "Cause. "

1963
01:50:45.768 --> 01:50:48.566
WEITZ: And when we first shot it.
we just loved that line so much.

1964
01:50:48.637 --> 01:50:51.936
that we'd make up things like.
"Have you ever met a cat?"

1965
01:50:52.007 --> 01:50:54.771
"Not without paws. "

1966
01:50:56.245 --> 01:50:59.840
LAMBERT: Again. that's the kind of comedy
which takes place

1967
01:50:59.915 --> 01:51:01.075
in the New Moon cutting rooms.

1968
01:51:01.150 --> 01:51:03.243
WEITZ: That is the kind of hilarity
which goes on.

1969
01:51:03.318 --> 01:51:09.553
That was an all too brief shot of Noot Seear.
the lovely Canadian model. now actress.

1970
01:51:10.292 --> 01:51:16.094
who plays Heidi. the girl who was
sent out to fish for tourists

1971
01:51:16.165 --> 01:51:18.633
for the vampires to go and eat.

1972
01:51:19.501 --> 01:51:23.267
Now this scene. for a while.
we called the schnozberry scene.

1973
01:51:23.338 --> 01:51:27.672
because it was...
Let me see. how to explain?

1974
01:51:27.743 --> 01:51:29.802
-LAMBERT: I can explain this.
-Okay. please explain it.

1975
01:51:29.912 --> 01:51:35.009
LAMBERT: So. when your film has been shot.
it gets rushed to a laboratory

1976
01:51:35.084 --> 01:51:38.986
where they do a very quick version of it.
which you can edit on your computer

1977
01:51:39.088 --> 01:51:41.181
at a sort of not-perfect resolution

1978
01:51:41.256 --> 01:51:43.087
just so that you can get
to work on it straight away.

1979
01:51:43.158 --> 01:51:44.989
And they have to make
their own quick decisions

1980
01:51:45.060 --> 01:51:47.995
based purely on some notes
from the camera department

1981
01:51:48.063 --> 01:51:49.496
as to how to color them.

1982
01:51:49.565 --> 01:51:53.262
And this was the one occasion
where it didn't quite work perfectly.

1983
01:51:53.335 --> 01:51:57.999
And due to sort of an accident
based on the pillow being lilac colored.

1984
01:51:58.073 --> 01:52:00.769
the entire scene came out very blue.

1985
01:52:01.844 --> 01:52:03.675
WEITZ: Yeah. because the guy
who was coloring it thought

1986
01:52:03.746 --> 01:52:06.078
that that lilac pillow in back of her head
was white.

1987
01:52:06.148 --> 01:52:09.174
So he thought that everything white
was supposed to go lilac.

1988
01:52:09.251 --> 01:52:13.312
And suddenly this scene looked
like they'd all been eating schnozberries.

1989
01:52:13.388 --> 01:52:14.616
from. you know. that movie...

1990
01:52:14.690 --> 01:52:16.055
LAMBERT:
Willie Wonka's Chocolate Factory.

1991
01:52:16.125 --> 01:52:18.184
WEITZ: I think we're not supposed to say
the name of movies.

1992
01:52:18.260 --> 01:52:20.319
-And so...
-LAMBERT: It's a book. It's a book.

1993
01:52:20.395 --> 01:52:21.589
WEITZ: Okay. well. whatever.

1994
01:52:21.663 --> 01:52:25.497
Anyway. everyone looked
like they'd been eating schnozberries.

1995
01:52:26.568 --> 01:52:28.001
All right. too many blueberries.

1996
01:52:28.070 --> 01:52:30.504
LAMBERT: We called it the blueberry scene
for a long time.

1997
01:52:30.572 --> 01:52:33.541
-WEITZ: The blueberry scene.
All right. yeah. -Yeah.

1998
01:52:33.609 --> 01:52:35.907
-Anyway. it was soon rectified.
-WEITZ: Yeah.

1999
01:52:35.978 --> 01:52:40.312
And I hope that people don't think
that Edward is now hiding

2000
01:52:40.382 --> 01:52:45.081
in a cowering fashion underneath the bed
so that Charlie can't see him.

2001
01:52:45.154 --> 01:52:48.590
That's what I suddenly thought
when he opened the door there.

2002
01:52:48.924 --> 01:52:52.451
'Cause that would be a very
undignified thing for a vampire to do.

2003
01:52:52.528 --> 01:52:54.325
LAMBERT: No. I think people have got used
to the fact that

2004
01:52:54.396 --> 01:52:56.091
he can sort of jump out of windows

2005
01:52:56.165 --> 01:52:57.826
-and dart around wherever.
-WEITZ: Right. Right.

2006
01:52:57.900 --> 01:53:01.165
LAMBERT: I think he's actually on the ceiling.
If the camera just tilted up.

2007
01:53:01.236 --> 01:53:03.397
you'd find him.
just hanging there like a beetle.

2008
01:53:03.472 --> 01:53:04.939
WEITZ: Like a ninja.

2009
01:53:06.942 --> 01:53:08.102
Okay.

2010
01:53:08.243 --> 01:53:11.735
LAMBERT: Just like a bead of sweat's gonna
drop down and Charlie'll be on to him.

2011
01:53:14.116 --> 01:53:19.486
WEITZ: Now. that. I think. was from the
first film. that wolf painting. I assume.

2012
01:53:19.555 --> 01:53:21.580
But it's funny
because it's as though you see Jacob.

2013
01:53:21.657 --> 01:53:22.681
and then you see Edward.

2014
01:53:22.758 --> 01:53:26.854
Now here is where most fans of the books
will be expecting the proposal.

2015
01:53:28.297 --> 01:53:32.791
But in an act of sadism.

2016
01:53:33.402 --> 01:53:35.836
I kept Edward from proposing here.

2017
01:53:37.806 --> 01:53:41.242
LAMBERT: When you got him to kneel down.
was that on your mind?

2018
01:53:41.710 --> 01:53:44.042
Did you think. "People will think
he's definitely gonna propose now?"

2019
01:53:44.112 --> 01:53:46.546
Or was that just a happy accident.

2020
01:53:47.249 --> 01:53:49.979
-You can tell the truth.
-WEITZ: A happy accident.

2021
01:53:50.085 --> 01:53:53.282
LAMBERT: It was probably
your subconscious instinct was saying.

2022
01:53:53.355 --> 01:53:54.481
"Make him kneel down. "

2023
01:53:54.556 --> 01:53:55.648
'cause part of you knew.

2024
01:53:55.724 --> 01:53:59.091
WEITZ: Yes. it did. I think so.
I think you're right.

2025
01:53:59.161 --> 01:54:00.560
LAMBERT: The mark of a true genius.

2026
01:54:00.629 --> 01:54:03.826
WEITZ: It is. when you don't even know
what you're doing.

2027
01:54:06.134 --> 01:54:09.194
And for a bit. I didn't have a kiss here.

2028
01:54:09.271 --> 01:54:11.705
but Gillian Bohrer at the studio insisted
that they kiss.

2029
01:54:11.773 --> 01:54:14.139
Once you say something as romantic as.
"I can't live without you. "

2030
01:54:14.209 --> 01:54:15.904
-you have to kiss.
-LAMBERT: Yeah.

2031
01:54:15.978 --> 01:54:17.741
-WEITZ: Yeah.
-She was right.

2032
01:54:17.813 --> 01:54:20.714
WEITZ: She was.
Yeah. she was right. She was right.

2033
01:54:23.619 --> 01:54:27.419
Okay. so. why Edward keeps on insisting

2034
01:54:27.489 --> 01:54:31.585
that she not turn into a vampire
is a matter of much frustration to me.

2035
01:54:31.660 --> 01:54:37.621
but anyway. he's again trying to get along
without turning her into a vampire.

2036
01:54:38.533 --> 01:54:40.660
and now he's made her angry.

2037
01:54:41.570 --> 01:54:43.970
Now she's like. "All right. let's... "

2038
01:54:44.039 --> 01:54:46.599
Well. actually it's not like he wakes
them up. They're awake anyway.

2039
01:54:46.675 --> 01:54:50.372
-They're sort of hanging out. I guess.
-LAMBERT: Yeah.

2040
01:54:51.914 --> 01:54:55.680
They've been in the pool outside.
which you can see through the back door.

2041
01:54:58.487 --> 01:55:00.387
-WEITZ: That is not a pool. Peter.
That is a... -Is it not?

2042
01:55:00.455 --> 01:55:02.480
-WEITZ: A water feature.
-Oh. I'm sorry.

2043
01:55:02.557 --> 01:55:04.616
WEITZ: They don't swim for fun.

2044
01:55:05.093 --> 01:55:09.928
It's just. you know. they look at
the water and contemplate it.

2045
01:55:09.998 --> 01:55:13.263
-LAMBERT: Kind of a Zen thing.
-Yeah. it's a Zen thing. exactly.

2046
01:55:13.435 --> 01:55:16.927
It would be nice to not
want to kill you all the time.

2047
01:55:17.205 --> 01:55:19.571
WEITZ: Laughter ensues.

2048
01:55:19.641 --> 01:55:22.439
The vote is actually going pretty well
for Bella.

2049
01:55:22.511 --> 01:55:24.911
I think she already has a...

2050
01:55:25.681 --> 01:55:27.706
-No. actually no...
-LAMBERT: No. she's gotta wait for...

2051
01:55:27.783 --> 01:55:31.116
-Yeah. she's gotta wait for Esme and...
-WEITZ: But it's actually...

2052
01:55:32.421 --> 01:55:36.380
When Kellan votes.
that kind of tips it in her favor.

2053
01:55:36.458 --> 01:55:38.585
-LAMBERT: Who's Calum?
-So she's got most of the delegates.

2054
01:55:38.660 --> 01:55:40.184
-LAMBERT: Oh. Kellan.
-Kellan. yeah.

2055
01:55:40.262 --> 01:55:41.524
LAMBERT: Yeah. sorry.
thought you said Calum.

2056
01:55:41.596 --> 01:55:43.689
WEITZ: Oh. no. Emmett. Kellan.

2057
01:55:43.765 --> 01:55:47.963
-LAMBERT: Yep.
-So now she's even stevens here.

2058
01:55:48.036 --> 01:55:51.335
2 against 2 and Kellan. 3 to 2.

2059
01:55:52.174 --> 01:55:53.971
when Esme says yes.

2060
01:55:54.042 --> 01:55:59.378
then. boom. she's got a majority.

2061
01:55:59.781 --> 01:56:01.715
LAMBERT: Unless Carlisle goes against her.

2062
01:56:03.085 --> 01:56:05.212
WEITZ: Interesting. Interesting.

2063
01:56:05.620 --> 01:56:08.248
Wait. no. no. 'cause she...

2064
01:56:10.125 --> 01:56:11.524
How does this voting go?

2065
01:56:11.593 --> 01:56:14.790
There should be a big board.
like at the presidential elections.

2066
01:56:14.863 --> 01:56:15.921
LAMBERT: Yeah.

2067
01:56:15.998 --> 01:56:18.558
-WEITZ: We should have had a little...
-A little commentator. as well.

2068
01:56:18.633 --> 01:56:21.261
-taking the count.
-WEITZ: Yeah. a counter. yeah.

2069
01:56:21.336 --> 01:56:24.499
Anyway. here's a lovely song
by the Editors coming on.

2070
01:56:25.540 --> 01:56:28.634
which is fantastic.
and you should hear more of.

2071
01:56:30.545 --> 01:56:34.641
Edward is not very pleased

2072
01:56:34.950 --> 01:56:39.046
at the notion of Bella becoming a vampire.

2073
01:56:40.022 --> 01:56:41.683
And there's Jacob.

2074
01:56:41.957 --> 01:56:44.289
The unresolved issue. here.

2075
01:56:46.495 --> 01:56:49.828
LAMBERT: Beautiful shot coming up of that.

2076
01:56:50.065 --> 01:56:54.229
WEITZ: Lovely shot.
thank you Javier and Dave Crone.

2077
01:56:55.203 --> 01:56:58.695
Jacob. I know you have something
to say to me.

2078
01:57:01.043 --> 01:57:04.945
But I want to say something to you first.
if that's all right.

2079
01:57:06.114 --> 01:57:07.979
WEITZ: Well. now.

2080
01:57:10.285 --> 01:57:15.279
this whole sort of confrontation is all
about the last second of the movie to me.

2081
01:57:15.957 --> 01:57:17.982
You know. leading. sort of...

2082
01:57:19.161 --> 01:57:22.221
You know. playing on these emotions.

2083
01:57:22.297 --> 01:57:25.095
crushing Jacob's heart once more

2084
01:57:26.201 --> 01:57:30.331
before the ultimate cliffhanger.

2085
01:57:32.140 --> 01:57:34.301
Hey. my turn to talk.

2086
01:57:34.876 --> 01:57:37.003
LAMBERT: There was an unfortunate sort of

2087
01:57:37.079 --> 01:57:39.070
thing that happened
when this scene was shot

2088
01:57:39.147 --> 01:57:43.106
where. through a sort of freak accident
of angles.

2089
01:57:43.318 --> 01:57:46.344
it made it look
like Taylor was absolutely tiny

2090
01:57:46.455 --> 01:57:48.650
when he jumped off the log.

2091
01:57:48.723 --> 01:57:50.020
WEITZ: Yeah.

2092
01:57:50.092 --> 01:57:51.855
LAMBERT: And not because
he is absolutely tiny.

2093
01:57:51.927 --> 01:57:54.896
He looked like he was about 2-feet tall.

2094
01:57:54.963 --> 01:57:57.932
and it was some sort of trick
of the depth of the shot or something.

2095
01:57:57.999 --> 01:57:59.967
so he had to be CG'd up a bit.

2096
01:58:00.035 --> 01:58:04.165
(LAUGHING) I remember the first iteration
of the visual effect.

2097
01:58:04.239 --> 01:58:05.866
they made him absolutely vast.

2098
01:58:05.941 --> 01:58:07.772
-WEITZ: Oh. yeah. he looked...
-Which was kind of exciting.

2099
01:58:07.843 --> 01:58:12.837
WEITZ: He suddenly looked like a troll
from The Lord of the Rings.

2100
01:58:12.914 --> 01:58:15.348
or the Balrog or something.

2101
01:58:15.417 --> 01:58:17.442
LAMBERT: He's about perfect now.
I would say.

2102
01:58:17.519 --> 01:58:20.215
WEITZ: Yeah. I'd say
he's just about perfect. too. Yeah.

2103
01:58:23.291 --> 01:58:25.725
This is the old "I love you. but... "

2104
01:58:28.263 --> 01:58:29.855
I love you.

2105
01:58:30.599 --> 01:58:31.759
LAMBERT: But...

2106
01:58:35.337 --> 01:58:36.395
She says. "So. "

2107
01:58:36.471 --> 01:58:38.336
-That's good management tactic.
-WEITZ: Yeah. the thing you do

2108
01:58:38.406 --> 01:58:40.874
when you're disappointing someone.
is you don't say "positive thing but. "

2109
01:58:40.942 --> 01:58:44.878
you say "positive thing and or so. "
you know.

2110
01:58:44.980 --> 01:58:46.948
-So. it's not a big letdown.
-LAMBERT: Yeah. "I love you.

2111
01:58:47.015 --> 01:58:49.313
"so. I'm letting you go from your job. "

2112
01:58:49.384 --> 01:58:51.716
That would be an example in the workplace.

2113
01:58:51.786 --> 01:58:54.619
WEITZ: "We really appreciate the job
you're doing. so... "

2114
01:58:54.689 --> 01:58:57.453
LAMBERT: "So please pack up
and be out of the office within half an hour

2115
01:58:57.526 --> 01:58:59.858
"or security will escort you out. "

2116
01:59:01.496 --> 01:59:03.862
WEITZ: I'm sorry. We shouldn't be laughing.
This is a very...

2117
01:59:03.932 --> 01:59:06.162
LAMBERT: Yeah.
it's only 'cause it's so painful

2118
01:59:06.234 --> 01:59:08.259
-that I can't take it seriously.
-WEITZ: That you can't face it.

2119
01:59:08.336 --> 01:59:11.328
-This is a lovely moment from Taylor.
-LAMBERT: Otherwise. we see this every day.

2120
01:59:11.406 --> 01:59:13.738
-I'd be crying all the time.
-WEITZ: Yeah. Yeah.

2121
01:59:13.808 --> 01:59:16.402
Things are about to get a bit sticky.

2122
01:59:19.548 --> 01:59:25.248
Yeah. vampire-wolf fight on the way
unless someone stops them.

2123
01:59:27.656 --> 01:59:28.953
Stop!

2124
01:59:29.024 --> 01:59:31.822
You can't hurt each other
without hurting me.

2125
01:59:31.893 --> 01:59:33.121
WEITZ: So true.

2126
01:59:33.762 --> 01:59:37.528
LAMBERT: The Jacob theme in the music
at its most extreme.

2127
01:59:37.599 --> 01:59:38.691
WEITZ: Yeah.

2128
01:59:39.701 --> 01:59:41.692
And now a reprise of the eye shot.

2129
01:59:41.770 --> 01:59:46.036
but there is frickin' Edward
in the background.

2130
01:59:46.107 --> 01:59:48.200
Different. Different times.

2131
01:59:48.777 --> 01:59:50.972
And off he goes.

2132
01:59:51.046 --> 01:59:52.377
Jake.

2133
01:59:52.447 --> 01:59:53.744
WEITZ: Sorry. Jake.

2134
01:59:53.982 --> 01:59:58.214
Now this is a 20-second-long shot
on Bella's face.

2135
01:59:58.920 --> 02:00:02.048
and it's rare the actor
who could support that.

2136
02:00:04.759 --> 02:00:08.490
But you can sort of see what's going on
in her mind.

2137
02:00:08.563 --> 02:00:12.192
She's giving up Jake.
She's realizing what she's sacrificed.

2138
02:00:13.235 --> 02:00:17.296
and then. helpfully. we ADR'ed in
this bit of Edward again.

2139
02:00:19.407 --> 02:00:21.705
saying that he doesn't want her
to become a vampire.

2140
02:00:21.776 --> 02:00:24.836
Okay. so from this moment.
this is all about...

2141
02:00:29.451 --> 02:00:32.352
What I'm trying to do
is manipulate the audiences' emotions

2142
02:00:32.454 --> 02:00:33.546
to a fever pitch

2143
02:00:33.622 --> 02:00:37.786
as the music swells.
as we get more and more emotional.

2144
02:00:38.693 --> 02:00:43.756
and it's gonna just come
to this moment of sheer frenzy.

2145
02:00:44.065 --> 02:00:47.193
LAMBERT: I love the way Rob plays this.

2146
02:00:47.269 --> 02:00:49.635
I remember you saying.
when we first watched dailies

2147
02:00:49.704 --> 02:00:51.672
and you were suggesting
how to assemble it.

2148
02:00:51.740 --> 02:00:55.039
that you'd told him that he should be
a little flirtatious and it's almost...

2149
02:00:55.110 --> 02:00:58.705
I think you said Darcy
in Pride and Prejudice.

2150
02:00:59.281 --> 02:01:03.741
-like he's toying with her. almost.
-WEITZ: Well. he knows that he's got this...

2151
02:01:03.818 --> 02:01:05.410
LAMBERT: But he's also nervous.
He's also nervous.

2152
02:01:05.487 --> 02:01:08.217
WEITZ: Yeah. it's nice
that he's got some hesitations.

2153
02:01:08.290 --> 02:01:11.316
but he also knows that he's about
to drop a nuclear bomb.

2154
02:01:11.393 --> 02:01:13.861
...if you want me to do it myself.

2155
02:01:13.995 --> 02:01:19.023
WEITZ: He's nervous about it.
He knows she loves him.

2156
02:01:20.869 --> 02:01:23.838
He knows this is gonna
change everything. though.

2157
02:01:23.905 --> 02:01:25.805
That's what I'm asking.

2158
02:01:27.776 --> 02:01:29.744
WEITZ: And then I really wanted
the end of the movie

2159
02:01:29.811 --> 02:01:32.746
to be an intake of breath. I don't know why.

2160
02:01:34.115 --> 02:01:35.480
LAMBERT: 'Cause it's
what vampires don't do.

2161
02:01:36.051 --> 02:01:37.450
WEITZ: Very good point.

2162
02:01:37.952 --> 02:01:41.285
-LAMBERT: That's what makes her human.
-You're so right.

2163
02:01:41.356 --> 02:01:44.621
LAMBERT: Again. you didn't know that.
but your instinct did.

2164
02:01:47.662 --> 02:01:49.095
WEITZ: That has been...

2165
02:01:51.132 --> 02:01:52.394
Oh. me.

2166
02:01:53.335 --> 02:01:54.768
Let's wait until... Melissa!

2167
02:01:54.836 --> 02:01:56.064
LAMBERT: You know.
I think as a bonus. Chris...

2168
02:01:56.137 --> 02:01:57.161
(WEITZ CLAPPING SOFTLY)

2169
02:01:57.238 --> 02:01:59.638
Should we clap everyone?
I can't see this.

2170
02:01:59.708 --> 02:02:01.335
WEITZ: Stephenie.

2171
02:02:01.409 --> 02:02:04.037
There's Wyck and Karen. well done.

2172
02:02:04.112 --> 02:02:05.875
(BOTH CHEERING HALF-HEARTEDLY)

2173
02:02:05.980 --> 02:02:08.778
Marty. Greg. Mark. Guy.

2174
02:02:10.485 --> 02:02:12.783
Okay. Bill Bannerman.

2175
02:02:12.854 --> 02:02:16.688
Okay. so. Kerry. well done.

2176
02:02:16.758 --> 02:02:18.783
Obviously. I wanna thank
all of these people.

2177
02:02:18.860 --> 02:02:22.318
I wanna thank Summit Entertainment
for giving me the chance to do this.

2178
02:02:22.397 --> 02:02:26.697
I would like to thank Peter Lambert
for being such a brilliant editor

2179
02:02:26.768 --> 02:02:29.498
-and a good friend through this process.
-LAMBERT: You're welcome. Thank you.

2180
02:02:29.571 --> 02:02:34.406
WEITZ: Thank you for everyone
who's worked on the making of DVD extras.

2181
02:02:34.476 --> 02:02:35.773
Thank you. guys.

2182
02:02:35.844 --> 02:02:39.007
Alexandre. well done by you
with your music.

2183
02:02:39.080 --> 02:02:42.846
Alexandra. well done music supervising.

2184
02:02:44.619 --> 02:02:47.019
All of these people. lovely...

2185
02:02:47.088 --> 02:02:52.185
Thank you. Mercedes and Sebastian.
for coming to Vancouver with me.

2186
02:02:52.260 --> 02:02:54.421
That's my wife and child. of course.

2187
02:02:55.430 --> 02:02:58.524
Thank you to all the actors.
the extraordinary crews.

2188
02:02:58.600 --> 02:03:01.433
both in Vancouver and in Italy.

2189
02:03:03.638 --> 02:03:07.699
Thank you
to the Quileute Executive Council.

2190
02:03:09.444 --> 02:03:14.404
Gosh. the city of Vancouver.
the city of Forks. Washington.

2191
02:03:15.049 --> 02:03:18.985
the city of Montepulciano.
The city of Volterra. sorry.

2192
02:03:22.991 --> 02:03:25.323
Stephenie Meyer of course. gosh.

2193
02:03:26.795 --> 02:03:28.285
-All right.
-LAMBERT: All right. bye-bye.

2194
02:03:28.363 --> 02:03:31.355
WEITZ: Bye-bye. Thanks. Have a good dinner.
LAMBERT: Thanks.

2195
02:03:33.030 --> 02:03:38.830
Subtitles: Arigon

2196
02:04:02.030 --> 02:04:03.759
(A WHITE DEMON LOVE SONG PLAYING)

